{ White makes two deadly mistakes - he gives Black's KB an indirect attack on the White King, and he makes a target out of his h3-pawn.
By move 12, Black has enough advantage that he can sacrifice a Bishop to blow away the White kingside pawns. The attack is ferocious and White resigns on move 17 in the face of mate threats. Yet on analysis we find that White had a resource in 18.Bxf7+. Black would probably still win after that, but this defense is fasinating.

The beginner will have more questions about this game than Chernev could possible answer. Chernev was trying to get the beginner's feet wet by giving him some generally sound principles and advice. Rules-of-thumb (ROT). But as Chernev says after Black's second move ... "I would caution you that this and other maxims are not to be blindly followed. In chess, as in life, rules must often be swept aside."

References:
[GPE] "Chess Openings: Ideas & Analysis: Giuoco Piano", by Larry Evans, 1973, page 23
Wikipedia on Theodor von Scheve
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodor_von_Scheve
Wikipedia on RichardTeichmann
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Teichmann
Fritz-12 and the Power Book 2000 from Chessbase.
This is commercial software I've had for years.
- }
1. e4 { Rule Of Thumb(ROT): 1.e4 or 1.d4 } 1... e5 { The current favorite of modern masters is c5 (the Sicilian Defense). However e5 is the runner-up. e5 maintains a balanced position, while c5 unbalances immediately. } 2. Nf3 { ROT: Knights before Bishops. ROT: Develop with a threat. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e5] } 2... Nc6 { The logical defense of the King pawn and the overwhelming choice of masters. } { [%cal Rf3e5,Gc6e5] } 3. Bc4 { This went out of favor with the masters at the turn of the 20th century. However Fritz Power Book 2000(FPB-2000) still has it being played 10% of the time with almost as good results as the current preference of Bb5. At c4 the Bishop as a direct influence on the center and attacks f7. } { [%cal Gc4d5,Gc4f7] } 3... Bc5 { The Giuoco Piano (Italian Game). Black continues to balance the position. Slightly more popular today (2000) is Nf6; the Two Knights Defense. Now in 2020 the Lichess OB has Bc5 just slightly more popular. } (3... Nf6 { -
Chernev: This pawn [f7] is guarded by one piece only - the King. It is not unusual even early in the game to sacrifice a piece for this pawn, so that the King in capturing it is uprooted, driven into the open and exposed to a violent attack.
jomega: As an example let's look at the Two Knights Defense.
- } 4. Ng5 { Tarrasch called *this* move a coffee-house move. A duffer's mistake. Yet it has never been refuted! } { [%cal Rc4f7,Rg5f7] } 4... d5 { White has threatening f7 with two pieces. } 5. exd5 Nxd5?! { This is just asking for trouble. The King Knight was guarding the f7 pawn by blocking frontal attacks on it. Better is ...Na5.
Now comes that sacrifice of the type Chernev was talking about. } 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ { Oh, my! The pinned d5-Knight is now attacked twice and defended only by the Black Queen. Unless Black wants to lose the Knight he is practically forced into playing Ke6. White would then get further attackers on the Knight by Nc3. The variation is called the Fried Liver Attack; because Black's King is liver being "fried" in the center of a fire. See Wikipedia for an explanation. } { [%cal Rf3d5,Rc4d5,Gd8d5] } 7... Kg8?? { A serious error a beginner is likely to make (and have against me). } 8. Qxd5+ Qxd5 9. Bxd5+ Be6 10. Bxe6# { The Black King was not safe on g8 after all. }) 4. c3 { One idea of this move is to support moving the Queen Pawn to d4. Another is to simply control b4 and d4 if White decides to play the quiet d3 instead of d4. The big drawback is that the Queen Knight cannot go to c3. } { [%cal Rd2d4,Yb1c3] } 4... Qe7 { Black intends to hold the center against White's d4. Notice that this move puts the Black Queen and King on the same file and so Black must be careful that the Queen does not get pinned. } (4... Nf6 { The favorite of modern masters in this position. Picking the favorites for the next few moves we get... } 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a6 7. Bb3 Ba7 8. Nbd2 { Because the d-pawn is not at d4, the Queen Knight can develop here at d2. If the d-pawn was at d4, then this Knight move would block the necessary defense of the pawn by the Queen. } 8... O-O 9. Nc4) 5. O-O { Playing this move now avoids the pawn sacrifice that could come with an immediate d4. ROT: Castle early in the game. Drawback - you've just told your opponent where he can attack your King! Black has not castled yet. He might castle queenside and pawn-storm on the kingside. } (5. d4 { -
Questions for beginners.
1. How do you know that if exchanges start occurring on d4 that you will not lose material? (Attack/Defense network, exchange-rules-of-thumb. A/D and EROT)
2. Do you see Knight moves as a L-shape or all the moves at once?
- } 5... Bb6 (5... exd4 { This would be inconsistent if Black's plan was to hold the center. } 6. O-O! { The Pawn on e4 is safe and if Black plays dxc3 then White recaptures with the Knight and gets good play for the sacrificed Pawn.
Not 6.cxd4 as in LCMBM. } 6... dxc3 (6... Qxe4?? 7. Re1 { Winning the Queen for a Rook. } { [%cal Ge1e8] } 7... Qxe1+ 8. Qxe1+ $18) 7. Nxc3 $16) 6. O-O d6 { As in the game. }) 5... d6 { Black continues his plan to hold the center. } 6. d4 { The original intent of c3 was to play d4. However FPB-2000 has Black winning 45% of the time! d3 is a less aggressive alternative. } 6... Bb6 { Black would not want to play exd4 because White would get the better center. } (6... exd4 { This is not consistent and gives up the center. } 7. cxd4 Bb6 8. Nc3 $16 { All of White's problems have been solved. }) 7. a4 { White does not want to play d5 because that would relieve the tension in the center and open up the diagonal for Black's Bishop. White has to keep a triple guard on d4, so he cannot play Nbd2. Chernev says that Scheve was trying to play against the Black Bishop. Scheve's 8.a5 seems to be good evidence for that opinion.
But the real point of this move in theory is that White, with the threat of 8.d5 winning a piece, gains some queenside space. Also White would like to eventually play Na3/Nc2 so that the Knight can protect d4. } { [%cal Rd4d5,Rd5c6,Ra4a5,Ra5b6,Rb2b4] } (7. h3 { This move is the favorite of masters in this position. Here is an example of knowing when to break a rule of thumb by disturbing the pawns in front of the castled King. A possible continuation follows.
But why is this move ok here, but Chernev calls 8.h3 a coffee-house move? Because of White's follow-up later. Here, White is still blocking the b6-Bishop's attack on f7. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Rb6g1,Gc8h3] } 7... Nf6 8. Re1 O-O 9. Na3 Nd8 10. Nc2 $14) 7... a6 { Makes a retreat square for the Bishop. } 8. a5? { Chernev says White's attack is premature and should not succeed. He is correct, but his analysis is wrong. Black can play Nxa5 without losing a piece. } (8. h3 Nf6 9. Re1 h6 10. Na3 O-O 11. Nc2 { If White wants to hold the center tension as is. }) 8... Ba7 { Teichmann preferred to keep his Bishop hitting at the center. } { [%cal Ra7g1,Gh2h3] } (8... Nxa5! { This works. The line in Chernev's book is not best. } 9. Rxa5? (9. Bd3 Nc6 10. d5 Nb8 11. Na3 Nf6 12. Nc4 Ba7 13. Bc2 h6 14. h3) 9... Bxa5 10. Qa4+? { [%cal Ga4e8,Ga4a5] } 10... b5! 11. Qxa5 (11. Bxf7+ Qxf7 12. Qxa5 $17) 11... bxc4 $17 { Gunsberg-Alekhine, St. Petersburg 1914. Black has a plus. [GPE] }) 9. h3 { White has other possibilities: 9.Bg5, 9.Qd3, 9.Rfe1. The move played is to stop the pin Bg4. } (9. d5 Nxa5 10. Rxa5) 9... Nf6 { Continued development with attack on the e4-pawn. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } (9... exd4? 10. cxd4 { White has good control of the center. } 10... Qxe4?? 11. Re1 $18 { The Black Queen is lost. } { [%cal Ge1e8] }) 10. dxe5? { This has to be bad. It is inconsistent, opens lines for the opponent, who is better developed, and accentuates the weakness of h3. } { [%cal Rc8h3,Ra7g1,Rf6e4,Ge1e4] } (10. Re1 { Straight forward defense of the King pawn. }) (10. Bg5 { Indirect defense of the King pawn by pinning the attacker. }) 10... Nxe5 { Black has the initiative. The immediate threats are Nxc4 or Nxe4. } { [%cal Re5c4,Rf6e4] } (10... dxe5 11. Nbd2 O-O) (10... Nxe4 11. exd6 Qxd6 $14) 11. Nxe5 { White is practically forced into this exchange. The following almost all lose a pawn. } (11. Na3 Nxe4 $17) (11. Bb3 Nxe4 $17) (11. Bd5 c6 12. Bb3 Nxe4 $17) (11. Re1 { -Stockfish. Stockfish finds a way out. } 11... Nxc4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd1a4,Ga4e8,Ga4c4] } 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qxc4 $15) 11... Qxe5 { The recapture with the Queen brings another piece to the attack that is coming. Black is threatening Bxh3. } { [%cal Ra7g1,Re5g3,Rf6g4,Rc8h3] } 12. Nd2? { Not fast enough. White is in trouble on the kingside. } (12. Qe2 { If White tries to activate his Queen along the King file trying for 13. Be3 to contest the Black Bishop on a7 to relieve the pin, Black can continue with the Bishop sacrifice. } 12... Bxh3 13. gxh3 Qg3+ { Notice that the f-pawn is pinned. } 14. Kh1 Qxh3+ 15. Kg1 Ng4 { Threatening Qh2#. } 16. Bf4 g5 { The Bishop cannot take this pawn because the Bishop is guarding against the mate at h2. } 17. Qd3 Qxd3 18. Bxd3 gxf4 $19 { Black is two pawns up and has a passed pawn. White's King
is not very safe either. }) (12. Qd3 { The best defense I've found so far in this position. } 12... Nxe4 { Winning a pawn. } 13. Be3 { Getting rid of the pin. } 13... Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Nc5 $15) 12... Bxh3! { Stripping away the White King's pawn cover. } 13. gxh3? { White should not accept this sacrifice. } (13. Bxf7+?! { White has this resource throughout. } 13... Ke7! (13... Kxf7 14. Nf3 Qb5 15. Ng5+ { Forking the King and Bishop. } 15... Kg8 16. Nxh3 Nxe4 $17) 14. Kh1 (14. Nf3? { No longer works. } 14... Qg3! { Threatening Qxg2#. } 15. Nh4 Qxh4 $19) 14... Bg4 15. Qb3 Rhf8 $19 { Black has won back his piece and still has pressure on the kingside. }) (13. Qf3 Bg4 14. Qd3 O-O $17) 13... Qg3+! { This is possible because of White's 10'th move that opened the diagonal for the Black Bishop. } { [%cal Ra7g1] } 14. Kh1 { Forced. } 14... Qxh3+ { This picks up another pawn and more importantly clears the way for Ng4. } (14... Bxf2? 15. Qf3 $18 { And White can now defend easily. }) 15. Kg1 { Forced. } 15... Ng4 { Threatens mate with the Queen on h2. } { [%cal Rh3h2,Rg4h2] } 16. Nf3 { Stops the mate. } (16. Bxf7+ { Another defensive try for White. } 16... Kd7 (16... Kxf7? 17. Qf3+ Qxf3 18. Nxf3 $19 { Black is winning, but his kingside attack is over. }) 17. Nf3 Qg3+ 18. Kh1 Bxf2 { Black is threatening a mate in two starting with Qh3+. } 19. Be6+! Kxe6 20. Qd5+ Ke7 21. Bg5+ Kd7 22. Qf5+ Kc6 (22... Ke8?? 23. Qe6+ Kf8 24. Be7+ Ke8 25. Bxd6+ Kd8 26. Qe7+ Kc8 27. Qxc7#) 23. Qd5+ Kd7 24. Qf5+ Kc6 25. Qd5+ Kd7 { Draw by repetition. }) 16... Qg3+ { Preparing to remove the last of the pawns shielding the King and set up a mate in two moves. } { [%cal Ra7g1] } 17. Kh1 { Forced. } 17... Bxf2 { -
Threatening Qh3+ and then Qxh2#. White resigned. It is clear why a master would resign instead of playing on at move 18. However nonmasters should not resign this position. I know; it looks like White is about to be mated. Chernev thought so. He mentions only 18.Rxf2 and claims there is no escape. However as IM Jeremy Silman says in his book "The Complete Book of Chess Strategy" (pg 144).... "You will find that a lion's heart and a fighting spirit can overcome tremendous difficulties on the chessboard. Never give up, hang on like grim death, and force your opponent to play like a genius if he's going to drag you down." So how does White come up with a defense in this "hopeless" position? Well Black has been busy with his attack and has not castled. Can we take advantage of the exposed Black King?
The following analysis is for advanced players, or those just interested. It is quite complex.
- } { [%cal Rg3h3,Rh3h2] } 18. Bxf7+! { This is not just a spite check. } (18. Bf4? Qxf4 19. Bxf7+ Qxf7 $19) (18. Ke7 Bg5+ 19. Kf8 Bf4 { White has found a way to protect against the mate. } 20. Qxf4 Bh5 21. Nf6 Rxf2 22. Nxh5 Qd5 23. Ng3+ Kg1 24. c6 Qg5 25. Qxg5 Nxg5+ 26. Kg8 $17 { And White, down two pawns, has survived the attack. }) (18. Kxf7? { This exposes Black's King. White can penetrate with the Queen and in some variations the Queen's Bishop. } 18... Qd5+ 19. Kf8 (19. Kg6?? Qf5#) (19. Ke7? Bg5+ 20. Kd7! Qf5+ 21. Kc6 Qd5+ { With a draw by three-time repetition coming. }) 19... Qf5+ 20. Kg8 Qe6+ 21. Kf8 Qf5+ { If Black continues to move to g8 then White can draw by repetition. } 22. Ke8 (22. Ke7? Bg5+ 23. Nf6 (23. Ke8?? Qe6+ 24. Kf8 Be7+ 25. Ke8 Bxd6+ 26. Kd8 Qe7+ 27. Kc8 Qxc7#) 23... e5 24. Raf8 (24. dxe5 Nxe5 25. Rad8 Rxf2 $18) 24... Ra4 $18) 22... Qe6+ 23. Kd8?? { If Black goes to f8 then White is getting his draw. } 23... Bg5+ 24. Nf6 Rxf2 { White is winning! } 25. Re8 (25. Qxf2?? Ne5! 26. Qf3+ { Forced! } (26. dxe5 Rd1+ 27. Qd4 cxd4 28. c6 dxe5+ 29. Kc7 exf6 30. Kb8 Qe5+ 31. Ka7 Be3+ 32. c5 Bxc5+ 33. b6 Rd7#) 26... Nxf3 $18) 25... Bxf6+ 26. gxf6 Qxf6+ 27. Re7 Rg1 28. Qxf2 Rg8+ 29. Kd7 Qf5+ 30. Kc6 Rg1 31. Qxf3+ { Black had to stop Nd4+. } 31... Qxf3 $18) (18. Rxf2?? Nxf2#) 0-1


