{ I annotated this game decades ago. Here are those annotations plus some new ones.

White makes a grave positional mistake with 7.d5. The problems:
- the move gives Black's Bishop the g1-a7 diagonal. The pin that will come on the f2 pawn becomes an issue,
- the move locks the center in a situation where White plans to castle kingside and Black does not. Hence, there will be a Black kingside attack and no counter-play for White in the center,
- the move puts another center pawn on White and so makes White's KB "bad".

After castling, White plays h3 to prevent a Bishop pin, but that makes a target out of the h3-pawn. Black attacks the h3-pawn with a pawn storm. There is no way for White to avoid having a file open on the kingside. White grab of a pawn with 13.Bxh6 is a beginner blunder - it just opens another file for Black to use in the attack. Black's kingside attack wins.

Wikipedia on Soultanbeieff
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Soultanbeieff
Edward Winter has a picture and a short note about
Liubarski
https://www.chesshistory.com/winter/winter36.html
- }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 { The Giuoco Piano. White's 4.c3 prepares for d4. } { [%cal Rd2d4,Yb1c3] } 4... Bb6 5. d4 Qe7 { -
Black's idea is to protect his King pawn and maintain a blockade in the center.
Chernev's comment that Black is "threatening" to win a pawn with 6... exd4 is questionable! You cannot claim a threat based on the opponent not playing his best moves! I know annotators do this, but it is misleading.
White could play 7.cxd4 Qxe4+ 8.Be3 and now White is "threatening" to win Black's Queen! You can see the problem with this use of the word "threatening".
9.Bxf7+ Kxf7?? 10.Ng5+ and wins the Queen.
- } 6. O-O (6. a3 { Played to see the "threat". Unfortunately you cannot enter a null-move in Lichess. } 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Qxe4+ 8. Be3 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc4f7,Gf3g5,Gg5f7,Gg5e4] } 8... Nf6? 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7?? 10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Nxe4 $18) 6... Nf6 { -
It is better for White to maintain the tension in the center. Releasing that tension would not only give Black's Bishop a fine diagonal, but also stifle White's counter-play in the center later. Beginners tend to want to "resolve" the clash of the attacks - here on d4. This may be because they have not yet learned to do static tactical analysis. Instead they do sequential analysis of the captures on d4, and that gets tiring.
- } 7. d5? { White would do better not to open the diagonal for Black's King Bishop. Black's Knight is only temporarily put at a disadvantage. Pawn moves are permanent!
PixelatedParcel: So, White having castled, Black can now castle queenside and launch a pawn-storm and kingside attack. } (7. Re1 { The master's choice in the OB. Because the d4-pawn blocks the Black Bishop, this move works. Playing the OB moves we find... } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6e4,Ge1e4] } 7... d6 8. h3 { How interesting. The move that is bad in the game is the master's choice here. Again it is ok because the Black Bishop is blocked. } { [%cal Gb6g1] } 8... h6 9. a4 a6 10. Be3 { White maintains the center tension. } 10... Ba7 { If Black does not want to 0-0, then this is the next OB move. } 11. Nbd2 O-O { Black cannot put off castling forever. Because the center might still become open, Black gets his King to safety. }) 7... Nb8 8. Bd3 { White should either protect the King pawn with Nbd2 or Qe2, or play d6. Note how the White King Bishop is blocked by White's pawns.
Stockfish likes 8.Bd3. The OB has 8.Qc2. } (8. d6 { This might be played to give the QB some scope. } 8... Qxd6 { Black is threatening 10... Bxf2+ 11.Kxf2 Qc5+ winning a pawn, and 10...Qxd1 11.Rxd1 Nxe4 winning a pawn. } 9. Qxd6 cxd6 { I'd rather be playing Black. }) (8. Qc2 { Defending the e4-pawn. } 8... O-O 9. a4 { A recurring theme - attacking the Black Bishop. }) (8. Re1?! { This allows a small tactic if Black wants. } { [%cal Gb6g1] } 8... Bxf2+ 9. Kxf2 Qc5+ { Winning back the Bishop. } { [%cal Gc5c4] } 10. Kg3 Qxc4 11. Nxe5 Qa6 { Maybe Black should not play that tactic. :-) }) 8... d6 9. h3 { Weakens g3 (note the f-pawn is pinned). } 9... h6! { Beginning a plan to open White's Kingside by using Black's kingside Pawns. Note that Black's King is fairly safe in the center because the center is closed.
It is interesting that Stockfish wants to play either ...0-0 or ...c6, and ...h6 is 3rd choice. } { [%csl Gh6] } 10. Qe2 { [Stockfish would rather go after the b6-Bishop with Nfd2, Nc4 or a4/a5.] } 10... g5 11. Nh2 { Hoping to stop 11... g4. } 11... g4! { It is easily worth a pawn to break up White's kingside. } 12. hxg4 (12. h4 { If White pushes thinking to stop Black from opening a file, it will not work. } 12... g3 { [%cal Gb6g1] } 13. Nf3?! gxf2+ 14. Kh1 Nh5 { [%cal Rh5g3,Rg3h1,Rg3e2] } 15. Kh2 Rg8 16. Be3 $19) 12... Rg8 13. Bxh6?? { White is in big trouble and has no time for this pawn grab. Also, this opens the h-file for Black's Rook!
Stockfish says -8.1 } (13. Be3 { [%cal Gb6g1] } 13... Bxg4 { [%cal Gf6g4,Gg8g4] } 14. Nf3 Nh5 $15) (13. Nd2 { Stockfish. } 13... Nxg4 14. Nhf3 Nf6 15. Nc4 { [If it was not for this, White would be in serious trouble.] } 15... Nh5 16. Nxb6 axb6 { White still has to defend the kingside attack. }) 13... Nxg4 14. Be3 Nxh2 15. Kxh2? { Taking the Bishop would give better chances, though White has a lost position. } (15. Bxb6 axb6 16. Re1 (16. Kxh2? Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Rxg2+! 18. Kxg2 Bh3+ 19. Kh2 (19. Kg1 Qg5+ 20. Qg4 Qxg4+ 21. Kh2 Qg2#) 19... Bxf1+ 20. Kg1 Bxe2 $19) 16... Bg4 17. Qe3 Nf3+ 18. Kf1 (18. Kh1?? Qh4#) (18. gxf3 Bh3+ 19. Kh1 Qh4 20. f4 Bd7+ 21. Qh3 Qxh3#) 18... Nxe1 19. Kxe1 Nd7 $19) 15... Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qh3 { White resigned. White can only throw pieces in the way and give spite checks. } (16... Rh8 { This still wins, but misses the faster win. This inversion of move ordering is a common problem noted in several books on tactics. } 17. f3 { This recourse works better here, but fails entirely off the mainline. } 17... Nd7 (17... Bxe3+?! 18. Qxe3) 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Qe1 Qh2+ 20. Kf2 Nc5 21. Bc2 Bh3 22. Rg1 O-O-O $19) (16... Bh3 { Another winning move, just not as fast as the text. } 17. g3 Bxf1 18. Qxf1 Bxe3 19. Kg2 Bf4 $19) 17. g3 (17. f3?? { This fails here. } { [%csl Gc8,Gb8,Ga8] } 17... Bxe3+ 18. Rf2 Qxg2#) 17... Rh8 { It is mate in 4 per Stockfish. } { [%csl Gh2,Gh8,Gh3][%cal Gh3h2] } 18. Bb5+ (18. Qh5 Rxh5 19. Bb5+ Kf8 20. Bh6+ Rxh6 21. Nd2 Qh1#) (18. Bh6 Qxg3+ 19. Kh1 Rxh6+ 20. Qh5 Rxh5#) (18. Nd2 Qh1#) (18. Rd1 Qh1#) (18. f3 { [%cal Ge2h2] } 18... Bxe3+ 19. Rf2 (19. Qxe3 Qxg3# (19... Qh2#)) 19... Qh1#) 18... Kf8 19. Bh6+ Rxh6 20. Qh5 Qxg3+ { [%cal Gb6g1] } (20... Rxh5 21. Re1 Qh1#) 21. Kh1 Rxh5# 0-1


