{ -
The Colle System is played by White in this game. The system is named after Edgard Colle, who plays White here.

Black releases the center tension twice in the opening, both times to his disadvantage. Black fails to find the best defense to White's kingside attack.

Wikipedia on Edgard Colle:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgard_Colle
- }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. c3 { -
The Colle System.
Opening systems are concerned more with the placement of the men than the sequence of moves. They also have associated plans.
For the Colle System see:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colle_System
- } 5... Nc6 { -
The main plan of the Colle System is to attack kingside. White aims to play a timely e4 and either exchange or drive off the Black King Knight. White plays c3 so as to allow recapture with the c-pawn if Black takes on d4, and to allow the King Bishop to retreat to c2 if necessary.
- } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rc5d4,Gc3d4,Ge3d4,Gf3d4] } 6. Nbd2 { The QN and e3 pawn only temporarily block the QB. The QN aids in the e4 push. } 6... Be7 { The move 6...Bd6 is more aggressive looking, but Black must be careful to not fall into a pawn fork on e5. } (6... Bd6 { [%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5] }) 7. O-O { Best to get the King into safety and this allows the Rook to move to e1 if desired. That Rook move would also help with the e4 plan and a possible Rook lift in a kingside attack. } 7... c4? { -
As we discussed in the last game (Liubarski - Soultanbeieff), locking the center when a kingside attack is coming is a "bad idea" for the defending player. The defender needs counter-play. That counter-play is best in the center. Instead, Black releases the center tension.
Black's idea may have been to gain space on the queenside, but his queenside counter-play is too slow.
Better is ...0-0
- } 8. Bc2 b5 9. e4 { The characteristic pawn break in the Colle. } 9... dxe4? { Black again releases the center tension, but the move is to White's advantage. Better was ...a5. Perhaps Black was worried about a later e5 move. } 10. Nxe4 { White captures with the Knight. He wants to rid Black of his KN which is protecting h7. White preserves his Bishop which already attacks h7. } 10... O-O (10... Nd5 { A much better move for Black. }) (10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4 { [%cal Ge4c6] } 11... Bb7 12. Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c6,Ge4c6] } 12... Qb6 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. d5 Nd8 15. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6] } 15... Qc7 16. Qf3+ Kg8) 11. Qe2 { White is threatening to win a piece; the c6-Knight which is loose. } { [%cal Ge4f6,Ge2e4,Ge4h7,Ge4c6] } 11... Bb7 { While this guards the c6-Knight, notice that the Bishop is not guarded. } 12. Nfg5 { With the added attacker on h7, White is threatening to win with 13.Nxf6+. } 12... h6? { Much better is 12...Nxe4. See the next variation. } (12... Nxe4 13. Qxe4 { [%cal Ge4h7] } 13... g6 14. Qh4 { [%cal Gh4h7] } 14... Bxg5 15. Bxg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] } 15... f6 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Rfe1 $16) 13. Nxf6+ { [%cal Gf6g8] } 13... Bxf6 { Trying to maintain his kingside pawn structure. } { [%csl Gc2,Gg5][%cal Gc2h7,Ge2e4] } (13... gxf6 14. Ne4) 14. Qe4 { Threatening mate in one. } { [%cal Gc2h7] } 14... g6? (14... Re8 15. Qh7+ Kf8 16. Ne4 $18) 15. Nxe6! { Knocking out the support for the g6-pawn with a sacrifice. } (15. Nxf7 Rxf7 16. Qxe6 (16. Qxg6+ Rg7 17. Qe4 Nxd4 { [%cal Gb7e4] } 18. Qxb7 Ne2+ 19. Kh1 Rxb7)) 15... fxe6?? { Black should not accept this sacrifice. } (15... Nxd4 { Black does not have to accept the sacrifice. One defensive technique is to complicate the position. If White is running short of time, he may find it difficult to calculate the best move. } 16. Qxb7 (16. Nxd8 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Ne2+ 18. Kh1 Raxd8 19. Bxh6 Rfe8 20. Bc6 Re7 21. Bxb5 Rb7 22. a4 a6 23. Bxc4 Rxb2 $16) 16... Nxe6 $16) 16. Qxg6+ Bg7 (16... Kh8 17. Qh7#) 17. Qh7+ { Reti in Masters of the Chessboard says that with a Queen-Bishop battery you usually lead with the Queen, whereas with a Queen-Rook battery you usually lead with the Rook. } { [%cal Gc2h7] } 17... Kf7 18. Bg6+ { [%cal Gf7e7,Gh7g7,Gg7b7] } 18... Kf6 { [%cal Gf6g7] } 19. Bh5 { White is threatening 20.Qg6+ winning both Bishops. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gh7g6,Gg6g7,Gg7b7,Gd4e5,Gc1g5,Gg6f5] } 19... Ne7? { [%cal Rc1h6,Rh7h6,Gg7h6] } (19... Qd5 { Better than the text, but still losing. } { [%cal Gd5h5] } 20. Qg6+ Ke7 21. Qxg7+ Kd6 22. Qxb7 Qxh5 { [%csl Gg1] } 23. Bf4+!! { An impossible looking move! } { [%cal Gf8a8] } 23... Rxf4 (23... e5 24. dxe5+ Ke6 (24... Kc5 25. Be3+ Kd5 26. Rad1+ $18 { Black gets mated in 7 moves, per Stockfish. }) 25. Qxc6+ Kf7 26. Rad1 Kg8 27. Bxh6 $18 { White wins. }) 24. Qxa8 $18 { White is the exchange and two pawns up. Black's pawns are worse than White's. Black's King is exposed. }) 20. Bxh6 { [%cal Rh6g7,Rh7g7,Gf6g7] } 20... Rg8 { [%cal Rh6g7,Rh7g7,Gf6g7,Gg8g7] } (20... Bxh6 21. Qxh6+ Ng6 (21... Kf5 22. g4+ Ke4 23. Qxe6+ Kd3 24. Qe3+ Kc2 25. Qe2#) 22. Qxg6+ Ke7 23. Qg7+ { [%cal Gg7b7] } 23... Kd6 24. Qxb7 $18) 21. h4! { Support for the Bishop to move to g5. } { [%cal Gh4g5,Gd4e5,Gh6g5] } 21... Bxh6?? { Allowing mate in one. Black was lost anyway. } { [%cal Gh5f7] } (21... Qd5 22. Bg5+ Qxg5 23. hxg5+ Kxg5 24. f4+ Kf6 25. Rae1 $18) (21... e5 22. Bxg7+ Rxg7 23. dxe5+ Ke6 24. Qxg7 $18) 22. Qf7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { [%cal Gh4g5,Gd4e5,Gf7f6,Gh5f7] } 1-0


