{ -
Black makes the mistake of accepting the King's Gambit pawn at a point when White can get it back immediately while at the same time White obtains the classical pawn phalanx d4/e4. Black On move 7, Black exchanges his Bishop for White's Queen Knight. While this gives White doubled-pawns, Black cannot take advantage of that in the middle game. Black then plays several weak moves and then a blunder - castling into an attack. White sacrifices a Bishop for two of the pawns in front of Black's castled King. There was no defense to White's kingside attack at that point.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Henry_Blackburne
- }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 { King's Gambit } 2... Bc5 { King's Gambit Declined
Black declines the gambit. His idea is to inhibit White's castling and to maintain his pawn on e5. However Black in this game makes the mistake of capturing White's f-pawn later. } 3. Nc3 { White usually plays Nf3 here. This attacks the pawn on e5 and keeps the Black Queen out of h4. Black could now try 3...Bxg1 4.Rxg1 Qh4+ 5.g3 Qxh2 and White's kingside is a mess. (But Chernev says White gets a fine game!) Probably better for Black is 3...d6. } 3... Nc6 (3... Bxg1 4. Rxg1 Qh4+? 5. g3 Qxh2 6. Rg2 Qh3 7. Nd5 $16) (3... d6 4. Nf3 Nf6) 4. Nf3 (4. fxe5 d6 5. exd6 Qxd6 { For a pawn, Black will develop easily and have good piece play. }) 4... exf4? { Giving up the center and letting White get the pawn back. } (4... d6 { Much better. }) 5. d4 Bb4 6. Bxf4 { [%csl Ge4,Gd4] } 6... d5 7. e5 { This makes it difficult for Black to finish developing his kingside. } 7... Bxc3+? { Black's idea is to give White a doubled pawn, but Black cannot take advantage of it and so it would have been better to not exchange. } (7... Nge7 { Much better. }) 8. bxc3 { This Bishop acts like a big pawn here. Better was Bf5 or Nge7. } 8... Be6? (8... Bf5) 9. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3h7] } 9... h6 { Too defensive and weakens the kingside. Nge7 was better. } 10. O-O { [%cal Gf1f7,Ge6f7] } 10... Nge7 11. Rb1 { Taking the half-open file. } { [%csl Gb7] } 11... b6 { This weakens the Knight on c6 and creates holes at a6 and c6. Better would have been Qc8. } 12. Qd2 { Anticipating Black's next move. } 12... O-O?? { Castling into an attack. } { [%cal Rd2h6,Rd3h7,Rf3g5,Rg5h7] } (12... Qd7) 13. Bxh6! gxh6? { Black should accept the loss of a pawn. Letting the White Queen in is a big mistake. } (13... Bf5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qg5+ Bg6 16. Nh4 Ng8 17. Nf5+ Kh8 18. Qg3 $18) 14. Qxh6 { [%cal Gh6h7,Gd3h7] } 14... Ng6? { Not the best defense, but Black is lost. } { [%cal Gd3g6] } (14... Nf5 15. Bxf5 Bxf5 16. Nh4 { Much stronger than Chernev's Qxc6. This threatens Nxf5 with mate threatened at g7. } 16... Bxc2 (16... Qxh4 { Stockfish wants to give away some pieces. } 17. Qxh4 Be4 18. Rf4 Rae8 19. Rg4+ Bg6 20. Rf1 $18 { The coming Rook lift of the Queen Rook to h3 is a killer. }) 17. Nf5 { [%cal Gh6g7] } 17... Bxf5 18. Rxf5 $18) (14... f5 15. exf6 { [%cal Gh6g7] } 15... Rf7 16. Ng5 Qf8 17. Qh5 Nd8 18. Bh7+ Kh8 19. Bg6+ Kg8 20. fxe7 Qxe7 21. Bxf7+ Nxf7 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Qh8# { [%cal Gf1f8,Gf7h8] }) 15. Ng5 Re8 { Allowing a mate in 3. } 16. Rxf7 { [%cal Gh6g7] } (16. Qh7+ Kf8 17. Rxf7+ (17. Nxe6+ { [%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1f8] } 17... Ke7 (17... Rxe6 18. Qxf7#) 18. Qxf7#) 17... Bxf7 18. Qxf7#) 16... Bxf7 { [%cal Rg5f7,Rh6h7,Rh7f7] } 17. Qh7+ Kf8 18. Qxf7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } 1-0


