{ -
In a Giuoco Piano opening, Black allows White to get the classical pawn phalanx d4/e4. Instead of breaking up the White center when he had a chance to do so, Black castled. White center pawns advance and Black's pieces get displaced. By move 12 White's pawns are both on Black's side of the board cramping Black's pieces. All Black's pieces except one Bishop are on the first or second rank! Black cannot defend against White's kingside attack.
- }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 { The Giuoco Piano. } 4... Nf6 { Black's idea with this move should be to grab the King pawn and consolidate quickly, but in this game Black doesn't take the pawn! } 5. d4 exd4 (5... Bb6? 6. dxe5 Nxe4? 7. Qd5 $18 { Chernev also mentioned this move. } (7. Bxf7+?! { -Chernev } 7... Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Kf8 9. Qxe4 d5 $16) 7... Bxf2+ 8. Ke2 Qe7 9. Qxe4 Bb6 $18) (5... Bb4?? { This is in the Lichess Master's Opening Book. White did not capture the Bishop, and Black went on to win?? The more probably answer is that the move is recorded incorrectly! } { Battulga, Namhai - Filippov, Anton, 0-1, Asia rap (Men) 16th, 2010, https://lichess.org/xbafFOgv }) 6. cxd4 Bb4+ (6... Bb6 7. d5 Nb8?! 8. e5 Ng8? 9. O-O Ne7? 10. d6 Ng6? 11. Ng5 O-O? 12. Qh5 h6 13. Qxg6 hxg5 14. Bxg5 Qe8 15. Bf6 $18 { -Chernev. Mate in 2. }) 7. Nc3 { White offers a pawn. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } (7. Nbd2 Nxe4 8. d5 Ne7 9. O-O Nf6 $15 { See the database. }) (7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 $14) 7... O-O? { Black makes a mistake in not taking the pawn. } (7... Nxe4 8. O-O (8. Qe2?! d5! 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O $17) 8... Bxc3! (8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3? { Black gets too materialistic. } 10. Ba3! { [%cal Ga3f8] } 10... Bxa1?? { [%cal Ga3f8,Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8] } 11. Re1+ Ne7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Rxe7+ Kxe7 14. Qxa1 $18) 9. d5! { The Moller Attack. Very complicated. } 9... Ne5 10. bxc3 Nxc4 11. Qd4 O-O (11... Ncd6 12. Qxg7 Qf6 13. Qxf6 Nxf6 14. Re1+ Nfe4) 12. Qxe4 Nd6 13. Qd3 Ne8 { Mieses-Suchting, Vienna 1908. }) 8. d5 { The White pawns now disrupt Black's piece positions. } (8. e5 Ne4 9. Qd3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Ba5 11. O-O d6 12. Ng5 g6 13. e6 d5?! 14. exf7+ (14. Qh3!) 14... Rxf7? (14... Kg7) 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Qf3+ Kg7 17. Bxd5 Qf6?? 18. Bh6+ Kxh6 19. Qxf6 { 1-0 Mietzner,T - Kitzberger,J Wilhelmshaven 1995 }) 8... Ne7 { Fritz-12 considers this a blunder and recommends 8...Na5. } (8... Na5) 9. e5 Ne4 { Rather than ...Ne8, which looks cramping. But this attack cannot work. } (9... Ne8 10. O-O d6 11. e6 Nf6 12. Re1 fxe6 13. dxe6 d5 14. Bd3 c5 15. a3 { [%cal Gb4a5,Ga5c7] } 15... Ba5 16. b4 cxb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Qb3 Bc5 19. Na4 Bd6 20. Nb6) 10. Qc2 { [%cal Ge4c3,Gb4c3,Gb2c3,Gc2c3] } 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bc5 12. Ng5! { Threatening Qxh7#. Black is forced into making some weakening move. Black is lost already. } 12... Ng6 (12... g6 { This creates holes around the castled King. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gh2h5,Gh5g6] } 13. h4 { -Stockfish. } (13. Ne4 { -Chernev. } 13... d6 14. Bh6 Bf5 { [%csl Gh6] } (14... Re8 15. Nf6+ Kh8 16. Nxe8 Qxe8 $16) 15. Bxf8 (15. Nf6+ Kh8 16. Bd3 dxe5 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. O-O (19. Ne4)) 15... Qxf8 $16)) (12... f5 13. d6+ Kh8 14. dxe7 Qxe7 15. O-O $16) 13. h4! { Threatening to dislodge the Knight. } 13... h6?? { Fritz-12 comment is: An oversight. But Black was lost anyway. } (13... Be7 14. h5 Bxg5 15. hxg6 Bxc1 (15... fxg6?? 16. d6+! Kh8 17. Qxg6 Bh4 18. Qh5 Qe8 19. Qxh4 Qxe5+ 20. Be2 Qf5 $18 { White can now try one of 21.Be3, Rh3, or dxc7. White is winning. }) 16. gxf7+ { [%cal Gh1h7,Gc2h7] } 16... Kxf7 17. d6+ Ke8 18. Qxc1 $18) (13... h5? 14. d6 Kh8 15. Bxf7 $18 { Black has to give up material to keep from getting mated immediately. }) (13... f6 14. d6+ Kh8 15. h5! (15. Nf7+? { -Chernev. } 15... Rxf7 16. Bxf7 Nxe5 17. Bb3 Bxd6 { White's attack is gone. }) 15... Bxf2+ 16. Kd1 (16. Kxf2?? fxg5+) 16... fxg5 17. hxg6 h6 18. Bf7 Bh4 { Because White was threatening mate in 4! } 19. g3 cxd6 (19... Bxg3?? 20. Rxh6+ gxh6 21. g7+ Kxg7 22. Qg6+ Kh8 23. Qxh6#) 20. gxh4 $18) (13... Qe8 14. h5 Qxe5+ 15. Kf1) 14. d6! { Threatens Qxg6. The Knight cannot move or else Qh7#. } 14... hxg5? { Mate in 7 per Stockfish. There was no good defense. } (14... Kh8 { To get out of the pin. } 15. Bxf7 { Renewing the Qxg6 threat. } 15... Qxg5 { Desperation, but there is nothing better. } 16. hxg5 Nxe5 17. gxh6 g6 18. Bf4 Rxf7 19. Bxe5+ Kh7 (19... Kg8 20. h7+ Rxh7 21. Qxg6+ Kf8 22. Rxh7 Bxf2+ 23. Kxf2 cxd6 24. Qf7#) 20. Rh5 $18) (14... Qxg5 15. hxg5) 15. hxg5 { The Knight still cannot move or else White would mate with Qh7#. } (15. Qxg6 Qe8 16. hxg5 Qxe5+ 17. Kf1 Qe1+ 18. Kxe1 Re8+ 19. Be3 Re6 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Qh8#) 15... Re8 (15... Qe8 { Activating the Queen does not help. } 16. Qxg6 Qxe5+ 17. Kf1 Qe1+ { Spite check. } 18. Kxe1 Re8+ 19. Be3 Rxe3+ 20. fxe3 Bxd6 21. Qxf7#) (15... Bxf2+ { Fritz-12: doesn't get the bull off the ice. } 16. Kxf2 Re8 17. Qxg6 Re6 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Qh8#) 16. Qxg6 { [%cal Gc4g8] } 16... Rxe5+ 17. Kf1 { Black resigned. The threats are 18.Qxf7# and 18.Qh7+ Kf8 19.Qh8#. Black can only throw away pieces. For example: } (17. Be3! { This is better because there is a forced mate in 3 more moves. } 17... Rxe3+ 18. fxe3 Qf6 { Stops the mate on f7, but... } 19. Qh7+ Kf8 20. Qh8#) 17... Re1+ (17... Qe8 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Qh8#) 18. Kxe1 Qe8+ 19. Be3 Bxd6 20. Bxf7+ Qxf7 21. Rh8+ Kxh8 22. Qxf7 b6 23. Kd2 Bb7 24. Rh1+ Bh2 25. Rxh2# 1-0


