{ -
In a Ruy Lopez, Black plays the Schliemann Defense. White aggressively counters with 4.d4. White continues with the aggressive 5.Nxe5 but Black chops that Knight off. Black wins a pawn, and then White allows his King Bishop to be shut out of the game. White also castles into an attack. White lacks any counterplay and fails to find the best defense in a lost position.

Regarding the quote from Young in Chernev's book see:
https://www.chesshistory.com/winter/extra/young.html
- }
1. e4 { Regarding the quote from Franklin K. Young by Chernev, see:
https://www.chesshistory.com/winter/extra/young.html } 1... e5 2. Nf3 (2. f4 { Compare the King's Gambit with the Schliemann Defense. } 2... exf4 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 { White has the d4/e4 pawn phalanx. Black cannot get this in the Schliemann. }) 2... Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy Lopez } 3... f5 { The Schliemann Defense to the Ruy Lopez. Compare ideas to the King's Gambit. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rd7d5,Rh8f8,Rf8f5] } (3... a6 { Morphy Defense } 4. Ba4 { [%csl Ra6][%cal Rb7b5] } (4. Bxc6 { Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation
Played just to show that White cannot win the e-pawn. } 4... dxc6 5. Nxe5? Qd4 { [%cal Rd4e5,Rd4e4] } 6. Nf3 Qxe4+) 4... Nf6 { The question was asked regarding White's King Bishop getting kicked around in some variations of the Ruy. What compensation does White get for that loss of time? Let's look at the main line. } 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 { Black has weakened his queenside. White may get his Bishop to c2 in some variations - it would then protect e4. Of course, Black is getting his queenside play started. So weakness or not? That's the question!
See also Reti's annotation after Black's move 4 in his game #15, Steinitz - Blackburne, London 1876. } { [%csl Ra5,Rc5,Rb6][%cal Ra8d5] } 7... d6 8. c3 { [%cal Rb3c2,Rc2e4] }) 4. d4 { Very aggressive. 4.Nc3 or 4.d3 may be better. } (4. exf5 { Played to compare with the KGA. } 4... e4 { Black tries to displace White's Knight. } (4... d6 { Black cannot play 4...d5. }) 5. Qe2 { White does not have to move his Knight immediately. } 5... Qe7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nd4 Qe5 8. Ne6! { A key idea that lead to masters abandoning the old gambits is giving back the pawn to reach a favorable position. } 8... Bxe6 9. fxe6 Bd6 10. Nc3 Nf6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Qxe6 { White can castle queenside with a good game. }) (4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. Bg5 (6. O-O) 6... Be7 (6... Bc5) 7. Nc3 d6 8. Bc4 Na5 9. Qe2 c6 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. h3 Nxc4 { Another sample line from MCO-11. }) (4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 { [%cal Rb5e8] } 6. Nxe5 dxe4 7. Nxc6 bxc6?! (7... Qg5 { [%cal Rg5b5,Rg5g2] } 8. Qe2) 8. Bxc6+ Bd7 9. Qh5+ Ke7 10. Qe5+ Be6 11. Bxa8! Qxa8 12. Qxc7+ Kf6 13. O-O Be7?! 14. f3 h6 15. fxe4+ Kg6 16. d3 { A sample line from MCO-11. Wild! }) (4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3) 4... fxe4 (4... Nxd4?! { -
In response to a question about examples where White did well with 4.d4.
A dubious move by Black.
- } 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. O-O c6 7. Bc4 Nf6 { Timofeev, Artyom - Zvjaginsev, Vadim, 1-0, RUS Cup, 2007, https://lichess.org/OLeHYV4Q }) 5. Nxe5 { MCO-11 gives this a ? and gives Bxc6 instead. But this move has been play by masters. } (5. Bxc6 { Safer. per Chernev. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5 { Chernev stopped here. } 6... Qh4! (6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. c3) 7. Qe2 (7. O-O Bd6) (7. Nc3 Bb4 (7... Nf6 { Short, Nigel D - Piket, Jeroen, 1/2-1/2, Dortmund, 1995, https://lichess.org/IBynO60I })) 7... Be6 8. h3 O-O-O { MCO-11. }) 5... Nxe5 (5... d6?? 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bxc6+ Bd7 8. Bxa8 $18 (8. Bxe4 c6 9. Qh5+ g6?! (9... Ke7 10. Bg5+ Nf6 11. O-O $18) 10. Bxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ Nf6 12. O-O $18)) 6. dxe5 c6 7. Bc4? { This Bishop will have no influence here. If White does not want to sacrifice the Bishop with 7.Nc3, then maybe Be2 would be better. } (7. Be2 { We looked at this line during the session. } 7... Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Qxe5 { Black has won a pawn. } 9. Be3 d5 { Played to compare with the game where Black had the same pawn structure. } 10. Bd4 Qe6 11. Qd2 Nf6 12. O-O-O { White would probably be safe if castled kingside, but let's see what happens if he castles queenside. } 12... Bd6 { Black cannot afford to leave his King in the center because the e-pawn will come under attack. } 13. f3 { White play is in the center. Sillman would say that Black's pawn structure (the chain of pawns) is indicating the Black should play on the kingside. } 13... O-O 14. Kb1 { A good idea when you castle queenside. Now the King guards a2 and is not on the same diagonal as White's Queen. } 14... b5 { In response to a question of why Black does not start a queenside pawn storm, we looked at this. } 15. Rhe1 { Can White sacrifice the h-pawn here? } 15... Bxh2 { Played to see what happens if Black gets distracted by the pawn grab. } 16. Bc5 Bd6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Nxe4! { White takes advantage of the pin up the d-file. } { [%cal Rd1d6] } 18... Nxe4 19. fxe4 Be6 20. exd5 Bxd5 { A "natural" move but ... } { [%cal Rd1d6] } 21. Bxb5 { Yet again the pin. } 21... cxb5 22. Qxd5+ Qxd5 23. Rxd5 a6 24. Rd2 { Chances for both sides. }) (7. Nc3 cxb5 8. Nxe4 d5 9. exd6 Nf6 10. Ng5? (10. O-O) 10... Qa5+? (10... Bxd6) 11. Bd2 b4 { MCO-11 gives this as analysis from Podgorny and Pribyl and gives Black a small plus. However I think the whole line is questionable because I'm not sure each side has played their best moves.
Stockfish in 2020 says +3.5! }) 7... Qa5+ { Winning a pawn and activating the Queen which will be quite safe because White's King Knight is gone. } { [%cal Ga5e1,Ga5e5] } 8. Nc3 Qxe5 { [%cal Rd7d5] } 9. O-O { Castling into a future attack. White should consider waiting and castling queenside. } (9. Bxg8 Rxg8 10. Be3 Bb4 11. Qd2 Kf7 12. f3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Re8 14. O-O Kg8 15. fxe4 c5 { Khechumyan, Gagik - Horvath, Tamas2, 1-0, HUN-chT2 Charousek 0203, 2003, https://lichess.org/QJd7Yb54 }) 9... d5 10. Bb3?! (10. Be2 { Chernev. }) 10... Nf6 { Black owns the center. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rc3e2,Rc1f4] } 11. Be3? { A faster way to challenge the Queen is 11.Ne2 followed by Bf4.
Stockfish counts this as -5.4; a loss of 3.2 points. } (11. Ne2 { [%cal Rc1f4,Re2f4] }) 11... Bd6 { Threatening Qxh2 and forcing some weakening of White's position. } { [%cal Rd6h2] } 12. g3 { [%csl Gf3,Gg4,Gh3,Gg2] } (12. f4 exf3 13. Rxf3 Qxh2+ 14. Kf1 (14. Kf2 Bg4 { Chernev }) 14... Qh1+ (14... Bg4 { Not as good as Qh1+. } 15. Bg1 Qe5 16. Bd4 Qe7 $19 { Black wins at least the exchange. }) 15. Bg1 (15. Ke2 Qxg2+ 16. Rf2 Bg4+ 17. Kd3 Qxf2 18. Bxf2 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 h5 $19) 15... Bc5 { [%cal Rc5g1,Rh1g1] } 16. Ne2 Ng4 17. Nd4 Nh2+ 18. Kf2 Nxf3 19. gxf3 O-O $19) 12... Bg4 { Chernev says the theme is penetration. } 13. Qd2? { [%cal Rd2f2,Rd2g2] } (13. Ne2 Qh5 14. f4 (14. Nf4 Bxf4 $19) (14. Re1 Bf3 15. h4 Qg4 $19 { [%cal Gg4h3,Gh3g2] }) 14... exf3 15. Nf4 Bxf4 16. Bxf4 f2+ { [%cal Rg4d1] } 17. Kg2 Qh3+ 18. Kxf2 Bxd1 $19) (13. Qd4 Qf5 (13... Qh5 14. h4 Bf3 $19) 14. f4 { Now Black would have to decide if it is ok to open the position with exf3 even though his King is not castled, or if it would be better to castle first and then try to take advantage of the holes around White's King. } 14... h5 { [%cal Rh5h4,Rh4g3] } 15. h4 $19) 13... Bf3 { Occupying one of the holes around the kingside. } { [%cal Ge5f5,Gf5h3,Gh3g2] } 14. Bf4 { Not the best defense. } (14. Rfb1 { White can try escaping with his King, but if he does not play the best defensive moves he'll still get mated in short order. The best defensive moves here involve giving up material! White is lost. } 14... Qf5 15. Kf1 Qh3+ 16. Ke1 Qxh2 { [%cal Rh2g1] } 17. Qd4 b5 { Threatening 19...c5 and the Queen is trapped because if 20.Qd2 then 20...Qg1#. } (17... Ng4 { [%cal Rd6e5,Rg4e5] } 18. Qxg7 Nxe3 19. Qxh8+? (19. fxe3? Qg1+ 20. Kd2 Qf2+ 21. Ne2 Qxe2+ 22. Kc3 Qxe3#) 19... Kf7 20. Qxa8? Ng2+ 21. Kd2 Qh6# { [%cal Re4d3,Rf3d1,Rg2e1,Rh6c1] }) 18. Ne2 c5 19. Qd1 d4 20. Bg5? e3 21. fxe3 Ne4 22. Qd3 Qf2+ 23. Kd1 Qf1#) 14... Qf5 { Preparing to invade at h3. } 15. Nd1 { There is nothing better. } 15... Qh3 { Black threatens Qg2#. White cannot stop a quick mate. } { [%cal Rh3g2] } 16. Ne3 { [%cal Re3g2] } 16... Ng4 { Now the threat is Qxh2#. If 17.Nxg4 Qg7#. } { [%cal Gg4h2,Gh3h2] } 17. Rfc1 Qxh2+ { White resigned. } 18. Kf1 Qh1# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } 0-1


