{ -
In the Delayed Exchange Variation of the French Defense, Black weakens his kingside with ...g6 and then castles kingside. White sacrifices the exchange to create a pin on Black's King Knight to his Queen. The pinned Knight is then piled on, even with more sacrifices, and Black's defense breaks down. White wins the pinned Knight and the final threats on the weakened dark squares cause Black to resign.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Spielmann
- }
1. e4 e6 { French Defense } 2. d4 d5 { Notice Black's bad Queen Bishop; the problem child of the French. } 3. Nc3 (3. e5 { Advance Variation
Nimzowitsch championed this. See his comments in "My System" section 5. Over-Protection.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Advance_Variation:_3.e5 }) (3. Nd2 { Tarrasch Variation
Avoids the Winawer Variation.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Tarrasch_Variation:_3.Nd2 }) 3... Nf6 { Classical Variation
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Classical_Variation:_3...Nf6 } (3... Bb4 { Winawer Variation
Very complex. See Nimzowitch and Botvinnik as early adopters.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Winawer_Variation:_3...Bb4 }) 4. exd5 { Delayed Exchange Variation
The Exchange Variation is discussed here:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Exchange_Variation:_3.exd5_exd5 } (4. Bg5 { Burn Variation }) (4. e5 { Steinitz Variation }) 4... exd5 { Exchange variation. Drawish. Notice how White has solved Black's Queen Bishop problems for Black. } 5. Bg5 { It seems White is trying to avoid the more symmetrical variations. The threat is Bxf6 breaking up the kingside pawns. } { [%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5,Gd8f6,Gg7f6] } 5... Be7 6. Bd3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 7. Nge2 { To avoid the Bishop pin. } { [%cal Ge2d4,Gc6d4] } (7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Be2 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 f6 14. Bg3 Qd7 15. Qd3 O-O-O 16. h3 f5 17. Be5 { Dueckstein,A-Roth,P (AUT BL 1990)
draw. }) 7... Nb4 { Black wants to trade his Knight for the good White Bishop on d3. Castling here would also be a good choice. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gb4d3] } 8. Ng3 (8. Bb5+ c6 9. Ba4 { Puts the Bishop out of the game. }) (8. Nf4 Nxd3+ 9. Nxd3) 8... Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 { In exchange for giving up the good Bishop, White has gained time and space. } { [%cal Rg3f5,Rd3f5] } 9... g6? { Was Black thinking that he could play 10...Bf5 attacking the Queen? But White's Knight on g3 guards f5. Or was he thinking that this move would keep the White Knight out of f5? The move Black played is really bad because it weakens the Knight and makes holes on the kingside.
Much better was ...0-0 or ...c6. } { [%csl Gh6,Gf6,Gg7] } (9... O-O 10. O-O h6 $15) 10. O-O c6 (10... Bf5?? 11. Nxf5 gxf5 12. Rfe1 (12. Qxf5 { Also works. }) 12... Ne4 13. Bxe7 $18 { If Black takes with the Queen he loses the Queen pawn. If he takes with the King, then f3 attackes the now pinned Knight. }) 11. Rae1 { [%cal Ge1e8,Gg5f6] } 11... O-O { Probably thinking he's escaping one of the pins and getting the King to safety. Not! } { [%cal Rg5d8] } (11... Be6 12. f4 { Threatening 13.f5. } 12... a6 { To see the threat. } 13. f5 gxf5 14. Nxf5 { Threatening Nxe7. } 14... Rg8 15. h4 Rg6 16. Nxe7 Qxe7 17. Rxf6 Rxf6 18. Qxh7 O-O-O (18... Kd7 19. Na4) 19. Qg7 Re8 (19... Rg6 20. Qxg6 $18) 20. Bxf6 $18) 12. Rxe7! { Knocking the support out from under the Knight and getting rid of one of the defenders of the dark squares. Watch now as White attacks on those dark squares. } (12. Bh6 Re8) 12... Qxe7 13. Qf3 { Threatening to win the Knight and plant the Bishop in the hole. } { [%cal Gg5f6,Gf3f6,Ge7f6] } 13... Kg7? (13... Bg4 { This attempt to "mix it up" is probably a better defense, but it still loses. } 14. Qf4 (14. Bxf6 Bxf3 15. Bxe7 Rfe8 16. Bf6 Bg4 17. f3 $18) 14... Kg7 15. Bxf6+ Qxf6 16. Qxg4 $16) (13... Bf5 { Chernev gives ... } 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Qg3 Kg7 (15... Kh8 16. Qh4 Kg7 17. Qh6+ Kg8 18. Bxf6 $18) 16. Bxf6+ Kxf6 17. Qh4+ Ke6 18. Re1+ Kd7 19. Qxe7+ Kc8 20. Qxf8+ Kc7 21. Qxa8 $18) 14. Nge4! { Pile on the pinned piece. } { [%cal Gg5f6,Ge4f6,Gf3f6] } 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4f6,Gg5f6,Gf3f6] } 15... Qe6 (15... Bf5 16. Bxf6+ Qxf6 17. Nxf6 Kxf6 18. g4 $18) (15... Nxe4 16. Bxe7 $18) (15... Qxe4?? 16. Qxf6+ Kg8 17. Bh6 Qxd4 18. Qxd4 f6 19. Qc4+! Rf7 20. Re1 Bd7 21. Re7 Be6 22. Qxe6 Rf8 23. Rxf7 Rxf7 24. Qe8+ Rf8 25. Qxf8#) 16. Bxf6+ Kg8 { or give up the Queen. } (16... Kh6 17. Qf4+ Kh5 18. Qg5#) 17. Qf4 { Black resigned. The only way to stop White's Queen from going to h6 and then mating is to give up the Black Queen. } { [%cal Gf4h6,Gh6g7] } 1-0


