{ -
This game features the Colle System. White plays the thematic e4 break. Black plays aggressively but has problems with the location of his Queen on c7 and defending White's kingside attack. White's threats induce a weakening of the dark-squares around the castled Black King. Black blunders and loses two pieces for a Rook while also letting White cut off the Black Queen's second rank defense. White then attacks on the weakened dark-squares and mates.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dawid_Przepi%C3%B3rka
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ladislav_Proke%C5%A1
- }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 d5 { -
Colle System, by transposition.
Opening systems are concerned more with the placement of the men than the sequence of moves. They also have associated plans.
For the Colle System see:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colle_System
- } 4. Bd3 c5 { Attacking the White center. } 5. c3 { Played both so that White can recapture with the c-pawn if Black exchanges pawns, and so that the Bishop can retreat to c2 if necessary. } 5... Nbd7 { Black has many options. 5...Nc6 is popular because it puts pressure on d4. The advantage of ...Nbd7 is that the Knight is protecting the King Knight and staying off the c-file where it could hinder action of a heavy piece on that file. } (5... cxd4 6. exd4) 6. Nbd2 { White plans to play e4. Eventually the Knight on d2 will move so that the Bishop on c1 is free. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge3,Gd3,Gd2,Gf3] } 6... Bd6 { Much more aggressive than ...Be7. Black must watch out for a pawn pin at e5 in some variations. } 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 { White could play e4 now, but decides to back it up with the Rook first. } 8... Qc7 { Black could have played e5!
Chernev says that this is an ideal location for the Queen. However, it seems to be a mistake to play this *and* open the c-file.
-
