- } (8... e5! 9. e4 { Who will break the tension in the center first? Black might as follows. } 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Qc7 11. exd5 exd4 12. Nc4) 9. e4 { The main point of the Colle System; White achieves e4.
Here is the threatened pawn fork mentioned before - 10.e5. } 9... cxd4 { This ends up causing trouble because the Black Queen is on the resulting open file. It is the most played move in the Lichess DB and in the Power 2009 DB from Chessbase. Yet it seems suspicious because Black's Queen becomes exposed. } (9... dxe4 { This is a safer alternative. } 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 Re8 12. Rh4 h6 (12... Nf8 13. Ng5 h6 14. Qh5 e5 15. Bc4! Be6 16. Nxe6 Nxe6 17. Bxh6 g6 18. Rg4 $18 { Threatening Rxg6+ winning. }) 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Rxh6 Bf4 15. Rh4 { Compare to Chernev's recommendation in an alternate line of mainline. }) 10. cxd4 dxe4 { Stops the threat of 11.e5 winning a piece. As in many of the variations here, White gets an isolani.
See my Intermediate study: https://lichess.org/study/6AnWFDzO/E1qIQ286 } { [%csl Gd4] } (10... e5 11. exd5 exd4 12. Nc4 { See above variation at Black's 8...e5. }) 11. Nxe4 b6 { Planning to fianchetto the Bishop. Probably too slow. } (11... Nxe4 12. Rxe4 { What is the best plan for Black here? } { [%csl Gd4] }) (11... Bf4 { Chernev's recommended this with no variation. } 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. Ne5 Bxc1 (13... Bxe5 14. dxe5 { [%csl Re5,Rf2,Rg2,Rh2] }) 14. Rxc1 Qd6 15. Re3 { [%csl Gd4] }) (11... Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 b6 14. Rac1 Qb8 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { [%csl Gd4] }) 12. Bg5 { Applying pressure. Threatening to break up the kingside pawns. } { [%cal Re4f6,Rg5f6,Gd7f6,Gg7f6] } 12... Nxe4 { Perhaps trying to relieve some of the pressure by exchanging pieces. But the Knight was needed for defense of the kingside. Black is just helping White develop his pieces for the attack. } (12... Bb7 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Bxf6 gxf6) (12... Bf4 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. g3 Bh6 15. Nxf6+ gxf6) 13. Rxe4 { This Rook lift makes the capture with the Rook much better than the capture with the Bishop. } 13... Bb7 { Developing the Bishop on the only square it can move to. } (13... Nf6?? { A "really bad idea". } 14. Rh4 a6 { null move } (14... h6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rg4+! (16. Rxh6 { -Chernev says this wins a pawn. It actually wins the game. }) 16... Kh8 17. Qd2 { The threat of Qxh6# wins. } 17... Bf4 18. Rxf4 f5 { Trying to stop Rg4. } 19. Rg4 { Anyway! } 19... Kh7 (19... fxg4?? 20. Qxh6+ Kg8 21. Qh7#) (19... f4 20. Ne5 f5 21. Qxf4 Rf6 22. Rg6 Qe7 23. Qh4 (23. Qxh6+ Qh7 24. Rxf6 Qxh6 25. Rxh6+) 23... Bd7 24. Rxf6 $18) 20. Rh4 Kg8 21. Qxh6 f6 22. Qh8+ Kf7 23. Qh7+ Ke8 24. Qxc7 $18) 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxh7+ Kg7 17. Rg4+ Kxh7?? 18. Qd3+ f5 19. Ne5! Be7 20. Qh3+ Bh4 21. Qxh4#) 14. Rc1! { Grabbing the open file. } (14. Rh4 f5 15. Rc1 Qb8 16. Bc4 Re8 17. Qd3 Be4 18. Rxe4 fxe4 19. Qxe4 a6 { Knezevic,Milorad-Dizdar,Goran (Trencianske Teplice(10) draw) }) 14... Qb8 { Trying to maintain some pressure on h2. } (14... Bxe4?? 15. Rxc7 Bxf3 16. Bxh7+! (16. Qxf3?! { -Chernev. } 16... Bxc7 17. Qc6?! Bd8 18. Be3 Bf6 19. Qxd7 $18) 16... Kxh7 17. Qd3+ Kg8 18. Rxd7 Bxh2+ 19. Kxh2 Bc6 20. Rc7 Bd5 21. Qg3 $18) 15. Rh4 { The threat to win the h7 pawn means that Black will have to weaken the kingside. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Rh4h7,Gg8h7] } 15... g6 { Weakens the dark squares. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh6,Rg7,Gd7] } (15... f5 { This weakens e6. White can now win it. For example... } 16. Bc4 Qe8 (16... Re8 17. d5 Nc5 18. dxe6 Be7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Ng5 $18) 17. Qb3 Kh8 18. Re1 e5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Qh3 Qg6 21. dxe5 $18) (15... Nf6?? 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Qd2 { Stronger than Chernev's Bxh7+. }) (15... h6 16. Bxh6 gxh6?? 17. Qd2 { Or Rg4+ first. Chernev is missing the Qd2 resource. } (17. Rg4+ Kh8 18. Qd2) (17. Rxh6?? { -Chernev. But this is a blunder because White had much better moves. } 17... Bf4 18. Bh7+?? Kg7 19. Rh4 Rh8)) 16. Bb5 { [%csl Rd7][%cal Rb5d7] } 16... Qe8? { Pinning the Queen. Not good. But Black wanted to defend his Knight, which had no place to go! } { [%cal Rb5e8] } (16... f6 { Counter attack. A *much* better defense here. } 17. Bh6 Rf7 $16) (16... Bc8 17. Bc6 { [%cal Rd1d2,Rd2h6,Rg5f6] } 17... a6 $18 { White can either win the exchange, or put on more pressure with Qd2 or d5. }) (16... Rd8 17. Bxd8 Qxd8 $18 { White has won the exchange. }) (16... Bxf3? 17. Qxf3 Qe8 18. Rxh7 { - Stockfish! } (18. Qc6? { Chernev thought this won a piece. } 18... Be7 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 { White's Rook is hanging. } 20. Rh3 Nf6 { So White has not won a piece. }) 18... Be7 (18... Kxh7? 19. Bxd7 $18 Qxd7?? { Black cannot take because now White forces mate. } 20. Qh3+ Kg7 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Bf6 Bxh2+ 23. Kh1 b5 24. Qg7#) 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Qh3) 17. Ne5 { A fine outpost for the Knight.
Double attacks the Knight on d7. } { [%cal Rb5d7,Re5d7,Ge8d7,Rd1d7,Rc1c7,Rc7b7] } 17... Bc8?? { This loses two pieces for a Rook and lets the Bishop on b5 invade. } { [%cal Rb5e8,Re5d7,Rc1c8,Ga8c8,Gc8d7] } (17... f6 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 (18... Bxe5 19. dxe5 $18) 19. Nxd7 Qf7 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Qg4 $18 { White is up the exchange. }) (17... Bxe5 18. dxe5 Bd5 { Blocks the Queen's attack on the Knight. } 19. Rc7 $18 { Wins the Knight. -Chernev } (19. Bf6 Rc8? { The Queen could not leave the Knight. And if the Knight moves the Queen is lost. If the Bishop moves the Knight is lost. } 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Qd2 Nxf6 22. exf6 { Still threatening mate on g7 with the Queen via h6. } 22... Rd8 23. Qh6 Qc1+ { The only move to stop mate. } 24. Qxc1 Bb7 (24... a6 25. Qh6 axb5 26. Qg7#) 25. Qh6 Rd1+ 26. Bf1 Rxf1+ 27. Kxf1 Ba6+ 28. Ke1 g5 29. Qg7#)) (17... Nxe5?? 18. Bxe8 $18 { Black loses the Queen. }) 18. Rxc8! Qxc8 (18... Rxc8? 19. Bxd7 $18 { Traps the Queen. }) 19. Bxd7 Qc7 { Threatens 20...Bxe5, which is not much of a threat. Also the Queen may be able to get to the kingside along the rank. } (19... Qb7 20. Ng4 { Threatening 21.Nf6+ Kg7 or Kh8 22.Rxh7# } (20. Bc6 { Chernev says this wins the exchange. True, but White has a better move. }) 20... f6 21. Bxf6 { Now the threat is 22.Nh6# } 21... Rf7 22. Nh6+ Kf8 23. Nxf7 Kxf7 (23... Qxd7 24. Rxh7 $18) 24. Qg4 { Threatening mate in 4 starting 25.Rxh7# } 24... Kxf6 25. Qxe6+ Kg7 26. Qxd6 $18) 20. Ng4 { Threatening mate in 2 with 21.Nf6# K-any 22.Rxh7#. White invades on the black squares. } { [%cal Rg4f6,Rf6g8,Rf6h7,Rh4h7,Rh7h8] } 20... h5 { Protecting all the material for now - except the King! } (20... f5 { So the Rook can guard f6, but these leaves the e-pawn unprotected. } 21. Bxe6+ Kg7 (21... Kh8 22. Nf6 $18) 22. Ne3!! { Threatening 23.Bh6 and more! } (22. Bh6+ { Chernev says this wins the exchange. True, but White has better. }) 22... Rfe8 23. Nxf5+!! { Mate in 9 starting with this sacrifice! The longest line is this... } 23... gxf5 24. Rxh7+! Kf8 25. Bh6+ Qg7 26. Bxg7+ Ke7 27. Be5+ Kd8 (27... Kxe6 28. Qb3#) 28. Rd7+ Kc8 29. Qf3 Rb8 30. Rxd6+ Rxe6 31. Qc6#) 21. Nf6+ { White has a forced mate! } 21... Kg7 { Prolongs mate. } (21... Kh8 22. Rxh5+! { One way or another the pawns get broken up. } 22... gxh5 (22... Kg7 23. Rh7#) 23. Qxh5+ Kg7 24. Qh7#) 22. Nxh5+! { Breaking up the pawns. } 22... gxh5 { There is nothing better. } (22... Kg8 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Rh7#) (22... Kh8 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Rh7#) 23. Qxh5 { [%cal Rh5h7] } 23... Rh8 (23... Bxh2+ { There is no defense. Black can postpone mate only by throwing material away. } 24. Kh1 Qc1+ 25. Bxc1 Bf4 26. Bxf4 Rfd8 27. Qg5+ Kf8 28. Rh8#) 24. Bh6+ { Black resigned. } 24... Rxh6 (24... Kf6 25. Qg5#) (24... Kh7 25. Qxf7#) (24... Kg8 25. Qg5+ Kh7 26. Qg7#) 25. Qxh6+ Kg8 26. Qh8# 1-0


[Event "Weston-Super-Mare"]
