[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dwrNFeej/TKCxnwct"]

{ -
In a Ruy Lopez Closed Defense, both sides maneuver to gain control of key squares. Black weakens his kingside with g6 so as to control f5. White skillfully removes Black's dark-square Bishop and then occupies both the f6 and h6 squares with Queen and Bishop. Then White swaps those two pieces in an interesting reorganization. Whites control of the d-file and kingside attack wins.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Znosko-Borovsky
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Henry_Mackenzie
- }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy Lopez } 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 { Ruy Lopez: Morphy defense } (4... d6 5. d4 b5 6. Bb3 Nxd4 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4? c5 9. Qd5 Be6 10. Qc6+ Bd7 11. Qd5 c4 $19 { Ruy Lopez, Noah's Ark Trap }) 5. O-O Be7 { Ruy Lopez: closed defense } 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 Na5 9. Bc2 c5 10. d4 Qc7 { -
So far these are all standard moves of the closed defense of the Ruy called the Chigorin Variation. Per Wikipedia this variation was refined by Mikhail Chigorin around the turn of the 20th century and became the primary Black defense to the Ruy Lopez for more than fifty years.
Black's Queen Knight has chased the White King Bishop off the a2-g8 diagonal and allowed Black to play ...c5 and ...Qc7. The Black Queen is defending e5 and might be used later on the c-file if/when Black plays ...cxd4.
Wikipedia on Mikhail Chigorin
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Chigorin
- } (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qc7 12. h3 O-O 13. Nbd2 Nc6 14. Nb3 a5 15. Be3 a4 16. Nbd2 Bd7 17. Rc1 Qb7 { Position A: Compare with the variation off mainline at Black's 14th move. }) 11. h3 { -
Restricting Black's white-squared Bishop. White determines this is worth the weakening of his kingside. Chernev gets into a discussion of whether a move is "weakening" if the opponent cannot take advantage of it. There are multiple definitions of "weak".
The position now reached is essentially the classical main line position of the Chigorin.
- } (11. Nbd2 O-O 12. h3 (12. d5)) 11... Nc6 { -
Usually Black castles first. According to Leonard Barden in "The Ruy Lopez: Winning Chess with 1.PK4", this move is an invention of Vassily Smylov (former WCC). The idea is similar to Black's play in the Alekhine's Defense, where Black entices White to advance pawns in the center where they may become weak.
Wikipedia on Vasily Smyslov
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasily_Smyslov
- } 12. Be3 { More usual here are 12.d5 (taking up the invitation to advance the center pawn), 12.Nbd2 and 12.dxc5. } 12... O-O { Still inviting 13.d5. } (12... exd4!? 13. cxd4 Nb4 { Black can now get rid of White's white-squared Bishop. }) 13. Nbd2 { Beginning a journey to d5! Chernev points out that if White played d5 here then he would deprive d5 for his pieces. It would also release tension in the center. Tension provides more opportunities. } { [%cal Rd2f1,Rf1e3,Re3d5] } (13. d5 Na5 14. b3 (14. b4?! cxb4 15. cxb4 Nc4) 14... Bd7 { Malashenkov, Alexei - Dabija, Mircea, 1-0, WC38/pr09, 2014, https://lichess.org/V7VN6cBq }) 13... Bd7 { If Black opens the c-file then White would play Rc1 indirectly attacking the Black Queen. } (13... Ne8 { The move in the Lichess DB. } 14. Nf1 Bb7 { [%cal Rb7d5] } 15. Ng3 g6 16. a4 Ng7 17. Bh6 exd4 18. cxd4 Bf6 19. axb5 Nxd4 20. bxa6 Rxa6 21. Rxa6 Bxa6 22. b4 Rc8 { Hacik, Radomir - Drtina, Milan, 1/2-1/2, SVK-chT 0708, 2008, https://lichess.org/RtCcNF2A }) (13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Na5 15. Rc1 Nc4) 14. Rc1 { Played to discourage Black from exchanging pawns which could put his Queen on an open file with this Rook poised for a discovered attack. } 14... Ne8 { Playing for control of f5 (...g6 and Knight at g7).
In the following variations I look for other ideas for Black. } (14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Qb7 { See position A earlier. }) (14... Rfc8 15. Nf1 Qd8 { Getting the Queen off the c-file. } 16. Ng3 cxd4 { Risky. } (16... h6 17. d5 (17. Nf5?! Bxf5 18. exf5 e4) 17... Na5 18. b3 Rab8) 17. cxd4 Bf8 18. dxe5 dxe5 19. Bb3 h6 20. Rxc6 { An exchange sacrifice suggested by SF. } 20... Bxc6 21. Nxe5 Be8 22. Qf3 { Threatening 23.Nf5, 23.Ng6, and 23.Rd1. } 22... a5 23. Rd1 Qc7 24. Ng4 { Threatening to win with 25.Nxf6+. } 24... Ra6 25. Bf4 Qb7 26. Nxf6+ Rxf6 27. Qg4 Kh8 28. e5 Rg6 29. Qf5 a4 30. Bd5 Qa6 31. h4 { Threatening h5 winning. } 31... Rd8 (31... h5? 32. Ne4 $18) 32. h5 Rc6 (32... Rb6 33. Ne4 Qc8 34. Qxc8 Rxc8 35. Be3 Rbb8 36. Ba7 f6 37. exf6 Bxh5 38. f3 Bg6 39. f7 Bxe4 40. fxe4 Bc5+ 41. Bxc5 Rxc5 42. e5 g6 43. e6 Rc7 44. Re1 Re7) 33. Kh2 Rxd5 34. Rxd5 Rc8 35. Ne4 Qe6 36. Nd6 Bxd6 37. exd6 Qxf5 38. Rxf5 f6 39. Rd5 Bd7 40. Kg3) 15. Nf1 { Black will probably be concerned that this Knight will go to g3 and then f5. f5 is often a Knight outpost for White in the Ruy. } 15... g6 { So Black has his pawn guard f5. But look at the holes this created on his kingside at f6 and h6. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh6] } 16. Bh6 { Of course. } 16... Ng7 { Protecting the loss of the exchange, though it is not clear if White would give up such a well placed Bishop for the exchange. } 17. Ne3 { Continuing his journey. } 17... Rae8 { Perhaps anticipating the opening of the e-file. Chernev says Black does not want to open lines and instead is making a tight nit defense. Black's problem seems to be the ordering of the moves. If the KR had moved earlier then the KB could retreat to f8. } (17... Be6?? 18. d5 $18) 18. Nd5 { A fine outpost for the Knight, but White can immediately use the outpost to remove a key defender. Meanwhile, White gains time by attacking the Queen. } 18... Qb7 { Black decides to keep his Queen close to the rest of his army. } 19. Nxe7+ { Removing one of the key defenders of the dark squares. } 19... Rxe7 { Black cannot recapture with the Knight because that would block the Rook's defense of the e5 pawn and Black would then lose that pawn as follows... } (19... Nxe7 20. dxc5 dxc5 21. Nxe5 $18) 20. dxc5 { White starts a combination aimed at getting his Queen to Black's kingside. } 20... dxc5 { Otherwise Black is a pawn down. } 21. Qd6 { Threatening to win the pawn on c5. An interesting way to bring the Queen to f6! } { [%cal Rd6c5] } 21... c4 { Removing the threat. } 22. Qf6 { Threatening Qxg7#. } { [%cal Rf6g7,Rh6g7] } 22... Nh5 { Stops the mate and attacks the Queen. } { [%cal Gh5g7] } 23. Qh4 { Retreating as part of a reorganization. } 23... Ng7 { Worth considering was Rc8. } (23... Rc8 24. Rcd1 f6 25. Rd2 $16 { White will double Rooks on the d-file. }) 24. Be3 { White reorganizes. Threatens Bc5 winning the exchange. } 24... Ne6? { Perhaps 24...f6. } (24... f6 25. Bc5 Ne6 26. Bxe7 Nxe7 $18) 25. Qf6!? { Occupying one of the dark square holes. } { [%cal Rf6e5,Rf3e5,Gc6e5,Ge7e5] } (25. Nxe5! { Winning. } { [%cal Rh4e7] } 25... h5 (25... Nxe5? 26. Qxe7 $18) 26. Rcd1 Rd8? 27. Nxc6 Bxc6 (27... Qxc6? 28. Qxe7 $18) 28. Rxd8+ Nxd8 29. Bg5 Rd7 30. Bxd8 $18) 25... Qc7 { Defending the e5 pawn. } (25... Ng7 26. Bc5 Re6 (26... Nh5 27. Qh4 $18) 27. Qh4 Rfe8 (27... Ree8 28. Bxf8 $18) 28. Ng5 $18) 26. Bh6 { Occupying the other dark square hole. } 26... Rc8 { Perhaps Black was thinking of moving the Bishop to e8. } (26... Rd8 27. Rcd1 (27. Nh2 Bc8 28. Ng4 Red7 29. Qh4 Rd6 30. Nf6+ Kh8 31. f4 exf4 32. Bxf4 h5 33. Rcd1 Qe7 34. Bxd6 Rxd6 35. e5 $18) 27... Bc8 28. Rd5 Ree8 29. Red1 $18 { The situation is very uncomfortable for Black. }) 27. Rcd1 { Applying pressure on the open file. } 27... Ree8 (27... Rce8 28. Nh2 Bc8 29. Ng4 $18 { White's attack is strong. }) 28. Nh2! { The Knight wants to attack the black squares f6 and h6. Ng5 looks strong, but Black has Nc6-d8 ready to recapture on e6 and defend against the mate on g7. } 28... Qd8 { Trying to exchange Queens. } (28... Rcd8 { A much better defense because now the Bishop can retreat. } 29. Ng4 Bc8 30. Rd5 Qe7 31. Red1 Qxf6 32. Nxf6+ Kh8 33. Nxe8 Rxe8 34. Rd6 $18) 29. Ng4 { White is threatening to win a piece. 30.Qxd8 Re8xd8 31.Nf6+ Kh8 32.Nxd7+- } 29... Qe7? (29... Rc7 30. f4 { The threat of 31.f5 is too much. } 30... Qxf6 (30... Qe7 31. f5 gxf5 32. exf5 Bc8 33. Re3! Rb7 34. Rg3 Qxf6 { Forced. } 35. Nxf6+ Kh8 36. fxe6 fxe6 (36... Rd8 37. Bg7#) 37. Nxe8 Rf7 38. Rf1 Rf4 39. Nf6! Rxf6 40. Rxf6 Ne7 41. Rf8+ Ng8 42. Rfxg8#) 31. Nxf6+ Kh8 32. f5 Nf4 33. Bxf4 exf4 34. Nxd7 $18) (29... a5 30. Qxd8 Rexd8 31. Nf6+ Kh8 32. Nxd7) (29... Re7 30. Be3 h5 (30... Re8?? 31. Nh6+ Kf8 32. Qxf7#) 31. Nh6+ Kh7 32. Nf5 { [%cal Rf6g7] } (32. Nxf7 Qf8 33. Ng5+ Nxg5 34. Qxg5 { [%csl Rd6] } 34... Rg7 35. Rd5 Qe7 36. Qh6+ Kg8 37. Red1) 32... gxf5 33. exf5 Nf4 34. Rd6 Qf8 35. Bxf4 exf4 36. Rxe7 Nxe7 { [%cal Rc2h7] } 37. Rxd7 Re8 38. Rxe7 Rxe7 39. Qxe7 Qxe7 40. f6+ $18) (29... Qxf6 30. Nxf6+ Kh8 31. Rxd7) 30. Qxe7 { Black resigns. He loses a piece. For example... } 30... Rxe7 31. Nf6+ Kh8 32. Nxd7 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


