{ -
In a French Defense, Tarrasch Variation Closed, Black does not play energetically enough with his counter-attack in the center. He also castles into a kingside attack. White blows away the kingside with a Bishop sacrifice, which Black accepts, and mate is forced in 4 moves.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siegbert_Tarrasch
- }
1. e4 e6 { French Defense
-
Tarrasch in "The game of Chess" :
I cannot consider 1...e6 an adequate reply to 1.e4. 1...e5 is, theoretically and practically, the only completely satisfactory answer to 1.e4.
See here for my notes on the Classical School
https://lichess.org/forum/team-jomegas-tabia/the-schools-of-chess?page=2#17
- } 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { Tarrasch Variation. Named after the player of the White pieces!
Avoids the Winawer Variation. } (3. Nc3 Bb4 { Winawer Variation
Very complex. See Nimzowitch and Botvinnik as early adopters.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Defence#Winawer_Variation:_3...Bb4 }) (3. exd5 exd5 4. c4) 3... Nf6 { -
Tarrasch Variation, Closed Variation
In the fourth printing Chernev thought this move was bad because the Knight gets displaced immediately. He recommended the immediate ...c5. In later editions the comment changed and Chernev says what the point of ...Nf6 is.
Here is a good example of the Classical School player (early Chernev) not liking the Hypermodern idea of tempting White's pawn to e5 where it will be attacked. We saw a similar idea in the last game in a Ruy. The exemplar for this idea is Alekhine's Defense. Yet later Chernev changed his mind and changed the comment in the book.
- } (3... c5 { The immediate ...c5 attacks the d4-pawn and gives Black's Queen the d8-a5 diagonal. } { [%cal Rd8a5,Rc5d4] } 4. Ngf3 (4. e5 { The advance e5 here looks bad because Black gets to take on d4 immediately. } 4... cxd4 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Nb3 Qc7 { White has to recover his pawn and defend his e5-pawn. } { [%cal Rc7e5,Rc6e5,Gf3e5] } 7. Bb5 { Defending by pinning. } { [%cal Rb5e8,Rc7e5,Rc6e5,Gf3e5] } (7. Nbxd4 Nxe5 8. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5c7,Rc7e8,Rc7a8] } 8... Qb8 9. Bf4 { [%cal Rf4b8] } 9... Nd3+ { [%cal Rb8f4,Rd3e1] } 10. Qxd3 Qxf4 { [%cal Rb5c7,Rc7e8,Rc7a8,Gf4c7] } 11. g3 Qb4+ { [%cal Rb4e1] } 12. c3 Qa5 { [%cal Ga5c7] } 13. Bg2 a6 14. Nbd4 Nf6 15. O-O Bd6 16. Rfe1 O-O { White has a lead in development for a pawn. }) 7... Bd7 8. Qe2 $17 { Black has the initiative. } { [%cal Gf3e5,Ge2e5,Rc6e5,Rc7e5] }) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. c4) 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3 c5 { Black immediately starts the process of attacking White's center pawns. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } 6. c3 { [%cal Rc5d4,Gc3d4] } 6... Nc6 { Threatening 7...cxd4 which would win a pawn. } { [%cal Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Gc3d4] } 7. Ne2 { [%cal Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Gc3d4,Ge2d4] } (7. Ngf3 { This is playable, though Chernev does not like it. } 7... Qb6 8. O-O cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nf3 Qb6 12. Qa4 { [%cal Ga2a3,Gc1e3,Ga1c1] }) 7... Qb6 { Black keeps pouring on the attackers. } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rc5d4,Rb6d4,Gc3d4,Ge2d4] } (7... cxd4 { Black can capture right now on d4. } 8. cxd4 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 { Both sides have a weak pawn. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge6] }) 8. Nf3 { Matching the number of attackers. } { [%cal Rb6d4,Rc6d4,Gf3d4,Ge2d4,Gc3d4] } 8... Be7? { Instead, 8...c5xd4 so Black gets counter-play. Yet this position has occurred in many master games. In Chessbase's Power 2009 DB it is listed as being played 3% of the games with a White "score" of 54.5%. } (8... cxd4 { White cannot avoid ending up with fixed pawns on d4/e5. } 9. cxd4 (9. Nexd4? Ndxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 $17) 9... f6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 10. exf6 Nxf6 { Both players have a weak pawn. }) 9. O-O O-O? { -
Black's King was not in danger in the center because the center was locked. So Black just castled into an attack.
The Lichess master DB does not make sense. Prior to 9...O-O it has no White wins out of 3 games, but after the move the stats list 4 games which have 2 games with Nf4, one a draw and one a Black win, one game with Bc2, a White win, and one came with Re1, a draw.
- } (9... f6? { Chernev says White missed his last chance to play 9...f6, but Black cannot play that here. } 10. Nf4 { Now how does Black defend? } { [%cal Rf4e6] } 10... Kf7? (10... Nf8? 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Nh4 { Threatening Qg4 or Qh5+ both winning. } 12... cxd4 13. Qh5+ Kd8 14. Qf7 { Threatening Qg7. } 14... e5 $18 { White wins with either 15.Nxd5 or 15.Qg7. }) (10... fxe5 { Stockfish wants to play this. } 11. Nxe6 $18 { Black's position is terrible. }) 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Re1 $18) (9... h6 10. a3 a5 11. Be3 a4 12. Rb1 Qa5 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Be3 Qa5 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Ng3 Nb6 17. Qe2 Na5 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Nh5 g6 20. Nf6+ Kf8 21. Nd4 Nbc4 22. Bf4 Be7 23. Bg3 Qd8 24. Bh4 Qb6 25. Kh1 Nc6) 10. Nf4 { Stopping 10...f6 because now the e6 pawn is attacked. } { [%cal Yf7f6,Rf4e6] } (10. Bc2 { Another idea for a kingside attack is the following. } 10... f5 11. Nf4 Nd8 12. h4 Qc7 13. g4 cxd4 (13... g6?? 14. gxf5 gxf5 15. Kh1 Rf7 16. Rg1+ $18 { With a winning attack. }) 14. cxd4) 10... Nd8? { Why relieve the pressure on d4? Chernev remarks that Black's move protects e6 so that Black can play ...f6. } { [%cal Rf7f6] } (10... cxd4 { Let's see what this move does at this point. } 11. cxd4 { Now Black cannot exchange twice on d4 because that would lose the Queen. } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rb6d4,Gf3d4,Gd1d4,Gd3h7] } 11... Re8 (11... Nb4 { This expedition with the Knight comes to nothing. } 12. Bb1 Bd8 { Stockfish's recommendation. } (12... f6? { This advance does not work here. } 13. a3 Nc6 (13... fxe5 14. Nxe5 Nc6 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 16. Qh5 { Threatening mate in two. } 16... g6 { White now has two interesting sacrifices to consider. 17.Nxg6 is much better. } 17. Nxg6 { Threatening mate in 4. This sacrifice offer cannot be accepted. } { [%cal Rg6e7] } (17. Bxg6? hxg6 18. Qxg6+ Kh8 19. Qh5+ Kg8 20. Nxe6 (20. Ng6? Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4h8] } 21. Nxf8 Bxf8 $19) 20... Bxe6 21. Qg6+ $10 { White draws by 3-time repetition. }) 17... Rf7 (17... hxg6?? 18. Qxg6+ Kh8 19. Qh7# { [%cal Rb1h7] }) 18. Nxe7+ Nxe