{ -
After Black's 8th move the position is best thought of in opening theory terms as a Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Classical Variation: Reversed. White has an extra tempo over Black in the Dragon. White fails to use that tempo to best advantage. At move 12 White continues his idea to own the c5-square, but in the process allows Black a kingside attack. White then compounds his kingside problems by exchanging his light-squared Bishop that could have defended the kingside. White makes a passive defense with his Queen and Black plays the standard f5-f4 attack in such positions. White's pawn cover for the King is torn away and White cannot prevent mate.
- }
1. c4 { English Opening
But this soon becomes another opening entirely. } (1. e4 { -
In order to understand better the position that arrives in the game, it is very helpful to know the Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Classical Variation.
- } 1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 (2... g6 { B27 Sicilian Defense: Hyperaccelerated Dragon } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nb3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 { Position A; White to move.
We have transposed to the Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Classical Variation. }) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be2 Bg7 { Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Classical Variation } 7. O-O O-O 8. Nb3 Nc6 { Position A; White to move. } 9. Bg5 { One idea of this move is to follow with Qd2 and use the Bishop-Queen battery to remove the Black King Bishop. If Black avoids that with ...Re1 then he has removed the Rook's protection from f7. } 9... h6 (9... Be6 { [%csl Rc4] } 10. Qd2 a5 { In the game here, White could have had this position (colors reversed) without the Queen on d2 and so could play the a-pawn to attack the Knight. This would have been a good use of the extra tempo White gains from playing this opening reversed. } { [%csl Rb3] } (10... Re8?! { Not in either DB. } 11. f4 Rc8 12. f5) 11. a4 (11. Bh6 { Stockfish does not like this. } 11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 a4 13. Nd2 a3 14. b3 Nd4 15. Bd1 Qa5 $17) 11... Rc8 12. Rad1 Nb4 { Threatening ...Rxc3. } 13. Nd4 Bc4 14. Rfe1 Qb6 { The position is complex. }) 10. Bh4 Be6 { In the game here, White will have the Black position with the move, and so could have played the g-pawn up. This would have been a good use of the extra tempo White gains from playing this opening reversed. } 11. f4 { Stopping ...g5. }) 1... e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 { English: Carls-Bremen system
White plays for control of d5. Note the Queen Knight eyes the square as does the c4 pawn. Now White plans to have his King Bishop train on the square also.
The position is a reversed Sicilian.
- } 3... d5 { [%cal Rd5d4] } 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 { -
Now this is a reversed accelerated Sicilian Dragon! Also known as the English Opening: Four Knights Variation with 4.g3.
White threatens to win the Knight.
Wikipedia: Initiative in a chess position belongs to the player who can make threats that cannot be ignored, thus putting the opponent in the position of having to spend turns responding to threats rather than creating new threats.
- } { [%cal Rg2d5,Rc3d5,Gd8d5] } 5... Nb6 { Keeping an eye on d5 and c4. Black has moved the Knight 3 times. } { [%cal Rb6c4,Rb6d5] } 6. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5 pawn. } { [%cal Rf3e5] } 6... Nc6 { Hence the reason this is called the Four Knights Variation. Black's last move defends his King pawn which was under attack. } { [%cal Rf3e5,Gc6e5] } 7. O-O { Safety for the King. } 7... Be7 { Black wants to Castle kingside, so the Bishop needs to be moved. From e7 the Bishop helps guard the dark squares on the kingside and keeps an eye on c5. } 8. d3 { Frees the Queen Bishop and puts pressure on c4 and e4. } 8... O-O { Safety for the King.
The position is the same as in the
Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Classical Variation with colors reversed. That is, this is Position A reversed; White to move. As would be expected for playing a reversed opening as White, White is a tempo ahead.
I covered this pawn formation here:
Intermediate: (Soltis) Pawn Structures
