https://lichess.org/study/B5upGe9A/yX0Or4Lz
- } 9. Be3 { Similar to the Sicilian Dragon, White will try to control c5. } 9... Bg4 { This Bishop, with support from his Queen, could try to trade for the Bishop on g2. } 10. h3?! { Attempting to make the Bishop trade for the Knight or leave. But this move creates a weakness, so White needs to be very careful. Better is to continue the queenside activity. Instead, a4 would be a good use of the extra tempo White has in this reversed opening. } { [%cal Rh3g4] } (10. a4 a5 { Stopping a5. } (10... Qd7? { The same position one can reach (colors reversed) in the Dragon, but now it is White's move and he can play a5. }) 11. Nd2 Qd7 12. Bxb6 cxb6 13. Nc4 { [%cal Rc4b6] } 13... Qe6 14. Bd5 Qf5 15. Nxb6 Rad8 16. Nc4 { Solak, Dragan - Papadopoulos, Ioannis, 1-0, Athens Acropolis op, 2006, https://lichess.org/9RWguRL3 }) (10. d4? Bxf3 { Starting a fireworks display. } (10... Nc4 { Chernev's idea. But he did not mention 11.d5!. } 11. d5! N6a5 (11... Nxb2? 12. Qc2 $18 { Now both Black Knights are in trouble. })) 11. Bxf3 exd4 12. Bxc6 dxc3 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bf3 cxb2 15. Rb1 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Bf6 17. Bf4 Na4 18. Rd2 Nc3 19. Rbxb2 Nxe2+ 20. Rxe2 Rxb2 21. Rxb2 Bxb2 22. Bxc7 $19 { Black is up the exchange. }) (10. Na4 { Chernev's suggestion to swing the Knight to c5. He gave no variations. } 10... Qd7 (10... Qc8 11. Rc1 Rd8 12. Rxc6 { A common sacrifice of the exchange in the Dragon. } 12... bxc6 13. Nxe5 Bh3 14. Nxc6 Re8 15. Nxe7+ Rxe7 16. Nc3 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 { Black has a Rook versus a Bishop and 2 pawns. }) 11. Nc5 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Rfe8 13. Re1 { To avoid the exchange of his King Bishop. }) 10... Bh5 { Continuing the pressure. The usual move with colors reversed is ...Be6. } 11. Rc1 { White should consider g4 here or the next move as a possibly good use of his extra tempo. } (11. g4 Bg6 $15 { The problem with 11.g4 is that it weakens the dark squares on the kingside. Also the pawns are targets for sacrificial attacks. On the plus side ... } 12. Rc1 f5 13. gxf5 Bxf5 14. d4 e4?! (14... exd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 c6 17. Qb3+ Kh8 18. Rfd1 $13) 15. Ne5 $16 { [%cal Rd1b3,Rb3g8,Re5f7,Rf7h8] }) (11. Kh2 { Chernev does not think this will suffice. He mentions this defense in a few moves. } 11... f5 { The usual attacking move in this position. }) (11. Qb3 { Chernev recommends this, with no variations, and the idea of playing Rad1 and advancing the d-pawn to get rid of the Black e-pawn. Of course, if Black had played 10...Be6, then White's Queen move would just hang the Queen. } { [%cal Rb3g8] } 11... Nd4 12. Bxd4 (12. Nxd4? exd4 $19) 12... exd4 13. Ne4 { Black's kingside attack has been stalled. }) 11... Qd7 { Attacking the h3 pawn (and developing the Queen). Yes, the pawn is guarded by the Bishop on g2, but that Bishop is also guarding the Knight on f3. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Rd7h3,Gg2h3,Rh5f3,Gg2f3] } 12. Na4? { Consistent with the plan to own c5, but White has missed the next Black move. } { [%cal Rg3g4,Ra4c5] } (12. g4 { [%cal Rg4h5] } 12... Bg6 $15) (12. Nd2 f5 { White will have to defend the kingside attack. } { [%cal Rf5f4] }) (12. Kh2 { This is where Chernev mentions Kh2 but without variations. He simply says that Black gets an attack by f5/f4. } { [%cal Gh2h3,Gg2f3,Rh5f3,Rd7h3] } 12... f5 13. Na4 f4 { [%cal Rf4e3] } 14. Nc5 { [%cal Rc5d7] } 14... Qd5 { Either this or the Queen retreats and then Bd2. } (14... Qc8 15. Bd2 { [%cal Rc5b7,Rg2b7,Rf3e5,Gc6e5] } 15... fxg3+?! { An obvious try to break up the kingside pawns. } 16. fxg3 { White is threatening 17.Nxb7, 17.Qb3+, and 17.b4. } 16... Bxc5 (16... a6 { A null move. } 17. Nxb7! Qxb7? 18. Nxe5 Rxf1 19. Qxf1 Qc8 20. Nxc6 $18) 17. Rxc5 $16) 15. Nd4 { With complications. } { [%cal Rg2d5] }) (12. Ne4 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxh3 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 f5 16. Bg2 Qg4) 12... Bxf3 { It is worth the Bishop for Knight trade to induce White into the coming trade of pawns. Black gets a kingside attack or White gets a very weak d-pawn. } 13. Bxf3 { To avoid weakening d3. } { [%cal Rf3c6,Rc1c6,Gb7c6,Gd7c6,Rd7h3] } (13. exf3 $17 { The d3 pawn is very weak. Black will quickly get the initiative by attacking it. } { [%csl Rd3] }) 13... Qxh3 { The close presence of the Queen has got to make White uncomfortable. Black temporarily wins a pawn, but that's not the point. The kingside attack is the point. } 14. Bxc6? { White wants to win his pawn back. But this is awful. The Bishop is needed to defend the kingside! } (14. Nc5! { White has compensation for the pawn. }) (14. Bg2 { Chernev likes this move because it banishes the Black Queen. } { [%cal Rg2h3] }) 14... bxc6 { Black is happy with the exchange. } 15. Rxc6 { Regains the pawn. } 15... Nd5 { Threatening 16...Nxe3 17.fxe3 Qxg3+ winning a pawn and continuing the attack. Notice that if White still had the Bishop sitting on f3 this Black Knight move would be met with Bxd5! } { [%cal Rd5e3,Gf2e3,Rh3g3] } 16. Qe1? { To guard g3. But this defense is too passive. } (16. Bc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Rab8 (17... Nf6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 { Chernev says that White would eventually lose. }) 18. Qd2 Nf6 19. Rxf6 { Necessary. White cannot allow the Knight to get to g4. } 19... gxf6 20. Rc1 Rb6 $17 { Black is up the exchange, but has an inferior pawn structure. }) 16... f5! { Planning to use the f-pawn to break up the White kingside.
Note Stockfish here has 17.Bc5 as the top move at -4.4, but after that move is made the evaluation changes to -26.5! } { [%cal Rf5f4] } (16... Nf4? 17. gxf4 Qg4+ 18. Kh2 exf4 19. Bd2 { Black has a draw or can play for a win. } (19. Bc5? Bxc5 20. Nxc5 Qh5+ 21. Kg1 { Looks to only be good for a draw. })) 17. Bc5?? { Removing the Bishop from attack when f4 comes. 17.Bd2 is also losing, but the game move is a blunder.
Stockfish evaluations are strange: 17...Bxc5 -26.5, 17...f4 -18.1 but after those moves are made the scores are -11.9 and -15.6 respectively. Horizon effect. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Rc5e7] } (17. Bd2 f4 { [%cal Rf8f5,Rf5h5,Rh3h1,Rh5h1] } 18. Nc3 { Stockfish gives 18...Nxc3 as the best move unless you ask for more than 3 lines. Then it finds 18...Rf5 and evaluates it as -14.4 at depth 21/21. After changing to the cloud, Stockfish finds 18...Rf5 is mate in 5. } 18... Rf5! { This Rook lift forces mate. } 19. Nxd5 { There is nothing better. } 19... Rh5 { [%csl Rh2,Rh1][%cal Rh5h2,Rh5h1] } 20. Nxe7+ Kh8 21. Ng6+ hxg6 { The spite checks are over. } 22. Bxf4 Qh2#) (17. Nc3? { Chernev says on this move that Black could play 17...Nf6 continuing the attack with ...Nh5. This is true. However, Stockfish likes 17...Nb4 and 17...Bb4 much better. } 17... Nb4 18. Rxc7 Nc2 19. Qc1 f4 20. Bxf4 (20. Bd2 Nd4 $19 { Threatening mate with ...f3. }) 20... exf4 21. Rxe7 Rf5 $19) 17... f4 { The pawn is ready to do its duty. } { [%cal Rf4g3,Rg3h2,Rh3h2,Re7c5,Gc6c5,Ga4c5,Gf2g3,Rd5e3,Re3g2,Rh3g2] } 18. Bxe7 { Trying to relieve some of the pressure by exchanging. } (18. g4?? { This allows mate in 3. } 18... f3 { [%cal Rh3g2,Rf3g2] } 19. exf3 Nf4 { [%cal Rh3g2,Rf4g2] } 20. d4 Qg2# { [%cal Rg2g1,Rf4g2] }) 18... fxg3 { Black does not need to recapture. Mate is now threatened. } { [%cal Rh3h2,Rg3h2] } 19. fxg3 { The only other move to avoid instant mate was the absurd 19.Rh6. } 19... Ne3 { White resigns. Black threatens 20...Qg2#. Here is a sample finale... } { [%cal Rh3g2,Re3g2] } 20. Rxf8+ (20. Rf2 Qxg3+ 21. Kh1 Rxf2 { [%cal Rf2h2,Rg3h2,Rg3g2] } 22. Qg1 Qh3+ 23. Qh2 Qxh2#) 20... Rxf8 { [%cal Re3g2,Rh3g2] } 21. Qf2 Rxf2 { [%cal Rh3h2,Rh3g2,Rf2g2,Re3g2] } 22. Kxf2 Nf5 { [%cal Rh3g3,Rf5g3] } (22... Qg2+ { Chernev gives this move, which wins the Rook. But Black can win the Rook *and* keep his Knight. } { [%cal Rg2f2,Rg2c6,Rf2e3] }) 23. Bc5 (23. Rxc7?? Qxg3+ 24. Kf1 Ne3# { [%cal Re3f1,Rg3g1,Rg3e1] }) 23... Qxg3+ 24. Kf1 Qh3+ 25. Kg1 (25. Ke1 Qh1+ 26. Kf2 Qxc6 $18) 25... Nh4 { [%cal Rh3g2,Rh4g2] } 26. Kf2 Qg2+ { [%cal Rg2c6,Rg2f2] } 27. Ke1 Qxc6 $18 0-1


[Event "Prague"]
[Date "1952.??.??"]
[White "Dobias"]
[Black "Podgorny"]
[Result "1-0"]
