{ -
In a French Defense: Rubinstein variation, Black gives up the center. Hence, Black has a cramped position. Black also has the usual problem in the French Defense of his Queen Bishop's development. In an attempt to untangle his pieces and remove one of the kingside attackers, Black trades a Knight, but this only brings White's Queen into the attack. Black attempts to solve the Queen Bishop's problem with a fianchetto. White's attack on the kingside forces weakening pawn moves there. White then cracks open the e-file for his Rook. The Rook both threatens a Rook lift and to remove a defender of the Knight which Black has guarding the mate on h7. White's attack on the g6 pawn and a surprise attack on the Black Knight results in Black's defenses failing.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Dobi%C3%A1%C5%A1
https://www.chessgames.com/player/jiri_podgorny.html
- }
1. e4 e6 { French Defense. } 2. d4 { [%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge5,Gf5] } 2... d5 3. Nc3 { French: Paulsen variation } 3... dxe4 { French: Rubinstein variation } 4. Nxe4 { White's center is better because he has more space. } 4... Nd7 { To support the King Knight when it moves to f6 and to stay out of the way of the c-pawn which may need to advance. } { [%cal Rd7f6,Rg8f6] } (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 6. Nf3 Bd7? 7. Bd3 Bc6 8. Bg5 Bxf3 9. Qd2! Bxg2 (9... Qxd4?? { Chernev points out this trap that wins the Black Queen. } 10. Bb5+ $18) 10. Bxf6 Bxh1 11. Bh4 $18) 5. Nf3 { Knights before Bishops. This is clearly the best spot for this Knight here. } 5... Be7 { It is not clear why Black prefers to play the Bishop move before the King Knight move. Black may be trying to force a particular line. } (5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { The usual line. }) (5... b6?! 6. Bb5 Bb7 7. Ne5 c6 (7... Bxe4? 8. Bxd7+ Ke7 9. Bc6 $18) (7... Bc8?? 8. Qh5 (8. Bg5 Nf6 (8... Be7 9. Nc6 $18) 9. Nc6 $18 { Chernev }) 8... Qe7 9. Bg5 Nf6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nc6 $18) 8. Nxc6 Qc7 9. Qf3 a6 10. Ne5 axb5 11. Qxf7+ Kd8 12. Ng5 Bd5 13. Nxe6+ Bxe6 14. Qxe6 Nxe5 15. Qd5+ Nd7 16. Qxa8+ Qc8 17. Qf3 $18) 6. Bd3 { A fine square for the Bishop. Protects the Knight and points toward the coming location of the Black King. } 6... Ngf6 { Finally. } { [%cal Re4f6,Gd7f6] } 7. Qe2 { Perhaps White avoids playing Nxf6 just to annoy Black who seems to have been preparing for just that move. } 7... O-O { It would take Black quite a few moves to Castle on the queenside and would not make much sense because he will need to advance those queenside pawns for counter-play. } { [%csl Rc8] } 8. O-O { White Castles before starting his kingside attack. } (8. Bg5 Nxe4? (8... Nd5 { Much better. }) 9. Qxe4 g6 10. h4 $16 { Chernev }) 8... Nxe4? { Black is trying to untangle his pieces. However this exchange helps the White Queen begin the kingside attack. Much better would have been to finish development. Better would be 8...b6 or 8...c5. } (8... b6 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. Bg5 Bb7 $14) (8... c5 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 $16) 9. Qxe4 { Threatening mate on h7. } { [%cal Rd3h7] } 9... Nf6 { Stops the mate and attacks the Queen. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Bg8h7,Bf6h7,Bf6e4] } (9... Re8?? 10. Qxh7+ Kf8 11. Qh8#) 10. Qh4 { Starting to attack on the kingside. } { [%csl Rc8] } 10... b6 { Attempting to solve the problem of developing his Queen Bishop. } { [%cal Re4a8] } (10... Nd5?? 11. Qxh7#) (10... Qd5 11. Ne5 (11. Bxh7+ Nxh7 12. Qxe7 $16)) (10... Re8 11. Ne5 g6 $16 (11... c5? 12. dxc5 Bxc5? 13. Rd1 $18)) 11. Bg5 { Threatening Bxf6 and Black could not recapture because of the mate threat on h7. } { [%cal Rg5f6,Yd3h7,Yh4h7] } 11... g6 { Stopping the threat, but creating weak dark squares. The Black Knight has lost a defender. } { [%csl Rh6,Rf6,Rg7] } (11... h6? 12. Bxh6 (12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qe4 { [%cal Rd3h7,Re4a8] } 13... g6 14. Qxa8 $18) 12... gxh6 13. Qxh6 Bb7? (13... Ba6 14. Bxa6 Ng4 15. Qf4 f5 16. Bc4 Bd6 17. Qd2 Qf6 18. h3 Nh6 19. Rae1 Rae8 20. Ng5 Kh8 21. Nxe6 Rg8 22. Nd8 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Qg5 (23... Rxd8 24. Re6 $18) (23... Qxd8?? 24. Qxh6#) 24. Qxg5 Rxg5 25. Re8+ Kh7 26. g3 $18) 14. Rae1 Bd6? 15. Re5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 { Chernev: The Knight date not move...
jomega: What? Chernev missed 16...Ne4. } 16... Ne4 $10) 12. c4! { Pressure on d5 which takes away any idea Black might have had of playing his Knight there. } { [%cal Rd4d5,Rd5e6,Gf7e6,Gf7g6,Yf1e1,Ye1e8] } 12... Bb7 { Grabbing the long diagonal. } 13. d5! { On the surface this just seems to lose a pawn. White hopes Black will open the e-file. } { [%cal Re6d5,Rf6d5,Rb7d5,Rd8d5] } 13... exd5? { This opens the Bishop to attack. The Bishop is guarding the Knight. The Knight is guarding h7. } (13... Re8 14. Rfe1 (14. dxe6 fxe6 $14 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rad1 Nd7 17. Qh6 Be4 18. Rd4 Bxg5 19. Nxg5 Qe7 20. Nxe4 Nf8 21. Rd3 Qg7 22. Qf4 $18) 14... Nh5 $14 { Black may survive. }) 14. Rfe1 { White is threatening Rxe7 and if Black takes the Rook with the Queen then Bxf6 Q-moves and then White wins. Example... } { [%cal Re1e7,Gd8e7,Rh4f6,Yh4h6,Yg5f6,Yf6g7,Yh6g7] } 14... h6 { Black hopes to return the pawn and force some exchanges. } (14... a6 { Null move. Just to show the White threat if Black plays a meaningless move. } 15. Rxe7 Qxe7 16. Bxf6 Qd6? 17. Ng5 h5 18. Qxh5! gxh5 19. Bh7#) (14... h5 15. Rxe7 Qxe7 16. Bxf6 Qd7 17. Qg5 Qd6 18. Bxg6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 fxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Ng5 Rf7 22. Nxf7#) (14... Kg7 15. Bh6+ (15. Nd4 { Threatening Nf5+. } 15... h5 (15... a6 { Null move. } 16. Nf5+ Kg8 (16... gxf5 17. Qh6+ Kg8 18. Bxf5 Re8 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. Bg6+ Kg8 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Qxf7#)) 16. Bxg6 Kxg6 17. Re5 Rg8 18. Bf4 { Threatening mate in 2. } 18... Rg7 19. Nf5 Bf8 20. Ng3 { Threatening Rxh5 and mate in 4. } 20... Kh7 21. Nxh5 Kg8 22. Nxf6+ Qxf6 23. Qxf6 $18) 15... Kg8 16. Bxf8 Bxf8 $16 { White is up the exchange for a pawn. }) 15. Qxh6 { White is threatening Bxg6 with a winning attack. } { [%cal Rd3g6,Gf7g6,Rh6g6,Ye1e5,Ye5h5] } 15... Ng4 { Attacking the Queen. But the Knight is not defended. } { [%cal Rg4h6] } (15... Ne4 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. cxd5 f5 (17... Bxd5? 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 Qxe4? 20. Ng5 $18 { Threatening mate and the Black
Queen. }) 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Qxg6+ Qg7 20. Qxe4 $18) 16. Qh4 { Attacking the Knight and the Bishop. } { [%cal Rh4e7,Gd8e7] } 16... Bxg5 { Forced to keep from losing a piece. } (16... Nf6 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Bxf6 $18) 17. Nxg5 { Now White threatens mate in 1. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rg5h7,Rh4h7] } 17... Nf6 { Stopping the mate for now. Black is in big trouble. } { [%cal Gf6h7] } (17... Kg7 18. Qh7+ Kf6 19. Nxf7 { Threatening Qxg6#. } { [%cal Re1e8] } 19... Ne5 20. Nxe5 Ke6 21. Nf7+ Kd7 22. Nxd8+ Kxd8 23. Qe7+ Kc8 24. Qxf8+ Kd7 25. Qe7+ Kc6 26. Re6#) 18. Qh6 { Double attack on g6 and perhaps mate on h7 if the Knight was not there. } { [%cal Rd3g6,Rh6g6,Gf7g6,Rh6f8] } 18... d4?? { Missing the next shot. } { [%cal Rd4e3,Ye1e3,Ye3h3] } (18... Qd7 { To stop Re6. } 19. Re3 dxc4 20. Bxc4 { Now White is threatening 21.Qxg6+ and Black cannot capture
the Queen because the pawn is pinned. Black would be mated in a few moves. } { [%cal Rc4g8] } 20... Qf5 21. Rg3 (21. Rh3? Qxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Ng4+ 23. Kg1 Nxh6 24. Rxh6 $18 { White's
winning but that was embarrassing. }) 21... Rab8 22. Bd3 Qd5 23. Ne6! { Threatening Qg7#. If Black takes the Knight with the pawn, then Rxg6#. } 23... Qxe6 24. Bxg6! { Mate in 4. Black can only throw away pieces to delay. } 24... Qg4 25. Bh7+ Kh8 (25... Nxh7 26. Rxg4+ Ng5 27. Rxg5#) 26. Bf5+ Kg8 (26... Nh7 27. Qxh7#) 27. Rxg4+ Nxg4 28. Qh7#) (18... Re8? 19. Bxg6 Rxe1+ (19... fxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kf8 (20... Kh8 21. Nf7#) 21. Qf7#) 20. Rxe1 fxg6? (20... Qf8 21. Bh7+ Kh8 22. Qxf6+) 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Nf7#) 19. Re6! { Threatening 20.Rxf6 and quick mate. } { [%cal Re6f6,Yg5h7,Yh6h7] } 19... Re8 { Trying to escape with the King. } (19... fxe6 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ Nh7 (21... Kg8 22. Bh7+ Nxh7 (22... Kh8 23. Bf5+ Nh7 (23... Kg8 24. Bxe6+ Rf7 25. Bxf7#) 24. Qxh7#) 23. Qxh7#) 22. Qxh7#) 20. Bxg6! { Black resigned. White threatens
21.Bxf7# and 21.Bh7+ Nxh7 22.Qxh7+ Kf8 23.Qxf7#. } { [%cal Rg6f7,Rg5f7,Rg6h7,Rh6h7,Rg5h7,Gf6h7] } 20... Qd7 { [%cal Gd7f7] } (20... fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Nf7# { [%cal Rf7h8,Rg6h7,Rg6g7,Rg6g8] }) 21. Bh7+ Kh8 (21... Nxh7 22. Qxh7+ Kf8 23. Qh8# { [%cal Re6e7,Rh8f8] }) 22. Qxf6# 1-0


[Event "Berlin"]
