{ -
As in the last game we have a French Defense: Rubinstein variation, Blackburne Defense. White plays 7.O-O instead of 7.Qe2 as Dobias played in the last game. This allowed Black to untangle his pieces somewhat with 7...Nxe4 without the negative consequences in the last game. Yet Black attempts to fianchetto his Queen Bishop and in so doing weakens his queenside. White's Ne5 stops that plan. Black castles and White takes the opportunity to use the weakened queenside square c6 to force an exchange that gives him the two Bishops. By move 14, Black is tied up and cramp. Black clearly missed White's reply when Black removed his Queen from guarding his King Knight. White locks down the Black King, and a Rook lift effectively ends the game as Black's Queen alone cannot defend against mate.
-
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siegbert_Tarrasch
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Mieses
