1. e4 e6 { French Defense } { [%csl Rc8] } 2. d4 { [%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge5,Gf5] } 2... d5 3. Nc3 { Paulsen Variation } { [%cal Rd5e4,Bc3e4] } (3. exd5 { French Defense: Exchange Variation } 3... exd5 { Finegold says in one of his lectures that he likes the Exchange Variation as White. The position is symmetrical and White has the first move. }) (3. e5 { French Defense: Advance Variation
This move was hotly debated in Tarrasch's time. While the e5-pawn cramps Black's game by preventing ...Nf6, White's center pawns are now immobile and subject to attack. }) (3. Nd2 { French Defense: Tarrasch Variation
This move protects the e4-pawn and avoids the Winawer. }) 3... dxe4 { -
Tarrasch disapproved of any opening where Black gave White the advantage we now call "pawn on 4th versus pawn on third". Tarrasch called this "giving up the center". Nimzowitsch disagreed that Black was necessarily giving up the center in all such cases. See "My System" by Nimzowitsch for a discussion. Also my study:
Intermediate: Control of the Center
https://lichess.org/study/mj8UtUBc
In that study I also discuss the feud between Tarrasch and Nimzowitsch.
- } (3... Bb4 { French Defense: Winawer Variation
A very complex line. }) 4. Nxe4 Nd7 { French Defense: Rubinstein variation, Blackburne Defense } (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ gxf6 { Better than the natural ...Qxf6. } (5... Qxf6 { We looked at this trappy line last game. } 6. Nf3 Bd7? 7. Bd3 Bc6?? { This attempt to develop the Queen's Bishop fails to tactics. } 8. Bg5 { Trapping the Black Queen. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rd3h7,Rg5d8,Rg5h6,Rg5f4] } 8... Bxf3 9. Qd2! { A zwischenzug that guards the g5-Bishop. } 9... Bxg2 (9... Qxd4?? 10. Bb5+ $18 { Winning the Black Queen. }) 10. Bxf6 Bxh1 11. Bh4 $18) 6. Nf3 $16) 5. Nf3 Ngf6 { [%cal Re4f6,Bd7f6] } 6. Bd3 Be7 { -
This is the same position as in the previous game by transposition.
- } 7. O-O { King safety. Less aggressive than Qe2 as played in the previous game. } 7... Nxe4 { Untangling his pieces. Unlike the previous game, White does not have Qxd4 so this move is often played by masters. } (7... O-O 8. Qe2 b6 (8... c5)) 8. Bxe4 { Black is not losing time because White has moved the Bishop twice and will move it yet again. } 8... Nf6 { Placing the Knight on a good square and attacking the Bishop. } { [%cal Rf6e4] } 9. Bd3 { -
White simply retreats. He wants to keep his Bishop for the attack. If you count tempi, White is still ahead by one tempo. Tarrasch had elaborate rules for counting tempi in the opening as did Nimzowitsch.
See my study:
Tempo Counting in the Opening
https://lichess.org/study/mj8UtUBc/2VtFeXfm
- } 9... b6 { Preparing to fianchetto the Queen's Bishop. But this weakens the white squares on the queenside. Black should have castled. His King is on a white square. White can now apply pressure on these white squares.
As we noted in a variation in the last game, this move also weakens the diagonal h1-a8 leading to Black's Rook, which is undefended. } { [%csl Ra6,Rc6] } (9... O-O { Modern opening theory gives this line. } 10. Ne5 c5 $16) (9... c5) 10. Ne5! { A fine outpost for the Knight and applies pressure on c6. } 10... O-O? { The planned fianchetto does not work. Like it or not Black should have played 10...Bd7. } (10... Bb7 11. Bb5+ Kf8 $14 { Black can no longer Castle. }) (10... Bd7 $16 { White's position is better because his pieces are more active. }) (10... Qxd4?? { Losing the Queen to a discovered attack.
General rule: If you are about to move a piece to a square where it will be unguarded, look for tactics that might win it.
General rule: Pay attention to indirect attacks. Such attacks should be part of your static tactical analysis via the A/D network. } { [%cal Rd1d4,Rd3b5] } 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 $18) 11. Nc6 { -
Invading on the white-square weakness. The point of this is to do away with the Bishop on e7 as it protects the Knight which is defending the Black kingside. Also, White gets the Bishop pair.
A novice likes making this kind of move just because the Knight is attacking Black Queen. The hope being that Black will just overlook the attack. You should not play chess this way. Always assume your opponent will play his best move.
- } { [%cal Rc6e7] } 11... Qd6 { -
The Queen moves; of course. Novices seem to like Knights better than Bishops; regardless of the position. Masters prefer to have the two Bishop. However, every position needs to be judged both statically and dynamically to figure out whether the Knights or Bishops are better.
- } 12. Qf3! { -
Before taking the Bishop, White plays this move which forces the Black Queen Bishop to the less desirable d7 square.
Notice the threat of 12.Nxe7+ Qxe7 13.Qxa8. As we discussed a few moves ago, the Black Queen Rook is undefended and tactics can occur where the Rook becomes the target.
General rule: Undefended pieces are often the target of winning tactics.
- } 12... Bd7 { The h8-Rook is now protected, but the plan to put the Bishop on b7 has been thwarted. } { [%cal Bf8a8,Rf3a8] } (12... Bb7?? { It is easy to see from the A/D network that White will win a piece. } { [%cal Rc6e7,Re7g8,Rf3b7,Bd6e7] } 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Qxb7 $18 { Winning a piece. }) (12... Nd5?? { -
This position takes a slightly more complex A/D network to discover that White will win material. The point is still the undefended a8-Rook, hence Black's Knight will get pinned. Notice again the importance of the indirect attacks. The arrow from the White Queen (the Queen's attacks) is drawn all the way to the edge of the board. Hence, the strong player sees White winning material here without calculating. It is not that he cannot calculate; if he has time he will. He will check for zwischenzugs, and other defenses that would spoil the normal pattern of piling on a pinned piece.
- } { [%cal Rc6e7,Re7g8,Bd6e7,Rf3a8,Yc2c4] } 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 { [%cal Rf3a8] } (13... Nxe7?? 14. Qxa8 $18 { Wins a Rook. And if Black plays Ba6 then White can simplify with Bxh7. } 14... Ba6 { [%cal Rf8a8] } 15. Bxh7+! { Queen retreats also win. White's tactical motif has several names; for example "removing the guard". } 15... Kxh7 16. Qxf8 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 Qxd4 { Sets a trap. It is all too easy after winning material to slip into a mode of "anything wins now" and not maintain your disciplined move selection process; including blunder checks. } { [%cal Rf8e7] } 18. g3 $18 { Luft. } (18. Qxe7?? { Minimally, always look at all the checks (and captures) as part of your blunder check. } 18... Qd1# { Ouch!! })) 14. c4 $18 { Attacking the pinned piece. White wins material. }) 13. Nxe7+ { Besides getting rid of the Bishop, the required recapture by the Queen puts the Queen in position to be behind the coming pin on the f6-Knight. } 13... Qxe7 { Required recapture. } 14. Bg5 { -
Pinning the Knight. With the fireworks over, it is a good time to summarize the position.
The pawn structure is the Caro formation. See
Intermediate: (Soltis) Pawn Structures:
https://lichess.org/study/B5upGe9A/SGzau8kg
It may not look like it, but if you're familiar with how the Soltis categories work, small changes to the pawn positions are usually not important. See the above study/chapter for the usual plans for both sides. Let's discuss the specific case we have in the game.
-
White has the pawn on 4th versus pawn on 3rd advantage. White's Knights have been exchanged and White has the two Bishops advantage. White's minor pieces are much better than Black's. Black's Knight cannot move because it is pinned, and his Bishop has little scope. Black's Queen cannot stop guarding the Knight because White would break up the kingside pawns (and currently win a pawn in the process). What should the plans be for each side?
-
As was said in the above study, Black should aim to strike at the White center. Candidate moves for this are the eventual ...c5 or ...e5. White's usual plan would be to make use of the e5-outpost and if his d-pawn is exchanged for Black's c-pawn, then White would have a queenside majority. However, it is clear in this position that White wants to attack kingside because of the strong pin, the attacking posture of his d3-Bishop and Queen, and the possibility of a Rook lift.
-
If both players are masters, they both know these things. Knowing these things gives the players just a few candidate moves; which greatly helps in the next phase of evaluating the position - to look at the position dynamically. That is, to calculate.
- } 14... Rac8 { Since the immediate ...c5 or ..e5 do not work, Black plays this move hoping for some counter-play with c5. This move also gets the Rook off the long diagonal, where it was attacked by the White Queen. } (14... h6 { -
This reflexive move would be the first candidate of most beginners, and the last for most masters! Why? Because beginners hope by this move to get rid of the pin. However, masters know that, in general, it is a "bad idea" to move the kingside pawns in front of a castled King. The move ...h6 undefends g6, and makes a target of the h-pawn. Also, it does not really unpin the Knight as White can respond Bh4, and then what is Black going to do? Well, the beginner would play ...g5, further weakening the kingside.
- } 15. Bh4 { This maintains the pin. } 15... g5 { Terrible! } 16. Bg3 { Despite material equality, Black's game is lost! Stockfish is giving White a score of 2.1 already. Here is an example ... } 16... Nd5 { Anticipating h4. } 17. c4 Nb4 18. Be4 { Gaining a tempo because of the weak queenside. } 18... Rae8 19. a3 Na6 { Sad. The best defender of the kingside is now on the edge of the board on the queenside! } 20. Bc2 { Anticipating ...f5. } 20... f5 21. Be5 { Note how White has made use of the e5-outpost. } 21... c6 { So as to get the Knight back in the game; the Knight was defending the c7-pawn. } 22. Qh3 Kh7 { If ...Qh7 then the f-pawn is still pinned. } 23. g4 Qf7 24. Rfe1 Rg8 25. Rad1 Nb8 26. d5 { Threatening to knock the support out from under the f5-pawn. } 26... cxd5 27. cxd5 exd5 28. gxf5 Nc6 29. Bc3 Rxe1+ 30. Rxe1 d4 31. Re6! { The continued threat of a discovered check is deadly. Now White is also threatening Qxh6#. } 31... h5 32. Rd6 { Now White is threatening, among other things, Rxd7, since the discovered check would then cause a discovered attack on the Black Queen. } 32... Be8 33. Rg6 { The threat is Qxh5#. } 33... Rg7 { Black defends as well as he can. } 34. Qxh5+ Kg8 35. Bd2 Ne5 { The Knight has finally returned. } 36. Rxg7+ Kxg7 37. f6+ Kg8 { Constantly having to find the best move is very tiring, Black was lost anyway. } 38. Bh7+ Kh8 (38... Kf8 { Instead, ...Kh8 walks into a discovered check. } 39. Qh6+ Qg7 40. Qxg7#) 39. Bg6+ Kg8 40. Bxf7+ Bxf7 41. Qh6 Nf3+ { Spite check. } 42. Kh1 Nxd2 43. Qg7#) (14... e5? { This would be one of the candidates Black would consider per the discussion. However, it fails to 15.Rae1, a pin, and so can be rejected. }) (14... c5? { This would be one of the candidates Black would consider per the discussion. However, after 15.dxc5, Black cannot retake with the Queen, so he would end up with weak queenside pawns. This candidate can be rejected. }) 15. Rfe1 { Grabbing the half-open file. A Rook lift to attack the kingside is coming. } (15. Qe4!? Nxe4 16. Bxe7 Rfe8 17. Bxe4 Rxe7 { Notice the Black Queen Rook is not on a8 or else this combination would have won for White. }) 15... Rfe8 { Black's pieces are cramped. This move might have been played with the idea to give the King an escape route. But c5 seems a better move. } (15... c5 { According to Tarrasch's notes he intended the
following lines against 15...c5 ... } 16. Qh3 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh3h7,Rd3h7,Rg5f6] } 16... h6 17. Bxh6 c4 (17... gxh6 18. Qxh6 cxd4 19. b4! { and then 20.Re5 with an easy win. }) 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qg3+ Kh8 20. Qh4+ Kg7 21. Qg5+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Re5? $18 { - Tarrasch, per Chernev. } (23. Re3 { This is the better move. } 23... Ne4 24. Rg3+ Qg5 { Prolonging mate. } 25. Rxg5+ Nxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kh8 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Qh7#)) 16. Qh3 { White applies more pressure on h7. } { [%cal Rh3h7,Rd3h7,Rg5f6] } 16... Qd6? { Black allows White to break up his kingside! Very strange! } (16... h6 { This is still better than the move Black played. } 17. Bxh6! gxh6 18. Qxh6 Qf8 19. Qh4 (19. Qxf6 $18) 19... Qg7 20. Re5 { Black is going to lose a least a piece. } 20... Nh7 21. Bxh7+ Qxh7 22. Rg5+ Kh8 (22... Kf8 23. Qxh7 $18) 23. Rh5 Qxh5 24. Qxh5+ Kg7 25. Re1 $18 { White wins because Black's King is exposed and Black cannot get effective counter-play with his pieces. }) (16... e5 { [%cal Rd7h3] } 17. Bxf6 Bxh3 18. Bxe7 Rxe7 19. gxh3 $18) (16... g6 17. Qh4 Kg7 18. Re4 Nxe4 19. Bxe7 f6 20. Qxe4 Rxe7 $18) 17. Bxf6 { Of course! The attack is winning. } 17... gxf6 { Did Black think that his King would now escape via f8 and e7? } 18. Qh6! { The Black King is going nowhere. Chernev thinks Black was hoping on Qxh7+ instead. White is threatening a standard mate in 4. } (18. Qxh7+? Kf8 { The Black King gets away. }) 18... f5 { Stopping Bxh7 which would lead to quick mate. } (18... a6 { Null move. } 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Bg6+ Kg8 21. Qh7+ Kf8 22. Qxf7#) 19. Re3 { The Rook lift we have been waiting for. Threatening Rg3+ and Black has to give up the Queen or get mated. } 19... Qxd4 { Not just to grab a pawn, but hoping to be able to guard g7 and avoid mate. } (19... f6 20. Rg3+ Kf7 (20... Kh8 21. Qxf6# { Chernev missed this. }) 21. Qg7#) 20. c3 { Black resigned. He has to give up the Queen or be mated.
Chernev said the game was awarded a brillancy prize. } (20. Rg3+ Kh8 (20... Qg4 21. Rxg4+ fxg4 22. Bxh7+ Kh8 23. Bg6+ Kg8 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Qxf7#) 21. c3! (21. Rh3?? Qg7 { The defense Black had in mind. }) 21... Qe5 22. f4 Qe3+ 23. Rxe3 Rg8 24. Qf6+ Rg7 25. Rg3 Rg8 { White can now win by applying more pressure or just simplifying. } 26. Rxg7 Rxg7 27. Qd8+ Rg8 28. Qxd7 $18) 20... Qc5 (20... Qg7 21. Rg3 $18 { Pinning the Queen. }) 21. Rg3+ Kh8 22. Qg7# 1-0


