[ChapterName "Reversed Openings"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dwrNFeej/VhQaz8lW"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[UTCDate "2020.07.26"]
[UTCTime "13:32:44"]

{ The list of ECO codes I have with attached names has 6 occurrences of the word "reversed". I've listed them here with the ECO code.
But there are many more openings that can be viewed as reversed openings. I've listed some.
What is the point you might wonder? It is sometimes possible to play an opening in reverse. If you are White you will have an extra tempo. Perhaps you can put that tempo to good use. If you are Black you'd be a tempo down, but perhaps it does not matter. Also, you may play the same system with both sides and so be familiar with the type of positions that occur. For example, playing the KIA and KID.
- }
1. g3 (1. e4 g5 { B00 Reversed Grob (Borg/Basman Defense/Macho Grob)
aka Borg Defense } (1... e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. Be2 { C00 French: Reversed Philidor formation })) (1. c4 c5 (1... e5 { Sicilian Reversed } 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 { A22 English: Bremen, Reverse Dragon
aka English Opening: King's English Variation: Two Knights Variation }) 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e3 e5 { A36/A37 English: Symmetrical, Botvinnik System Reversed }) (1. c3 { Saragossa Opening } 1... e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 { Center Counter Defense: Reversed } (3. cxd4 d5 4. Nf3 c5 { Caro-Kann: Panov-Botvinnik Attack: Reversed })) (1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c5 { King's Indian Defense: Reversed
aka King's Indian Attack }) 1... e5 2. Nf3 { A00 Benko's Opening: Reversed Alekhine
aka Hungarian Opening: Reversed Alekhine } *


