1. e4 { What hasn't been said about this, as a first move? As Bobby Fisher famously said, it is considered by many as "Best by test". It establishes a pawn in a central square and frees up both White's Queen and light-squares bishop (lsb). } { [%clk 119:58:41] } 1... c6 { The Caro-Kann is a really solid defence which gives winning chances to Black and that is why I eventually made my bed with it, after realizing that my initial choice - the Petrov - didn't suit my personality very well. Here, Black's response to White's goal of establishing a perfect pawn center with e4 and d4 is to prepare d5 (challenging e4) with the preliminary c6. But this move is not without its drawbacks, on of which being that is robs the Queen's Knight of its natural square. } { [%clk 119:39:01] } 2. d4 { [%clk 112:25:04] } 2... d5 { Black immediately challenges White's central pawn at e4 and forces him to make a decision that will lead to very different outcomes. Shall he capture, support or move forward? } { [%clk 116:32:38] } 3. e5 { I am not an "opening study" kind of guy but 3.e5 is known as the "Advance" variation of the Caro-Kann. So, now White has a space advantage in the centre and is cramping Black's style. White, having more space, can develop more freely. Black, having less space, has a harder time finding good squares for his pieces. I've already mentioned the fact that Black's Queen's Knight was robbed of its natural square by 1.c6. Now, Black's King's Knight has been robbed of its natural square by 3.e5. } { I know you said you are not an opening study guy, but if you play the Caro-Kann you are going to face the Advance variation and it might be good to look at the historic arguments (i.e. games and annotations) of the masters on this. Also, check out this video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vS_yagozyy4 } { [%clk 111:24:42] } 3... Bf5 { This is practically forced because Black's lsb risks being closed-in by his own pawn structure if he doesn't activate it quickly. } { ...c5 is popular! See the video link. } { [%clk 119:45:42] } 4. Nf3 { Develops White's Kingside Knight white supporting d4-pawn and preparing for castling. } { [%clk 117:06:01] } 4... e6 { This supports Bf5 and activates Black's dsb by opening up the a3-c8 file for it. } { [%clk 119:13:47] } 5. Be2 { White avoids 5.d3 and is careful not to give Black the chance of exchanging his "bad" bishop for White's "good" bishop. This is pretty much the extent of my "book knowledge" of the Advance variation of the Caro-Kann. } { The f5-Bishop may be technically bad, but it is active. Silman grades Bishop's as good/bad, active/inactive. } { [%clk 118:01:04] } 5... Qb6 { Here, Black's Qb6 puts pressure on both White's e4 and b2 pawns. I'm not sure this is the best move, if only because it develops the Queen before the minor pieces which is generally not a good idea as it often provides a nice target for the opponent, losing time escaping to safety while the other often moves with tempo. Better was probably 5...Nd7 } { I think you mean pressure on d4; not e4.
Black's plan should be to attack the White pawn chain. Hence, ...c5 immediately or ...Nd7 to prepare that. White then has three major threads of plan - either protect e5 with a pawn by c3 so as to recapture with a pawn, protect it with pieces, or attempt to play f4. Compare to the lines in the Advance French - the difference is that Black's QB is outside the pawn chain. } { [%clk 119:42:58] } 6. Nbd2 { I think this is the standard setup for White, though perhaps 0-0 comes first. I believe White's idea is Nb1-Nd2-Nb3 because this posting will gard the important c5 square. } { [%clk 119:43:15] } 6... h6 { 6...h6 provides a retreat for Black's vulnerable lsb which provide's a tasty target for White's kingside Bishop. Needless to say, Black has moved 4 pawns in 6 of his opening moves and is behind White in development. } { It was very important to play ...c5 now before White can play Nb3.
Black does not fear Bd3 or Nh4. See coming lines. } { [%clk 113:29:23] } (6... c5! 7. Bd3?! (7. Nh4 { Notice that if Black's Queen was still on d8 this Knight move of White's would not be possible. } 7... Be4! { Daring White to take the Bishop or play the weakening f3. } 8. Nxe4?! (8. f3? { Blocking his own KB and weakening the kingside. } 8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 $17 { Black's King is safe in the center for the moment. }) (8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O Nc6 { Black is threatening ...Nxe5. I think Black is ok here. }) 8... dxe4 { However White plays, Black gets the initiative. } 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O Nd7 $17) 7... Bxd3 8. cxd3 cxd4 { Whose pawn structure is better? Whose Bishop is better? Black!
White needs to regain material equality by capturing the d4-pawn. Black can finish development. }) 7. Nb3 { [%clk 109:34:27] } 7... c5 { Looking back at this, 7...c5 feels premature. I am gaining space on the Queenside but doing so at the cost of my development and king safety, not to mention the fact it took me two moves to reach c5, so there is an obvious loss of time here...But I'm feeling hemmed-in and need to create space so my pieces can have options... } { [%clk 119:10:24] } 8. dxc5 { [%clk 115:55:10] } 8... Bxc5 { [%clk 119:50:30] } 9. Nxc5 { [%clk 116:31:05] } 9... Qxc5 { I've lost the Bishop pair but the exchanges have left me with badly needed room and } { [%cal Gc5c2,Gf5c2,Gd1c2] [%clk 114:09:15] } 10. c3 { I'm not sure this is the best move for White who could have castled or developed his dsb to e3 with tempo against Black's Queen. } { But Black was threatening ...Bxc2 or ...Qxc2, so White cannot castle or play Be3 as they would lose material. } { [%clk 100:37:32] } 10... Ne7 { I'm certain I was quite happy to develop my kingside Knight and prepare to castle my king to safety } { [%clk 115:47:25] } 11. Be3 { [%clk 106:00:40] } 11... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7e5,Gf3e5] [%clk 117:25:40] } 12. Bb5+ { [%clk 117:00:32] } 12... Nec6 { Why not get the other Knight developed with ...Nbc6? Also, the KN was blocking the diagonal a3-f8, which stops the idea Bc5 if Black wants to castle. } { [%clk 114:56:55] } 13. Nd4 { Dropping the e-pawn. } { [%cal Gc7e5] [%clk 107:13:17] } 13... Bh7 { Missing the win of the e-pawn with ...Qxe5. } { [%clk 115:18:05] } (13... Qxe5 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. O-O O-O { White will be tempted to exchange a Bishop for a Knight to help win back the lost pawn. }) 14. O-O { [%clk 116:28:59] } 14... O-O { To me, White has more space in the centre and lines of attack on Black's kinside. White's e5 pawn prevents Black from posting a Knight on f6 and this isn't without consequence on its King's defensive position which is already weakened by the h-pawn having been moved. I'm fairly certain the engine will give White as being better, after 14...0-0 } { So why castle given all those things you said about White's kingside advantages? } { [%clk 116:29:46] } 15. Qg4 { Threatening Bxh6 } { We should investigate ...Qxe5. } { [%cal Gc7e5,Ge5g7] [%clk 99:48:56] } 15... Bg6 { Preventing the Bxh6 tactic, but losing a tempo in the doing. } { [%clk 116:56:38] } 16. Nxe6 { [%clk 104:10:56] } 16... Qd7 { Looking back at this, I don't like this move at all for many reasons. It is attacked by both White's lsb and its Queen and robs Black's queenside-Knight of the d7 square which it should normally develop to. } { But Black has to play ...Qd7 or ...Qc8 to keep from losing the exchange. } { [%clk 119:55:36] } 17. f4 { [%clk 119:34:53] } 17... fxe6 { I obviously lost focus here. These are correspondence games but I don't set them up on a board and deep-think every move. I typically play on my Iphone now and rarely spend more than a few seconds or minutes, at most, on a move. So, forgetting the obvious is par for the course for me. } { If you are only spending a few seconds on a move then why play correspondence? } { [%clk 104:54:10] } 18. Qxg6 { [%clk 116:37:16] } 18... Qf7 { [%clk 119:15:06] } 19. Qg3 { [%clk 108:53:17] } 19... b6 { Both sides are missing the tactics. } { [%cal Gf4f5,Ge3h6,Gg3g8] [%clk 117:23:51] } 20. Qf3 { [%clk 111:32:35] } 20... Ne7 { [%clk 119:56:59] } 21. c4 { [%clk 119:54:04] } 21... Nbc6 { Finally developing that Knight } { [%clk 119:02:12] } 22. Rfd1 { Adding pressure on Black's e5 pawn and ready to control the d-file should it open-up } { White should have played cxd5. That would give Black an isolani while giving White a passed e-pawn. } { [%clk 118:32:08] } (22. cxd5 exd5 { [%csl Gd5,Ge5] } (22... Nxd5?? 23. Bxc6)) 22... Rac8 { [%clk 119:03:13] } 23. cxd5 { [%clk 117:59:05] } 23... exd5 { Instead ...Nxd5 now that the c6-Knight is protected. } { [%clk 119:37:44] } 24. Ba4 { [%clk 114:11:36] } 24... Rfd8 { [%clk 108:50:38] } 25. Bb3 { Stopping the d-pawn from advancing. } { [%cal Gb3f7] [%clk 113:15:46] } 25... Kh8 { [%clk 110:30:12] } 26. Re1 { Instead, Rac1 to develop the Rook and contest the c-file. } { [%clk 111:06:47] } 26... Na5 { [%clk 117:25:44] } 27. Bd1 { This looks bad because it allows ...d4 with initiative and interrupts the communication of the Rooks. Instead, Bf2. } { [%clk 118:52:26] } 27... d4 { [%clk 118:45:55] } 28. Bd2 { [%clk 119:21:16] } 28... Qe6 { Looking at the board, this is how I see it in retrospect after 28...Qe6: White is up a pawn and has a better pawn structure. He has two passed pawns versus my one. One of his passed pawns is supported by the other whereas mine is isolated. My Queenside Rook has complete control of the c-file and is better than Black's, which is active. White has the Bishop pair. My Na5 is absolutely useless there and must be posted elsewhere, so that will take time. White's lsb is on the back rank and prevents its Rooks from communicating. My Queen is in the line of sight of White's Re1 and will have to find a better posting, so that will take time. I feel White has a significant advantage, at this stage of the game. } { -
White only has one passed pawn.
White is winning here. Besides being a pawn up, it seems to me that White will get his passed pawn moving. Black is currently trying to blockade with the Queen, which is the worst piece to use as a blockader.
As you said the a5-Knight needs to get off the side of the board. Since ...Nc4 would accomplish that, White should consider b3 as a candidate on positional grounds that it takes away that square from the Knight. That move also interrupts the Black Queen's attack on a2. White's d2 Bishop has an eye on the dark squares c3/e3, so perhaps the weakening of a3/c3 by b3 is tactically ok. If Black responds ...Nac6 then he's blocking his Rook. If he plays ...Nd5 with the idea of getting to the newly created holes on c3/e3 then White starts the pawns rolling.
I notice that Black's Queen and Rook are on the same diagonal. So tactically, getting a Bishop to g4 is an idea. That ties into the light squares being weak. Candidate would be Qh5.
White would like a timely g4 and f5.
Besides what's been said so far, this is a 2-Bishops vs 2-Knights middle game. Per Silman (and Steinitz) the general winning method is to take squares away from the Knights. Silman discusses this in "How to Reassess Your Chess" in the chapter "Dogs vs. Cats / Bishops vs Knights". In open positions the Bishops are usually superior.
