1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 { I'm not familiar with the proper way to defend against this attack } 4... d5 5. exd5 Ne7 (5... Na5 { This is better. I found it when looking at the opening explorer. }) 6. Nxf7 { sacrifices a piece but without concrete winning continuation } 6... Kxf7 7. d6+ Ned5 8. Bxd5+ Nxd5 9. Qf3+ Nf6 10. dxc7 Qxc7 { White's attack is over. They lost a piece without compensation. } 11. Qb3+ Be6 12. Qc3 { I'm up a piece, so I didn't mind exchanging the Queens. } 12... Qxc3 13. Nxc3 Bc5 (13... Bd5 14. Nxd5 (14. O-O) 14... Nxd5) 14. O-O Rhd8 { I wasn't sure which square is best for the Rook } (14... Rhf8) (14... Rhe8) (14... Rac8) 15. d3 h6 { Preventing any ideas of ...Bg5 pinning the Knight } 16. Bd2 { Developing White's last minor piece and connecting the Rooks } 16... Bd4 17. Na4 { Forced, or White will lose the b2 pawn } 17... e4 { Trying to open the position. I saw the following possible lines, but missed the 19.d4 played in the game. I was also contemplating 17...Kg8 first, but so no direct threat to the King } 18. c3 (18. dxe4 Nxe4 19. Be3 (19. Rad1 Bxf2+ (19... Nxd2 20. Rxd2) 20. Rxf2+ Nxf2 21. Kxf2) (19. Bb4 Bxf2+ 20. Rxf2+ Nxf2 21. Kxf2) 19... Bxe3 20. fxe3+ Kg8) 18... Bb6 19. d4 (19. Nxb6 axb6) 19... Bxd4 { Saw this tactic winning at least a pawn } 20. cxd4 (20. Rad1 Be5) 20... Rxd4 21. Bc3 Rxa4 22. b3 { saving the a2 pawn } 22... Ra6 { the only safe square other than a3 (which I felt will constrict my Rook's activity) } 23. Rfe1 Bf5 { adding another protector to e4 in case white played Bxf6 } 24. Rac1 Rc8 { This looks like a mistake, but I'm not sure how White would punish it } 25. f3 (25. Bxf6 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 Rxf6) 25... exf3 26. gxf3 Nd5 { Wither winning the Bishop, or forcing an exchange of Rooks. I didn't consider Re5 } 27. Re5 (27. b4 Nxc3) (27. Bd4 Rxc1 28. Rxc1) 27... Rxc3 28. Rxc3 { Did White have anything stroneger? } (28. Rxf5+ Kg6 29. Rxc3 Nxc3) 28... Nxc3 29. Rxf5+ Rf6 30. Rc5 Rxf3 31. Kg2 { This should be a winning end game. I let it slip and ended up with a draw } 31... Rf2+ { Hoping to further simplify with a Kinght fork } 32. Kg1 (32. Kxf2 Ne4+ 33. Kf3 Nxc5) 32... Rc2 { Hoping White would fall for ...Ne2+ winning the exchange } (32... Ne4) 33. Rc7+ { Now White is threatining to win 2 pawns } (33. h3 Ne2+ 34. Kf2 Rxc5 35. Kxe2) 33... Ke6 34. Rxg7 Rxa2 (34... b6 35. Rg6+ Kd7 36. Rxh6) 35. Rxb7 Kd5 36. Rh7 Ne2+ 37. Kf1 Nd4 38. Rxh6 Nxb3 39. h4 Rh2 (39... Nc5 40. h5 Ra6 41. Rh7) 40. Kg1 Ra2 41. h5 a5 42. Rh8 Ra1+ 43. Kh2 a4 44. h6 Ra2+ 45. Kh3 Rc2 { Without looking at the engine evaluation, I think here is where the game turned into a draw } 46. Rd8+ Kc4 47. h7 Rc1 48. h8=Q Rh1+ 49. Kg2 Rxh8 50. Rxh8 a3 51. Rc8+ (51. Ra8 Kb4 52. Rxa3 Kxa3) 51... Nc5 (51... Kb4 52. Ra8 Na5 53. Rb8+ Ka4 54. Rb1) 52. Ra8 Kb3 53. Rb8+ Ka2 54. Ra8 Nb3 55. Kf2 Kb2 56. Re8 a2 57. Re2+ Kb1 58. Rxa2 Kxa2 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


