{ As a first pass, I'm only going to comment on the tactical mistakes.
Unfortunate that you stalemated at the end.
- }
1. d4 { Move with goal to be able to get placement of knight to d4 } 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 { Have been taught to develop knights early and this protects d5 pawn } 4. Bf4 { After making this move, I realized I preferred to make the move bf5, have played bg4 many times but never seem to capitalize on that move } 4... Bg4 5. e3 { Not sure what I was thinking in making this move Nf5 } 5... e6 6. Nbd2 Bf5 7. Ne5 Bd6 { Felt I could pin the knight and prepare to castle } { The e5-Knight is not pinned by any usual definition. } 8. h3 { Not sure why I made the choice to move the pawn h3 } 8... O-O 9. g4 Bg6 10. Bg2 a5 11. a3 b6 { Hanging the c6-Knight. } { [%cal Ge5c6] } 12. Ke2 { Missing the win of the c6-Knight. } 12... Bxe5 13. Bg5 { White just lost a Knight on e5. White needed to recapture to equalize material. } 13... Ne7 { thinking back not clear why I chose to move ne7 as felt it blocked potential queen mobility } { Hanging the e5-Bishop. Simply ...Bd6 to be a piece up. } 14. dxe5 { prepare to move to e5 and capture pawn } 14... Nd7 { I should've made the move Nxe5 } 15. e4 { Hanging the e5-pawn. } { [%cal Gd7e5] } 15... Nc5 16. Qc2 { [%cal Gd5e4,Gg6e4,Gc5e4,Gd2e4,Gc2e4,Gg2e4] } 16... h6 { Black should play ...dxe4. White's King is in the center and Black's Queen can play to e8 and then b5. That would threaten the e5-pawn and the b2-pawn. To see these tactics here, imagine that Black gets to play 2 moves here. } { [%cal Gd5e4,Gd2e4,Gg6e4,Gc5e4,Gg2e4,Gc2e4,Rd8e8,Re8b5,Rb5e2,Rb5e5,Rb5b2] } 17. Bh4 b5 18. b4 { Feel I shouldve made move a5xb4 } 18... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5] } 19. bxa5 { White hangs the e5-pawn. Much better was 19.f4. } 19... Rxa5 20. g5 { Still hanging the e5-pawn. } { [%cal Gd7e5,Gh6g5,Gh4g5] } 20... Nxe5 { Better was ...hxg5 first to keep the kingside pawns connected. } 21. f4 { This is very suspicious because of the position of the White King. Black can play ...Bh5+ and open the position with ...dxe4 (sacrificing the e5-Knight). White's h4-Bishop is not protected. The tactics are interesting. } { [%cal Gg6h5,Gh5e2,Rf4e5,Ge7f5,Gf5h4,Gf5e3,Rd5e4,Re4e3,Re3f2,Re3d2] } 21... N5c6 22. f5 { This move loses material. } { [%cal Ge6f5,Gg6f5,Ge7f5,Ge4f5] } 22... exf5 23. Rab1 { Instead 23.gxh6. } { [%cal Gb1b5,Ga5b5,Rh6g5,Rf5e4] } 23... Rxa3 { rxa3 captures a hanging pawn and control a file } { Instead ...hxg5 and then ...fxe4 gives Black a protected passed pawn, and wins a pawn. } 24. Qb2 { [%cal Rb2a3,Rb2b5,Ga3c3,Gd8d6,Gd6a3,Gd6f4,Gf4h4,Gf5e4,Gd5e4,Gg6e4] } 24... Ra5 { Instead ...Qd6 is much stronger. } 25. Ra1 { Still gxh6 is better. Both sides are missing that since White's King is in the center, Black should attack in the center. } 25... Ra4 { mistake as left b pawn hanging } { All of ...Bh5+, ...dxe4, ...fxe4, ...hxg5, and ...Rxa1 are better. } 26. Qxb5 Ra8 { should've made move ra5 to threaten queen } { ...Ra5 would lose material. Draw the attack/defense (A/D) network on a5. } { [%cal Ga1a5,Gb5a5,Gc6a5] } 27. Bg3 Bh5+ { check will allow capture of rook on a1 } { I do not understand your comment "...check will allow capture of rook on a1". Black could have captured on a1 if desired. } 28. Bf3 Rxa1 29. Rxa1 hxg5 { mistake as should have made move bxf3 } { Yes. Simplest was 29...Bxf3 Nxf3 30.fxe4. } 30. Bxh5 { pin the bishop } { What does your comment "pin the Bishop" mean? } 30... fxe4 { [%cal Rd8d7,Rd7h3,Rh3g3,Rh3h5] } 31. Qb7 { Instead ...Qd7. } 31... f5 32. Ra8 { This is a blunder. Black has a8 covered twice. White loses a Rook after ...Qxa8. } { [%cal Gf8a8,Gb7a8] } 32... Qd7 { Missing the tactic to take on a8 and missing the double attack on c7. } { [%cal Gb7c7,Gg3c7,Gd7c7] } 33. Ra7 { Missing the simplification Rxf8 followed by exchanging Queens on c7 and missing that the c6-Knight guards a7. } 33... Nxa7 34. Qxa7 g6 { Excellent. Traps the h5-Bishop. } 35. Bxc7 { Bad. This is called a "self-pin". } 35... gxh5 36. Qc5 Rc8 { pin the bishop to the queen } 37. Bb6 { White should have just let Black win the Bishop. Giving up the Queen for a Rook makes no sense. } 37... Rxc5 38. Bxc5 { Black now has a check that wins the Bishop. } { [%cal Rd7b5,Rb5e2,Rb5c5] } 38... Ng6 { Missing the tactic to win the Bishop. } 39. Be3 f4 40. Bf2 Qb5+ 41. Kd1 e3 { Black wins as he pleases; this fork is one way. } 42. Be1 Qd3 { pins the knight } { Why not just play ...exd2 winning the Knight? It does not matter that White would win the pawn. } (42... exd2 43. Bxd2 Qb1+ 44. Ke2 Ne5 { Black will mate shortly. } { [%cal Ge5d3,Ge5f3,Gb1d3,Gf4g3,Gf4e3] }) 43. Bf2 { Allowing mate in one move. } { [%cal Re3d2,Rd3d2] } 43... exf2 { Missing mate in one. } 44. Kc1 Ne5 { Instead, take the Knight with the Queen and then make a new Queen. White would have no pieces left. } (44... Qxd2+ 45. Kxd2 f1=Q $19) 45. Nb3 Qxc3+ { check will lead to capture of knight } 46. Kd1 { [%csl Rc2,Rd2,Rc1][%cal Rf2f1] } 46... Qxb3+ { Missed mate in one. } (46... f1=Q#) 47. Ke2 Qc2+ 48. Kf1 Nf3 (48... f3 49. h4 Qe2#) 49. Kg2 Nh4+ 50. Kf1 f3 { blunder move leading to stalemate. thinking back I should've have moved Qd3# } { 1/2-1/2 Draw by stalemate. } *


