{ Rather than put more comments in chapter 4, I copied the chapter to here.
I'll only be making positional/strategic comments here.
- }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nc6 { -
Beginners are taught rules-of-thumb for the opening that get them started with the game, but later they have to learn exceptions. Hence, this Knight move for a certain level player is fine, and even played as a surprise move by GMs, but it has drawbacks.
There are two drawbacks and they are related. The Knight is blocking the c-pawn. The c-pawn will either want to play to c5 to attack the White d4 center pawn, or to c3 to defend Black's d5-pawn. In either case there may later be an exchange that causes the c-file to become half-open or fully open, and in that case Black can develop his Queen Rook to c8. Black may have difficulty otherwise finding a good square for the QR.
- } { [%cal Rc7c5,Rc5d4,Ra8c8] } 3. c3 Nf6 4. Bf4 Bg4 5. e3 e6 6. Nbd2 Bf5 { Black's Bishop was playing an active role on g4 by pinning the f3-Knight. However, this is Black's "bad Bishop"; Black has his center pawns on light squares so they hamper the mobility of this Bishop. Hence, Black should consider trading this Bishop. Ideally he'd trade it for White's good Bishop; White's light squared Bishop. But Black might also trade it for a Knight. } 7. Ne5 Bd6 8. h3 O-O 9. g4 { A finesse here is ...Be4. If White plays f3 then Black retreats the Bishop and White has taken f3 from his Knight. If White captures the Bishop then Black captures with the Knight. Either way Black might rid himself of the bad Bishop. } 9... Bg6 10. Bg2 { Instead h4 was the logical followup for White. } 10... a5 { Instead, Black needs to be getting rid of White's e5-Knight, even at the cost of his good Bishop. So see the line 10...Bxe5. } (10... Bxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 { White cannot save his pawn. } { [%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Gf4e5] } 12. O-O Bd3! { Taking advantage of the hole at d3. } 13. Re1 Ncxe5 14. e4 { White tries the center break. Black has several options. Suppose Black wants to maintain center tension, then ... } 14... Qf6 15. Bg3 c6) 11. a3 { This weakens the light squares. } 11... b6 { Every pawn move has to be judged carefully. Ask "What squares am I giving up that the pawn was attacking?". Besides hanging the c6-Knight, this pawn move weakens c6 and a6. Better was ...Bxd5 as mentioned earlier. } 12. Ke2 { It is a bad idea to have your King in the center of the board unless the pawn center is locked and unlikely to be opened. } 12... Bxe5 { Black starts the correct plan. } 13. Bg5 { Inexplicably losing a piece and allowing Black to maintain his good Bishop! } 13... Ne7 { The Knight has nowhere to go from here but back to c6. Perhaps Black wanted to move the c-pawn? } 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. e4 Nc5 { This is a difficult location for the Knight but it works tactically. } 16. Qc2 h6 { The correct followup is dxe4. This would be the reason for the last Knight move - an attack on the center that opens up lines to get at the White King that is in the center. } 17. Bh4 b5 { The wrong strategy. Open the center to attack the White King and/or put the Black Queen on e8 with the idea of penetration on the light squares (Qb5). } 18. b4 { The tactics are messy, but Black should either play ...Nxe4 or ...axb4 and after a Rook exchange play ...Nxe4. Black wants to push his weak c-pawn, even if he loses it, so long as he gets compensation in mobility. } 18... Nd7 19. bxa5 Rxa5 20. g5 Nxe5 { Instead, ...hxg5 to avoid the positionally bad kingside structure that would ensue. } 21. f4 N5c6 22. f5 exf5 23. Rab1 { Black should still be thinking of getting at the White King and White should know this, hence White needs counterplay. This move drops the e-pawn to ...fxe4. White's position is lost! } 23... Rxa3 { Wrong strategy. Black does not want to give White any possible counterplay on the queenside. } 24. Qb2 Ra5 { Black should get his Queen more mobility and can do this while protecting his Rook by ...Qd6 instead. } 25. Ra1 Ra4 { Instead ...Bh5+ is the correct plan. } 26. Qxb5 Ra8 27. Bg3 Bh5+ { Correct idea. } 28. Bf3 Rxa1 29. Rxa1 hxg5 { Now ...Bxf3 would remove one of the White King's defenders. } 30. Bxh5 fxe4 31. Qb7 f5 { Instead ...g6 and then ...f5. } 32. Ra8 Qd7 33. Ra7 Nxa7 34. Qxa7 g6 35. Bxc7 gxh5 36. Qc5 Rc8 37. Bb6 Rxc5 38. Bxc5 { Black has a won game. White cannot allow either of his pieces to be traded for the Black Knight. That means White will be in constant retreat from any piece improving moves that Black wants to make. The two passed pawns, properly guarded will roll over White causing a crises. This is if Black has no other tactical win; such as here with a fork that wins the Bishop immediately. } 38... Ng6 39. Be3 f4 40. Bf2 Qb5+ 41. Kd1 e3 42. Be1 Qd3 43. Bf2 exf2 44. Kc1 Ne5 45. Nb3 Qxc3+ 46. Kd1 Qxb3+ 47. Ke2 Qc2+ 48. Kf1 Nf3 49. Kg2 Nh4+ 50. Kf1 f3 { 1/2-1/2 Draw by
stalemate. } *


