1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. d4 { a3 this move signals 2 things , 1 limits the dsb but also enables b4 which means white prbablly wats to shortcastle } 4... e6 5. a3 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 5... c5 { c5 is to earlly, ofc u want to open the game but, now it is just reating more LSquare weakness, Bishop check with Qa4 followed is a common theamtic at my level at least.Instead Ne7 } (5... Nd7) (5... Ne7 { True it blocks the BsB but it protects the F5 Bishop. How I underatnd the advcned var is simple I am a simple man- u want to develope yor pieces and attack the center ideally attacking d4 pawnby mean s of Nf5, Nc6 , c5 Qb6 . But at the same time u need to develop ASAP keeping in mind that u have so much less space then White. } { [%cal Ge7f5] }) 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. O-O Qb6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 { NOt sure about Qb6 now as well I would still play Ne7 } 9. c3 h6 (9... cxd4 { Here i would just take }) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. b4 Be7 12. a4 Qd8 { This seems like a free tempo for White } 13. Nd4 Qc7 14. Bf4 { [%cal Gf5h7,Gf5b1] } 14... Bg5 { I would go back with the bishop or take the Knight } 15. Bg3 h5 { White wins another tempo and messes the pawn chain } { [%cal Gg3c7,Gd4f5] } 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. e6 Qc8 18. exf7+ Kxf7 19. h4 Bf6 20. Qd3 Ne7 21. Nd2 Re8 22. Nf3 Qd7 { IS the idea to protect D5? } { [%cal Gg3e5,Gf3e5,Gf1e1,Gg7g6,Ge7g6] } 23. Ne5+ Bxe5 24. Bxe5 Ng6 25. Bg3 Ne5 26. Bxe5 Rxe5 27. Rad1 Rae8 28. a5 R8e7 29. c4 Qe6 30. Qf3 g6 31. cxd5 Rxd5 32. Qc3 Re5 33. f4 Re2 34. Qh8 Qf6 35. Qc8 Qc3 36. Kh2 Qc2 37. Rg1 Qe4 38. Qb8 Rf2 39. b5 Rxf4 { At this point , I decided to go for the draw because even though I was going to end up with a material advantage, I could not see the win with White's Queen on the board and those pawns so deep in my territory. If I could have seen a way to force the Queen exchange, I would have felt much more confident and gone for the endgame. } (39... cxb5! 40. Rdf1 (40. Qxb5?? Qxf4+ 41. Kh3 Qg4+ 42. Kh2 Qxh4#) 40... Qe2 41. Rxf2 Qxf2 42. Rc1 (42. Qxb5?? Qxh4#) (42. Kh3?? Qxg1 $18) (42. a6?? Qxh4#) 42... Qxh4+ 43. Kg1 Re1+ 44. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 45. Kh2 Qxa5 46. Qb7+ Kf6 47. Qc6+ Kg7 48. Qb7+ Kh6 $19 49. Qb8! { If Black does not want to draw, he has to give up the b-pawn. } { [%cal Rb8h8] } 49... Qa1! 50. Qxb5 Qd4 51. Qb8 h4! 52. Qc7 { -
In "Basic Chess Endings" by Reuben Fine (the endgame "bible" in my day) he says of such endgames as we have now:
" ... much more complicated than the foregoing because a straightforward pawn advance simply will not do. For the King is secure against perpetual check only when surrounded by pawns, so that playing them out of the way merely invites a draw. The two chief winning stratagems in these cases are 1) playing the King over to the other side of the board and 2) a mating attack.
- } 52... a6 { Each pawn move resets the 50-move draw count. } 53. Kh1 Qd3 54. Qe5 Kh5 55. Kg1 Qd1+ 56. Kh2 Qd2 57. Qh8+ Kg4 58. Qf6 Qxf4+ 59. Kh1 g5 60. Qc3 (60. Qxa6?? h3 61. Qe2+ (61. gxh3+ Kxh3 $19 { Winning per tablebase. }) 61... Kh4! 62. Qe1+ Qg3 $19) 60... Qf1+ { A maneuver to end up with Queen on e4 and White King on h2 with White to move. } 61. Kh2 Qf2 62. Kh1 Qe2 63. Kh2 Qe4 64. Kh1 (64. Kg1 a5 65. Qxa5 h3 $19) 64... a5 65. Kg1 (65. Qxa5?? h3 $19) 65... a4 66. Kf2 { Now what? } 66... Qd5 67. Kg1 Qb7 68. Kf1 Qa8 69. Qd4+ Qe4 70. Qc3 Kh5 { The winning idea is to move the King back and use the Queen to cover the checks. Then circle the King back around in front of the kingside pawns, but this time Black has an improved Queen position and a more advanced a-pawn. The rest is SF analysis on my local computer but outside Lichess. } 71. Qh8+ Kg6 72. Qg8+ Kf6 73. Kf2 Qe6 74. Qh7 a3 75. Qh6+ Ke5 76. Qh8+ Qf6 77. Qe8+ Kd6 78. Qc8 Qd4+ 79. Kf1 Qd1+ 80. Kf2 Qb3 81. Kf1 Qd1+ 82. Kf2 Qb3 83. Qf8+ Ke5 84. Ke2 a2 85. Qg7+ Ke4 86. Qe7+ Kf4 87. Qd6+ Kg4 88. Qd4+ Kh5 89. Kd2 Qb1 90. Qh8+ Kg4 $19) (39... Qxf4+ 40. Qxf4 Rxf4 41. bxc6 Rxh4+ 42. Kg3 Rg4+ 43. Kf2 Ra4 (43... Rf4+ 44. Kg3 Rc4 45. Rd6 Ree4 46. Rd7+ Kf6 47. Rxa7 Rc3+ 48. Kf2 Rxc6 49. Rd7 Rc2+)) 40. Rge1 Rxh4+ 41. Kg1 Rh1+ 42. Kxh1 Qh4+ 43. Kg1 Rxe1+ 44. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 45. Kh2 Qh4+ 46. Kg1 Qe1+ 47. Kh2 Qh4+ (47... Qxa5 48. bxc6 Qd5 49. c7 Qe5+ 50. Kg1 $10) 48. Kg1 Qe1+ { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


