[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Rook and King against King 2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/JWsYWu3U"]
[FEN "8/8/8/4k3/8/8/8/4K2R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Since the Black King is in the centre of the board, the best way to proceed is to advance your own King thus: }
1. Ke2 Kd5 2. Ke3 { As the Rook has not yet come into play, it is better to advance the King straight into the centre of the board, not in front, but to one side of the other King. Should now the Black King move } 2... Ke5 { the Rook drives it back by } (2... Kc4 { instead, then also } 3. Rh5 { If now } 3... Kb4 { there follows } (3... Kc3 { then } 4. Rh4 { keeping the King confined to as few squares as possible. Now the ending may continue: } 4... Kc2 5. Rc4+ Kb3 6. Kd3 Kb2 7. Rb4+ Ka3 8. Kc3 Ka2 { It should be noticed how often the White King has moved next to the Rook, not only to defend it, but also to reduce the mobility of the opposing King. Now White mates in three moves thus: } 9. Ra4+ Kb1 10. Ra8 { or any square on the Rook's file, forcing the Black King in front of the White, } 10... Kc1 11. Ra1#) 4. Kd3) 3. Rh5+ *


