{ I shall now give a couple of simple endings of two pawns against one, or three against two, that the reader may see how they can be one. Fewer explanations will be given, as it is up to the student to work things out for himself. Furthermore, nobody can learn how to play well merely from the study of a book; it can only serve as a guide and the rest must be done by the teacher if the student has one; if not, the student must realize by long and bitter experience the practical application of the many things explained in the book.

White can win the position given in the diagram by playing: }
1. Kd7 (1. f6 { because Black plays, not gxf6, which would lose, but } 1... Kg8 { and if then } 2. fxg7 (2. f7+ Kf8 { and White will never be able to Queen his Pawn without losing it. }) (2. Ke7 gxf6 3. Kxf6 Kf8 { and draws. }) 2... Kxg7 { and draws, as shown in previous case. }) 1... Kg8 2. Ke7 Kh8 3. f6 gxf6 (3... Kg8 4. f7+ Kh8 5. f8=Q#) 4. Kf7 f5 5. g7+ Kh7 6. g8=Q+ Kh6 7. Qg6# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } *


[Event "Capablanca: Chess Fundamentals Part I: Theory: 8. Pawn Endings"]
