[SetUp "1"]

{ White can win by playing: }
1. Ke4 (1. f5 { Black's best answer would be } 1... g6 { draws. The student should work this out. }) (1. g5 { because } 1... g6 { draws. This, because of the principle of the "opposition" which governs this ending as well as all the Pawn-endings already given, and which will be explained more fully later on. }) 1... Ke6 (1... g6 2. Kd4 Ke6 3. Kc5 Kf6 4. Kd6 Kf7 5. g5 Kg7 6. Ke7 Kg8 7. Kf6 Kh7 8. Kf7 { and White wins the Pawn. }) 2. f5+ Kf6 3. Kf4 g6 { If this Pawn is kept back we arrive at the ending shown in Example 7. } 4. g5+ Kf7 5. f6 Ke6 6. Ke4 Kf7 7. Ke5 Kf8 { White cannot force his Bishop's Pawn into Queen (find out why), but by giving his Pawn up he can win the other Pawn and the game. Thus: } 8. f7 Kxf7 9. Kd6 Kf8 10. Ke6 Kg7 11. Ke7 Kg8 12. Kf6 Kh7 13. Kf7 Kh8 14. Kxg6 Kg8 { There is still some resistance in Black's position. In fact, the only way to win is the one given here, as will easily be seen by experiment. } 15. Kh6 (15. Kf6 Kh7 { and in order to win White must get back to the actual position, as against } 16. g6+ Kh8 { draws. }) 15... Kh8 16. g6 Kg8 17. g7 Kf7 18. Kh7 { and White queens the Pawn and wins. } *


