{ In this ending, White can win by advancing any of the three pawns on the first move, but it is convenient to follow the general rule, whenever there is no good reason against it, of *advancing the pawn that has no pawn opposing it.* Thus we begin by: }
1. f5 Ke7 (1... g6 2. f6 { and we have a similar ending to one of those shown above }) (1... h6 2. g5) 2. Ke5 Kf7 3. g5 Ke7 (3... g6 4. f6) (3... h6 4. g6+ { and in either case we have a similar ending to one of those already shown }) 4. h5 { and by following it up with g6 we have the same ending previously shown. } { Should Black play 4...g6 then } 4... g6 5. hxg6 hxg6 6. f6+ { with the same result. } *


