[SetUp "1"]

{ In this position, whoever moves first wins. The first thing is to find out, by counting, whether the opposing king can be in time to stop the passed pawn from queening. When, as in this case, it cannot be done, the point is to count which pawn comes in first. In this case, the time is the same, but the pawn that reaches the eighth square first and becomes a queen is in a position to capture the adversary's queen when he makes one. Thus: }
1. a4 h5 2. a5 h4 3. b6 axb6 { Now comes a little calculation. White can capture the Pawn, but if he does so, he will not, when Queening, command the square where Black will also Queen his Pawn. Therefore, instead of taking, he plays: } 4. a6 h3 5. a7 h2 6. a8=Q { and wins. } *


[Event "Capablanca: Chess Fundamentals Part I: Theory: 27. The Opposition"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/jyBdvzW0/5e0764RJ"]
