{ Before turning our attention to this matter it is well to state now that *two knights alone cannot mate*, but, under certain conditions they can do so if the opponent has one or more pawns.

In this position, White because black has a pawn, White wins with or without the move. Thus: }
1. Ng6 h4 { White cannot take the pawn because the game will be drawn as explained before. } 2. Ne5 h3 3. Nc6 h2 4. Nb5 h1=Q 5. Nc7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { The reason for this peculiarity in chess is evident. *White with the two knights can only stalemate the king, unless Black has a pan which can be moved. } 1-0


