{ A good example of a successful direct attack on the king is shown in this diagram. The game continues thus: }
12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Kg6 14. Qg4 f5 (14... e5 { would have been immediately fatal. Thus: } 15. Ne6+ Kf6 16. f4! e4 17. Qg5+ Kxe6 18. Qe5+ Kd7 19. Rfd1+ Nd3 20. Nxe4 Kc6 (20... Ke8 21. Nd6+ { wins the Queen. }) 21. Rxd3 Qxd3 22. Rc1+ Kb6 (22... Kd7 { mate in two. }) 23. Qc7+ { and mate in five moves. }) 15. Qg3 Kh6 16. Qh4+ Kg6 17. Qh7+ Kf6 (17... Kxg5 18. Qxg7+ { and mate in a few moves. }) 18. e4 Ng6 19. exf5 exf5 20. Rad1 Nd3 21. Qh3 Ndf4 22. Qg3 Qc7 23. Rfe1 Ne2+ { This blunder loses at once, but the game could not be saved in any case; } (23... Be6 24. Rxe6+ Nxe6 25. Nd5#) 24. Rxe2 Qxg3 25. Nh7+ Kf7 26. hxg3 Rh8 27. Ng5+ Kf6 28. f4 { and Black resigns. } *


