[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Lasker Defense"]
[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Marshall v. Capablanca (Queen's Gambit Declined)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/OuKunmYV"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 Ne4 { I had played this defense twice before in the match with good results, and although I lost this game, I still played it until my very last game, when I changed my tactics. The reason was my total lack of knowledge of the different variations in this opening, coupled with that fact that I knew that Dr. E. Lasker had been successful with it against Marshall himself in 1907. I thought that since Dr. Lasker had played it so often, it should be good. The object is to exchange a couple of pieces at the same time to bring about a position full of possibilities and with promising chances of success once the end-game stage is reached. On general principles, it should be wrong because the same knight is moved three times in the opening, although it involves the exchange of two pieces. In reality, the difficulty in this variation, as well as in nearly all the variations in the Queen's gambit, lies in the slow development of Black's Queen Bishop. However, whether this variation can or cannot be safely played is a question still to be decided, and it is outside the scope of this book. I may add that at present my preference is for a different system of development, but it is not unlikely that I should some time come back to this variation. } 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Bd3 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Qb3 Nf6 12. a4 c5 { Played with the intention of obtaining the majority of pawns on the queenside. Yet it is doubtful whether this move is good, since it leaves Black's queenside pawns disrupted in a way. } 13. Qa3 b6 14. a5 Bb7 15. O-O Qc7 16. Rfb1 Nd7 { Black's position was bad and perhaps lost in any case, but the text move makes matters worse. As a matter of fact, I never saw White's reply, Bf5. It never even passed through my mind that this was threatened. } 17. Bf5 Rfc8 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. a6 Bc6 20. dxc5 bxc5 21. Qxc5 Rab8 { The game was lost. One move was as good as another. } 22. Rxb8 Rxb8 23. Ne5 Qf5 24. f4 Rb6 25. Qxb6! { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "San Sebastian  Round: 12"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/Yoj3NVDl/ZCXtVWBI"]
[Date "1911.??.??"]
[White "Rubinstein, Akiba"]
[Black "Capablanca, Jose"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Capablanca"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D33"]
[Opening "Tarrasch Defense: Rubinstein System"]
[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Rubinstein v. Capablanca"]
