{ French Defense }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 { Of all the variations of the French Defense I like this best because it gives Black more chances to obtain the inititative. } 5. e5 h6 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Qg4 Kf8 { By this move Black gives up castling, but gains time for an attack against White's center and queenside. } 9. Bc1 c5 10. Bd3 Qa5 11. Ne2 cxd4 12. O-O dxc3 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 Nc6 { Black has come out of the opening with a pawn to the good. His development, however, has suffered somewhat, and there are bishops of opposite color, so that it cannot be said as yet that Black has a won game. } 15. Rd1 g6 16. f4 Kg7 17. Be3 Ne7 18. Bf2 Nd5 { This knight completely paralyzes the attack, as it dominates the whole situation and there is no way to dislodge it. Behind it Black can quietly develop his pieces. The came can now be said to be won for Black strategically. } 19. Rd3 Bd7 20. Nd4 Rac8 21. Rg3 Kh7 22. h4 Rhg8 23. h5 Qb4 24. Rh3 f5 25. exf6 Nxf6 26. hxg6+ Rxg6 27. Rxh6+ { This wins the queen. } 27... Kxh6 28. Nf5+ exf5 29. Qxb4 Rcg8 30. g3 Bc6 31. Rd1 Kh5 { The tables are turned. It is now White who has the upper hand, and Black who has to fight for a draw. } 32. Rd6 Be4 33. Qxc3 Nd5 34. Rxg6 Kxg6 35. Qe5 Kf7 36. c4 Re8 37. Qb2 Nf6 38. Bd4 Rh8 39. Qb5 Rh1+ 40. Kf2 a6 41. Qb6 Rh2+ 42. Ke1 Nd7 43. Qd6 Bc6 44. g4 fxg4 45. f5 Rh1+ 46. Kd2 Ke8 47. f6 Rh7 48. Qe6+ Kf8 49. Be3 Rf7 50. Bh6+ Kg8 { Most players will be wondering, as the spectators did, why I did not resign. The reason is that while I knew the game to be lost, I was hoping for a variation [spelled out in book], which Chajes came very near playing, and while White has a won game it is by no means easy. If the reader does not believe it, let him take the White pieces against a master and see what happens. } 51. Bg7 g3 52. Ke2 g2 53. Kf2 Nf8 54. Qg4 Nd7 55. Kg1 a5 56. a4 Bxa4 57. Qh3 Rxf6 58. Bxf6 Nxf6 59. Qxg2+ Kf8 60. Qxb7 { and after a very few more moves Black resigned.
A very fine game on Chajes' from move 25 on, for while Black, having the best of the position, missed several chances, White, on the other hand, missed none. } 60... Be8 61. Qb6 Ke7 62. Qxa5 Nd7 63. Kf2 Bf7 64. Ke3 Kd6 65. Kd4 Kc6 66. Qf5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


