[ChapterName "Capablanca v. Janowski (Ruy Lopez)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/yGVvdomV"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 { I played this move after having discussed it with Alekhine on several occasions. Alekhine considered it, at the time, superior to 5d4, which is generally played. He played it himself later in the tournament, in one of his games against Lasker, and obtained the superior game, which he only lost through a blunder. } 5... Bc5 { ... f6 is probably the best move in this position. I do not like the text move. } 6. d3 Bg4 7. Be3 Bxe3 { This opens the f-file for White, and also reinforces his center, but Black naturally did not want to make a second move with his bishop. } 8. fxe3 Qe7 9. O-O O-O-O { Bold play, typical of Janowski. } 10. Qe1 Nh6 { The problem for White now is to advance his b-pawn to b5 as fast as he can. If he plays 11 b4 at once, Black simply takes it. If he plays 11 a3 and then 12 b4 White will still have to protect the b-pawn before he can go on to play a4 and b5. As a matter of fact, White played a rather unusual move, but one which, under the circumstances, was the best, since after it he could at once play b4 and then a4 and b5. } 11. Rb1! f6 12. b4 Nf7 13. a4 Bxf3 { He simplifies, hoping to lighten White's attack, which will have to be conducted practically with only the heavy pieces on the board. He may also have done it in order to play ... Ng5 and ... Ne6. } 14. Rxf3 { Taking with the pawn would have opened a possibility for a counterattack. } 14... b6 { He is forced to do this to avoid the breaking up of his queenside pawns. The only alternative would have been 14 ... b5; which on the face of it looks bad. } 15. b5 cxb5 16. axb5 a5 17. Nd5 Qc5 18. c4 { The white knight is now a tower of strength. Behind it White will be able to prepare an attack, which will begin with advancing the pawn to d4, driving away the black queen and thus leaving White free to play c5. There is only one thing to take care of and that is to prevent Black from sacrificing the rook for the knight and pawn. } 18... Ng5 19. Rf2 Ne6 20. Qc3 Rd7 { Had White on his 19th move played 19 Rf1 instead of 19 RF2, then Black could have played instead 20 ... Rxd5 21 exd5 Qxe3+ followed by 22 ... Nd4 with a winning game. } 21. Rd1 Kb7 { It would have been better for Black to play 21 ... Kd8. The text loses very rapidly. } 22. d4 Qd6 23. Rc2 exd4 24. exd4 Nf4 25. c5 Nxd5 26. exd5 Qxd5 27. c6+ Kb8 28. cxd7 Qxd7 29. d5 Re8 30. d6 cxd6 31. Qc6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "New York"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1918.10.26"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Black "Oscar Chajes"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Capablanca"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C11"]
[Opening "French Defense: Classical Variation, Swiss Variation"]
[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Capablanca v. Chajes (French Defense)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/BWW46WMA"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bd3 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Qe4 g6 { This weakens Black's kingside. Re8 was the right move. } 12. h4 e5 { This is merely giving up a pawn in order to come out quickly with his queen's bishop. But as he does not obtain any compensation for his pawn, the move is bad. He should have played Qd5 and tried to fight the game out that way. The text move might be considered a mild form of suicide. } 13. dxe5 Bf5 14. Qf4 Bxd3 15. O-O-O Bg7 16. Rxd3 Qe7 17. Qc4 { In order to keep the black queen from coming into the game. } 17... Rad8 18. Rhd1 Rxd3 19. Rxd3 Re8 20. c3 c6 21. Re3 c5 22. Kc2 b6 23. a4 { White's plan is now to *fix* the queenside in order to be able to maneuver freely on the other side., where he has the advantage of material. } 23... Qd7 24. Rd3 Qc8 25. Qe4 Qe6 26. Rd5 Kf8 27. c4 Kg8 { Black sees that he now stands in his best defensive position, and therefore waits for white to show how he intends to break through. } 28. b3 Kf8 29. Kd3 Kg8 30. Rd6 Qc8 31. Rd5 Qe6 32. g4 Kf8 33. Qf4 Kg8 34. Qe4 Kf8 { Black persists in waiting for developments. } 35. Ke2 Kg8 36. Kf1 Kf8 37. Kg2 Kg8 38. Kg3 Kf8 { Now that he has completed his march with the king, White is ready to advance. } 39. h5 gxh5 40. gxh5 Qe7 41. Qf5 Kg8 42. Rd7 Bxe5+ { This loses a piece, but Black's position was altogether hopeless. } 43. Kg4 Qf6 44. Nxe5 Qg7+ 45. Kf4 { The interest of this game centers mainly on the opening and on the march of the white king during the final stage of the game. It is an instance of the king becoming a fighting piece, even while the queens are still on the board. } { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "New York"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1918.11.03"]
[Round "10"]
[White "John Stuart Morrison"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Capablanca"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C62"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Steinitz Defense"]
[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Morrison v. Capablanca (Ruy Lopez)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/HqYoX8QJ"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Nc3 Bd7 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bg5 Nf6 9. Qd2 h6 10. Bh4 { An error of judgment. White wants to keep the knight pinned, but it was more important to prevent Black from castling immediately. Bf4 would have done this. } 10... O-O 11. O-O-O { Bold play, but again faulty judgment, unless he intended to play win or lose, throwing safety to the winds. The black bishop at g2 becomes a very powerful attacking piece. The strategical disposition of the black pieces is now far superior to White's, therefore it will be black who will take the offensive. } 11... Re8 12. Rhe1 g5! { Now that the king's rook is in the center, Black can safely advance, since, in order to attack on the kingside, White would have to shift his rooks, which he cannot do as long as Black keeps up the pressure in the center. } 13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Nd5 a6 { Black drives the bishop away so as to *unpin* his pieces and be able to maneuver freely. } 15. Bd3 Be6 { Preparing the onslaught. Black's pieces begin to bear against the king's position. } 16. c3 f5! { Initiating an attack to which there is no reply, and which has for its ultimate object either the winning of the white queen's bishop or cutting it off from the game. } 17. h4 f4 { The bishop is now out of action. White naturally counterattacks violently against the seemingly exposed position of the black king, and, with very good judgment, even offers the bishop. } 18. hxg5! hxg5! { Taking the bishop would be dangerous, if not actually bad, while the text move accomplishes Black's object, which is to put the bishop out of action. } 19. Rh1 Bf7 20. Kb1 { This move unquestionably loses time. Since he would have to retire his bishop to h2 sooner or later, he might have done it immediately. It is doubtful, however, if at this stage of the game it would be possible for White to save the game. } 20... Ne5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 { It was difficult to decide which way to retake. I took with the rook in order to have it prepared for a possible attack against the king. } 22. Bh2 Nf6 23. g3 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Rxe4 25. gxf4 c6 26. Ne3 Qa5 27. c4 Qxd2 28. Rxd2 gxf4 29. Ng4 Bg6 { This forces the king to the corner, where he will be in a mating net. } 30. Ka1 Rae8 { Now at last the queen's rook enters the game and soon the battle is over. } 31. a3 Re1+ 32. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 33. Ka2 Bf7 34. Kb3 d5 { The quickest way to finish the game. } 35. Bxf4 dxc4+ 36. Kb4 c3 37. bxc3 Re4+ 38. c4 Rxc4+ 39. Ka5 Rxf4 40. Rd8+ Kh7 41. Rd7 Be6 { A very lively game. } { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


[Event "New York"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1918.11.01"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Frank James Marshall"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Capablanca"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D64"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Orthodox Defense, Rubinstein Attack"]
[StudyName "Chess Fundamentals"]
[ChapterName "Marshall v. Capablanca (Queen's Gambit Declined)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ZnwEQKyt/s2wreIGg"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Rc1 c6 { This is one of the oldest systems of defense against the queen's gambit. I had played it before in this tournament against Kostic, and no doubt Marshall expected it. At times I change my defenses, or rather systems of defense; on the other hand, during a Tournament, if one of them has given me good results, I generally play it all the time. } 8. Qc2 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Qxc3 b6 13. e4 Bb7 14. Rfe1 Rfd8 { The developing stage can now be said to be complete on both sides. The opening is over and the middle game begins. White, as is generally the case, has obtained the center. Black, on the other hand, is entrenched in his first three ranks. } 15. d5 Nc5! 16. dxe6 Nxe6 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. Nd4! Qe5! 19. Nxc6 Qxc3 20. Rxc3 Rd2 21. Rb1 { A very serious error of judgment. White is under the impression that he has the better game because he is a pawn ahead, but that is not so. The powerful position of the black rook at d2 fully compensates Black for the pawn minus. } 21... Re8 { With this powerful move Black begins, against White's center, an assault which will soon be shifted against the king itself. } 22. e5 g5 23. h4 gxh4 24. Re1 { White cannot stand the slow death any longer. He sees danger everywhere, and wants to avert it by giving up his queenside pawns, expecting to regain his fortunes later on by taking the initiative on the kingside. } 24... Re6! 25. Rec1 Kg7 26. b4 b5 27. a3 Rg6 28. Kf1 Ra2 { Notice the remarkable position of the pieces. White cannot move anything without incurring some loss. } 29. Kg1 h3 30. g3 a6 { Again forcing White to move and to lose something thereby, as all his pieces are tied up. } 31. e6 Rxe6 32. g4 Rh6 33. f3 Rd6 34. Ne7 Rdd2 35. Nf5+ Kf6 36. Nh4 Kg5 37. Nf5 Rg2+ 38. Kf1 h2 39. f4+ Kxf4 { An ending worth very careful study. } { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


