1. e4 { Notes by Stockfish 8 v270317 (minimum 30s/ply) } 1... c5 { With the hope of eventually gaining an extra pawn in the centre which may lead Black to a favourable endgame, after slow and meticulous play. } 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 g6 { Preparing ...Bg6, acting in concert with Black's c5 pawn and Nc6 adding pressure on the d4-square } 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 d6 7. h3 { better is
7.Qd2 Nf6 8.f3 O-O 9.g4 h5 10.g5 Nd7 11.O-O-O Qa5 +/= +0.52
(28 ply) } { Preparing a kingside pawn-attack, despite the fact that the centre is only partially closed.
This move is particularly noteworthy it is clearly not be the best or most theoretically appropriate or in accord with basic principles, and Lasker knows it!
Lasker's decision is designed to destabilize his opponent, Napier, who has chosen 1...c5 in response to Lasker's 1.e4... Black's plan is to meticulously work towards an advantageous endgame by virtue of having an extra pawn in the centre.
Lasker chooses to move 7.h3 - rather than the usual and natural 7.Be2 - preparing a flank attack despite the fact that the centre is not closed, in flagrant contradiction of basic principles of which Lasker is a masterful exponent.
This forces Napier to abandon his original plan which is based on slow, meticulous play designed to reach a favourable endgame, in favour of the required attacking action in the centre theory dictates he undertake in response to a flank attack! } 7... Nf6 { = 0.00 (35 ply) } 8. g4 O-O { Black castle's his King to safety in preparation for his counterattack in the centre. } 9. g5 { better is 9.Bg2
