[Event "Rated Rapid game"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/XNzrs1CH"]
[Date "2020.11.30"]
[White "Repiked"]
[Black "Rawkward"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "1698"]
[BlackElo "1500"]
[TimeControl "600+5"]
[Termination "Time forfeit"]
[Annotator "lichess.org"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E60"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Normal Variation, King's Knight Variation"]
[StudyName "Repiked vs Rawkward"]
[ChapterName "Repiked - Rawkward"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tO1NM1k6/zN4r2ar7"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 { E60 King's Indian Defense: Normal Variation, King's Knight Variation } 3... Bg7 4. Bf4 O-O 5. Nc3 { Nothing much to say, so far. White has established a strong central pawn formation. His Knights are well developed, on "natural" squares, looking at the centre. The dark-squared bishop is outside of the pawn-chain, if White should choose e3 instead of e4. Black's setup is looking at the centre from afar and confident he will be able to challenge it, soon enough. } 5... d5 { I'm not a King's indian player but this is the first move that strikes me...Black is very forceful, here. He could just as easily have chosen 5...d6. So, this tells me that Black is naturally aggressively inclined...The move strikes me as a bit bold, because though Black's King is already castled and White's King is still centrally located, one generally doesn't open lines unless one also has a lead in development. The tone of the game will certainly be different than had Black played 5...d6. } (5... c5) (5... d6) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 { I'm not so sure about this move. It is not a bad move, because a Knight-Bishop trade would not be advantageous to White, but is it the best, i.e. "most active" square? } 7. Bg3?! { (-0.05 → -0.90) Inaccuracy. Be5 was best. } (7. Be5 Bxe5 8. Nxe5 c5 9. e3 Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bc4 Nb6) 7... Nxc3?! { (-0.90 → -0.27) Inaccuracy. c5 was best. } { So, I think Black's strategy is simply to open lines and simplify...But does this exchange leave Black in a better position? I don't think so. You know what they say: only trade if you have to. } (7... c5 8. e3 cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. Be2 Nb6 11. Rc1 Be6 12. O-O) 8. bxc3 c5 { Ok, 9.dxc5 would take the Queens off the board and leave White's queenside pawn structure in a mess. That would be a clear liability in the endgame. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gg7c3] } 9. e3 { White doesn't take the bait. } (9. dxc5 Qxd1+ (9... Bxc3+ 10. Nd2) 10. Rxd1 Bxc3+ 11. Nd2) 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 { White is better than Black here, as far as I am concerned. He has complete dominion over the centre, is ready to castle and has first options on the open c-file and the half -open b-file is his for the taking, obviously. } 10... Qa5+ 11. Nd2? { (0.27 → -0.86) Mistake. Qd2 was best. } { I don't like this type of move, on principle. Entering into a pin at one's own initiative should be more of "last possible" option of defense, as far as I am concerned. The Knight was actively and centrally located at Nf3 and now you have relegated it to a purely defensive role and White's Queen will have to protect it as I presume you want to castle your King to safety? So, I'm not a fan of this move at all. Far better would have been 11.Qd2 because it would have kept Nf3 on a very good square and forced Black to decide if he wanted to keep the Queens on the board. Now, you may say: "the Queen-trade would have taken away my casting privileges". The point is with the Queens off the board and your strong pawn structure, KxQd2 would have been an excellent move because you are moving into the endgame. In other words, with Queens off the board and a strong centre, the King would have been perfectly safe on d2 plus he would have moved to a more central location in preparation for the endgame. } (11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2) 11... Nc6? { (-0.86 → 0.52) Mistake. e5 was best. } { This is inconsistent because now that Nd2 and no longer guarding e5, Black can contest White's centre with 11...e5. } (11... e5 12. Bc4 (12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 { Not a good continutation for Black. }) 12... exd4 13. O-O dxe3 14. fxe3 Bf5 15. Nb3 Qc3 16. Qc1 Nc6 17. Qxc3 Bxc3 18. Rad1) 12. Be2?? { (0.52 → -1.14) Blunder. Bc4 was best. } { White's a2 pawn will be vulnerable at some point... } (12. Bc4 Bf5 13. O-O Rac8 14. Rc1 Qa3 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Rfd8 17. Bh4 Rd7 18. Rfd1 Bh6) 12... Rd8 { Finally activating Black's kingside square, commanding the half-open d-file. } 13. O-O?! { (-1.07 → -1.82) Inaccuracy. Rc1 was best. } { I would say this is the third consecutive "weak" move from White. The first being 11.Nd2, voluntarily pinning the Knight in defense of White's King, the second being the passive 12.Be2 and this one foregoing the more aggressive 13. Rc1 which could have been followed by 14.c4 or b5, perhaps? These are just first impressions but certainly something one might have liked to look at, during the game. } (13. Rc1 e5 (13... Qxa2 14. Bb5 a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rxc6 Bb7 { Looks like this wasn't a proper line for White, so Bc4 would have to be looked at... } 17. Rc2 Qd5 18. f3 { Then again, this would have been playable, I think...It depends were the clocks are... })) 13... b5?? { (-1.82 → 1.44) Blunder. Nxd4 was best. } (13... Nxd4 14. exd4 Rxd4 15. Bc4 Qxd2 16. Qxd2 Rxd2 17. Rad1 Rd4 18. Bd5 Be6 19. Rxd4 Bxd4 20. Bxb7) 14. Nb3 Qb6 15. Qc2 a5? { (0.99 → 2.28) Mistake. Be6 was best. } (15... Be6 16. Rac1 Rac8 17. Qb2 b4 18. Rfd1 a5 19. Nc5 Bd5 20. Na4 Qb7 21. Rc5 Nxd4 22. exd4) 16. Bf3? { (2.28 → 1.07) Mistake. Qc5 was best. } (16. Qc5) 16... Nb4?? { (1.07 → 3.82) Blunder. Bd7 was best. } (16... Bd7) 17. Qc7 Rb8?? { (3.59 → 8.04) Blunder. Qxc7 was best. } (17... Ra6 18. Qxb6 Rxb6 19. Bc7 Rbd6 20. Bxd8 Rxd8) (17... Qxc7 18. Bxc7 Be6 (18... Rd7 19. Bxa8 Rxc7) 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 20. Nxa5 Bxa2 21. Nc6 Nxc6 22. Rxa2 Nxd4 23. exd4 Bxd4 24. Rb1) 18. Qxb8 Qxb8 19. Bxb8 Bf5 20. Bf4 Nd3 21. Rfd1 Nb4 22. e4 Bc8 23. Be5 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Nc6 26. Nxa5 { White wins on time. } 1-0


