Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 75). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 75). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 12. d4 { [%eval 0.67] } { White now takes the opportunity to open up the game, which in turn enables him to be first to the central files with his Rooks.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 76). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 12... cxd4 { [%eval 0.69] } 13. Qxd4 { [%eval 1.0] } 13... dxc4 { [%eval 1.03] } 14. Qxc4 { [%eval 1.0] } 14... Nc6 { [%eval 0.84] } 15. Rfd1 { [%eval 0.73] } 15... Qe8 { [%eval 0.81] } 16. Qf4 { [%eval 0.51] } { The strongest and aesthetically most pleasing moves in chess are often very quiet ones. This innocent-looking Queen move suddenly renders Black’s position most precarious.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (pp. 76-77). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 16... Rc8?! { [%eval 1.29] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rd8. } (16... Rd8) 17. Rd2 { [%eval 0.52] } { Another mouse-like move with the strength of a lion. White doubles on the d file because he can see an entry point on d7.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 77). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 17... Kg7? { [%eval 1.57] } { Mistake. Best move was f6. } (17... f6 18. Rad1) 18. Rad1 { [%eval 1.31] } 18... Ba8 { [%eval 1.66] } 19. Ne5 { [%eval 0.79] } 19... Nxe5 { [%eval 0.91] } 20. Qxe5+ { [%eval 0.9] } 20... f6 { [%eval 0.79] } 21. Qe6 { [%eval 0.85] } 21... Bxg2?! { [%eval 1.58] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Qf7. } (21... Qf7 22. Qe3) 22. Rd7 { [%eval 1.53] } { We now see the immense power of a Rook on the seventh row.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 78). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 22... Rf7?! { [%eval 2.57] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bh3. } (22... Bh3 23. Qxh3) 23. Kxg2 { [%eval 2.22] } 23... Rc5 { [%eval 2.59] } 24. Rxa7 { [%eval 2.39] } 24... b5 { [%eval 2.53] } 25. e3 { [%eval 2.46] } { 1-0 Black resigns. } { To summarize, the use of open files can be broken down into three parts: (i) Take control of the file. (ii) Find a point of entry (this is the important part; without an entry point a file has no value). (iii) Penetrate via the entry point.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (pp. 78-79). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 1-0


