Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 43). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 8... Nf6 { [%eval 0.56] } 9. cxd5 { [%eval 0.48] } 9... cxd5 { [%eval 0.28] } 10. exd5 { [%eval 0.29] } 10... exd5?! { [%eval 0.81] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Qxd5. } (10... Qxd5 11. Nc3) 11. Nc3 { [%eval 0.82] } 11... Be7 { [%eval 0.84] } 12. Qa4+ { [%eval 0.78] } { weak Pawns are only a handicap if they result in the pieces being driven to bad or passive squares in order to defend them.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 44). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 12... Qd7 { [%eval 0.92] } 13. Re1 { [%eval 0.85] } { Always be wary of grabbing material at the cost of the coordination of your pieces.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 44). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 13... Qxa4 { [%eval 1.04] } 14. Nxa4 { [%eval 0.77] } 14... Be6 { [%eval 1.03] } 15. Be3 { [%eval 0.68] } 15... O-O?! { [%eval 1.2] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nd7. } { White's strategy is to use the weakness of the two isolated Pawns to tie down the Black pieces while maximizing the activity of his own.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 45). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } (15... Nd7 16. Be2 O-O 17. Rad1 Rfc8 18. a3 Rc2 19. Bf3 Rd8 20. Re2 Rxe2 21. Bxe2 a5 22. Nc3) 16. Bc5 { [%eval 1.23] } { the Black-squared Bishop is the only piece which cannot be tied down to the defence of Black's isolated pawns...White also wants to use the c5 square as an outpost for his Knight.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 45). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 16... Rfe8 { [%eval 1.3] } 17. Bxe7 { [%eval 0.85] } 17... Rxe7 { [%eval 0.89] } 18. b4 { [%eval 0.86] } { Having just traded the ‘right’ pair of Bishops, White does not want the Black Pawns to run away onto Black squares, for in that case he will have traded the wrong Bishops...fixing weaknesses on squares where they are most readily assailable is particularly common and should always be borne in mind when playing against weak Pawns.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 46). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 18... Kf8 { [%eval 0.86] } 19. Nc5 { [%eval 1.13] } 19... Bc8 { [%eval 1.41] } 20. f3 { [%eval 1.16] } 20... Rea7 { [%eval 1.6] } 21. Re5 { [%eval 1.37] } 21... Bd7 { [%eval 1.63] } 22. Nxd7+?! { [%eval 1.05] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was a4. } { This move is praised in every annotated version of this game. Stupid SF which doesn't understand human chess ! } (22. a4 Bc8) 22... Rxd7 { [%eval 1.11] } 23. Rc1 { [%eval 1.06] } 23... Rd6 { [%eval 1.44] } 24. Rc7 { [%eval 1.31] } 24... Nd7 { [%eval 1.46] } 25. Re2 { [%eval 1.19] } 25... g6 { [%eval 1.17] } { The necessity to guard two isolated Pawns has reduced Black to Pawn moves alone. White now only has to add one more weight, namely his King, and the scales must tip.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 48). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 26. Kf2 { [%eval 1.13] } 26... h5 { [%eval 1.25] } 27. f4 { [%eval 0.96] } 27... h4 { [%eval 1.23] } 28. Kf3 { [%eval 1.08] } 28... f5 { [%eval 1.5] } 29. Ke3 { [%eval 1.25] } 29... d4+ { [%eval 1.7] } 30. Kd2 { [%eval 1.73] } 30... Nb6? { [%eval 3.0] } { Mistake. Best move was a5. } (30... a5 31. b5) 31. Ree7 { [%eval 2.93] } 31... Nd5 { [%eval 2.78] } 32. Rf7+ { [%eval 2.84] } 32... Ke8 { [%eval 2.48] } 33. Rb7 { [%eval 2.41] } 33... Nxf4?? { [%eval 11.54] } { Blunder. Best move was Rb6. } (33... Rb6) 34. Bc4 { [%eval 10.81] } { 1-0 Black resigns. } { The quaint final position shows the immense power of even a small coordinated force. Despite having a Pawn more, Black is quite helpless in face of the threat of Rg7 and Rg8 mate. This classic game shows with perfect simplicity all the steps necessary to transform a superior Pawn structure into a win. The one underlying theme running through the whole game is the way the Black pieces are systematically deprived of all mobility.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (pp. 50-51). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle. } 1-0


