Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (pp. 7-8). Dover Publications. Édition du Kindle.
Starting with this simple move, White will slowly but surely establish domination over Black's light coloured squares and use them as a highway into Black's territory and the primary agents of the mating net his king will be trapped in. } 12... Bb6 { [%eval 0.19] } 13. a4 { [%eval 0.11] } 13... Rfd8 { [%eval 0.47] } (13... a5 14. Ba3 (14. bxa5 Bc7 15. Ba3 Bd6 16. Qb3 Nc5)) 14. Qc2 { [%eval 0.0] } 14... Rac8?! { [%eval 0.91] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was a5. } (14... Nf8) (14... a5 15. bxa5 Bxa5 16. Ba3 Qe6 17. Kg2 Ra7 18. Be2 Rda8 19. Bc4 Qe8 20. Bb3 b5 21. Nf3) 15. Be2 { [%eval 0.72] } { A classy move since instinct and training would push me to finish development, instead Botvinnik eyes the c4 square. } 15... c5 { [%eval 1.06] } 16. b5 { [%eval 1.16] } 16... Ne8 { [%eval 1.21] } 17. Nc4 { [%eval 1.07] } 17... Nd6?! { [%eval 1.68] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bc7. } { Botvinnik, is conducting a classic light squared strategy, since the dark squared bishop doesn't have a clear role in light squared domination he trades it at the first opportunity. } (17... Bc7 18. Kg2 Ndf6 19. a5 Nd6 20. Bg5 Nxc4 21. Bxc4 h6 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. Qe2 b6 24. axb6) 18. Bg5 { [%eval 1.8] } 18... f6 { [%eval 2.13] } { denying the trade but improving whites scope on the a2 g8 diagonal. The black king will feel caged soon. } 19. Be3 { [%eval 2.26] } 19... Nxc4 { [%eval 2.26] } 20. Bxc4+ { [%eval 2.58] } 20... Kh8 { [%eval 2.56] } 21. a5 { [%eval 2.44] } 21... Bc7 { [%eval 2.48] } 22. Rfd1 { [%eval 2.25] } 22... Nf8 { [%eval 2.38] } 23. Qa2 { [%eval 2.03] } 23... Rxd1+ { [%eval 2.23] } 24. Rxd1 { [%eval 2.1] } 24... Rd8 { [%eval 2.44] } 25. Rxd8 { [%eval 2.42] } 25... Bxd8 { [%eval 2.23] } { usually trading all the rooks can free up space for the cramped side, here though it's not enough. White light squared highway is too effective for black to deal with. Note the absence of meaningful counter play. } 26. a6 { [%eval 2.21] } 26... b6 { [%eval 2.24] } 27. Kg2 { [%eval 2.24] } 27... Qd7 { [%eval 2.32] } 28. Qe2 { [%eval 2.24] } 28... Ng6 { [%eval 2.27] } 29. Bb3 { [%eval 2.28] } 29... Ne7 { [%eval 2.35] } 30. Qc4 { [%eval 2.36] } 30... h6?? { [%eval 5.04] } { Blunder. Best move was Qe8. } (30... Qe8 31. Qe6 Bc7 32. h4 Qf8 33. h5 h6 34. Bd5 Qd8 35. c4 Nc8 36. f3 Bb8 37. Kf2) 31. Qf7 { [%eval 2.39] } { Nice attractive domination, now blacks next move is a mistake but in these kinds of one sided positions it's impossible to defend like a computer forever. We sharpen our sword with tactics but what of our shield rusting in the corner. Defending is grueling. } 31... Kh7 { [%eval 9.09] } 32. Bc4 { [%eval 8.6] } 32... Qd6 { [%eval 8.09] } 33. h4?? { [%eval 3.21] } { Blunder. Best move was g4. } (33. g4) 33... Qd1?? { [%eval 10.62] } { Blunder. Best move was Qd7. } (33... Qd7) 34. Qe8 { [%eval 10.15] } 34... f5 { [%eval 15.52] } 35. exf5 { [%eval 14.37] } 35... Nxf5?! { [%eval #3] } { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Best move was Qd6. } (35... Qd6 36. Be6) 36. Bg8+ { [%eval #2] } 36... Kh8 { [%eval #2] } 37. Bf7+ { [%eval #1] } { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


