1. d4 { Notes by J. R. Capablanca } 1... d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Be6 8. O-O Be7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bg5 d4 { I had never seen this variation before and I therefore
thought for a long time in order to make up my mind as to
whether I should play Bxf6 or Ne4. I finally decided upon the
latter move as the safest course. } 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 { It is my position that this position is not good
for Black, though perhaps there may be no way to force a win. } 14. Qa4 O-O 15. Qb5 { Threatening not only the b Pawn, but also
Qg5, exchanging Queens. } 15... Rab8 16. Rfd1 h6 17. Ne1 Rfe8 18. Rd2 { Bxc6 would only lead to a draw. Viz, 18.Bxc6 bxc6 19.Qxc6
Rec8 followed by Rxb2. } 18... Bg4 19. Rc1 Re5 20. Qd3 { If Rc5 Qg5 with
a winning game. } 20... Rbe8 21. Bf3 Bxf3 { Black could have tried to
keep up the attack by playing h5. The text move simplifies
matters and easily leads to a draw. 22.Nxf3 Re4 23.Rc4 Qe6
24.Nxd4 Nxd4 } 1/2-1/2


