key here.)
IOW - his fear is understandable, but his action is misguided. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } (8... b6) 9. Qe2 { [%eval 0.84] [%eval 0.85] } { This strikes me as a bit odd, instead of 9.Ne5...Did you want to play your cards close to the chest and keep your options open, before casting? } { One of the ideas of this structure is to put pressure on the half-open e file if a K-side attack does not develop. It was this thought that led to to put my Q on the e file.
Before making this move, SF at depth 26 lists Ne5 best at 1.0, followed by Bc2, Qe2, and h4 all at 0.9.
After making the move, the SF eval stays at 0.9. } { [%clk 0:04:40] } 9... Nh5 { [%eval 1.35] [%eval 1.21] } { Black continues losing time on rather useless moves, instead of developing. } { [%clk 0:03:59] } 10. g3 { [%eval 1.27] [%eval 1.32] [%clk 0:04:39] } 10... Qf6?! { [%eval 1.85] } { Inaccuracy. Nf6 was best. } { [%eval 1.82] } { I have got to say, I don't believe I have ever seen Black play this way against the London. He seems totally out of his depth here, playing one poor move after another. This Qf6 stuff will more likely than Knight come back to bite him on the backside... } { [%clk 0:03:22] } (10... Nf6 11. O-O-O) 11. Ne5 { [%eval 1.84] [%eval 1.72] [%clk 0:04:18] } 11... g6 { [%eval 1.7] [%eval 1.88] [%clk 0:02:54] } 12. h3 { [%eval 1.52] [%eval 1.47] } { Objectively this move isn't very good. It succeeded in scaring him to play Ng7, but he didn't have to do that when the f4 pawn is unprotected if I play g4.
