 } 33... Rb2+? { [%eval 8.08] } { Mistake. Rxb1 was best. } { [%eval 7.83] } { (5.28 → 7.83) Inaccuracy. Rxb1 was best. } { Simply horrible...Totally misguided. Now Black not only needlessly exchanges an important piece but also loses his advanced-pawn and gives White a passed-pawn!! } { [%clk 0:00:34] } (33... Rxb1 34. Kxb1) 34. Rxb2 { [%eval 7.72] [%eval 7.57] [%clk 0:02:16] } 34... axb2 { [%eval 7.32] [%eval 7.66] [%clk 0:00:36] } 35. Qxb2 { [%eval 7.33] [%eval 6.91] [%clk 0:02:18] } 35... Qc7 { [%eval 8.31] [%eval 7.66] [%clk 0:00:33] } 36. Kc3 { [%eval 6.95] [%eval 7.16] [%clk 0:02:18] } 36... Nh5 { [%eval 9.16] [%eval 9.0] [%clk 0:00:30] } 37. Qb5 { [%eval 7.98] [%eval 7.82] } { With lots of time on your clock and a crushing advantage, I think you "relaxed" a bit here and missed 37. Nxe6...I happen to have my Kotov handy and he calls this type of thing (though yours is neither a mistake or blunder) "Diziness due to success". } { Actually I did not miss the N capture. My thought was the pawn wasn't going anywhere.
If I capture right away, then his Q has to move. He has a check on a5, and I can't interpose my Q, so would have to retreat my K.
Instead I play in "Comfortable" style, moving my Q to b5 to capture space/take squares away from his Q, the only active piece he has.
Anyway, it's always a good idea in endings to post the Q to a commanding position. Better to do that than snatch a pawn right away. } { Can confirm that's my kind of move. what there is a hint of counterplay take the squares away. } { [%clk 0:02:12] } 37... Qa7 { [%eval 10.5] [%eval 10.48] [%clk 0:00:20] } 38. a4 { [%eval 9.39] [%eval 9.06] } { Not taking any chances but perhaps playing a bit too fast, considering the time left on your clock? } { Yeah, I wasn't looking at how much time I had left. OTOH, my position is so dominating that I can win many ways and am not concerned about SF "best" moves at this point.
This is more space capturing and prophylaxis. I want my Q to wander over to his K-side. After this move he doesn't have Qa3+ where my K has to move and he can follow with moves along the 3rd rank, where his c pawn may provide additional support and threats. } { [%clk 0:02:11] } 38... f4? { [%eval #25] } { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Ng7 was best. } { [%eval #17] } { (9.06 → Mate in 17) Checkmate is now unavoidable. Ng7 was best. } { [%clk 0:00:18] } (38... Ng7 39. a5) 39. Qe8+ { [%eval #41] [%eval #16] } { Having shored up my Q-side, I move in for the kill, if I can find it. If not, the a pawn will easily win after piece exchanges. } { [%clk 0:02:07] } 39... Kg7 { [%eval #42] [%eval #16] [%clk 0:00:17] } 40. Nxe6+ { [%eval 77.76] [%eval #15] [%clk 0:02:09] } 40... Kh7 { [%eval 70.72] [%eval 68.27] [%clk 0:00:13] } 41. Nf8+ { [%eval 64.31] [%eval 14.45] [%clk 0:02:06] } 41... Kh6?! { [%eval #1] } { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Kg7 was best. } { [%eval #1] } { (14.45 → Mate in 1) Checkmate is now unavoidable. Kg7 was best. } { [%clk 0:00:13] } (41... Kg7 42. Ne6+) 42. Qxg6# { White wins by checkmate. } { How sweet it is! I love these little mates. } { [%clk 0:02:03] } 1-0


