1. e4 { [%eval 0.0] } 1... d5 { [%eval 0.24] } 2. exd5 { [%eval 0.44] } 2... Nf6 { [%eval 0.56] } { Hoping to get a sharp Portuguese variation, as recommended in Moret's Black Opening Repertoire. Or an Icelandic Gambit if you play aggressively with pawns in the center. } 3. Bb5+ { [%eval 0.64] } { You dash my hopes. (Interestingly, in 3 tries to get a Portuguese, it has never happened.)
This check is recommended in Play it Simple e4, and has a tendency to suck the fun out of Black's game. } 3... Bd7 { [%eval 0.53] } 4. Bc4 { [%eval 0.64] } { My opening sources suggest Be2 as standard. It prevents my next move. However, c4 is an OK square for the B if White expects to lose the pawn on d5.
SR considers the two moves to be equal. } 4... Bg4 { [%eval 0.7] } { I get to play the move that is played in the Portuguese after all. } 5. f3 { [%eval 0.4] } { I see that SF considers this the best move.
But it does take away a potentially good square from the Nf1 and slightly weakens the K-side pawn shield.
From comments you made, it seems the resulting pawn formation left you puzzled for much of the rest of the game. } { That's odd...Stockfish prefers both 5.Bb5+ and 5.Nf3, on my end. The Lichess master-play database does give 5.f3 as the most frequent move by far. It does have its drawbacks, such as robing the King's Night of its natural square and, perhaps just as importantly, weakening the King's eventual castle-defences, notably by opening the g1-a7 diagonal. On a gut-level, I just didn't want to walk into a pin and let you push me around while keeping the initiative. ;D } 5... Bc8?! { [%eval 1.07] } { Inaccuracy. Bf5 was best. } { [This follows the sample game in Moret's First Black Opening Repertoire.] } { I'm not familiar with that book (other than its notoriety) and will take you at your word but I find the move horrible. You had a lead in development and are now clearly behind. It just doesn't make any sense to me, from a principles-perspective. } (5... Bf5 6. g4 Bc8 7. Nc3 c6 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. d4 e5 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 { Here despite Black being down a pawn after the coming capture on e5, SF rates the position as essentially equal. Kind of a surprise to me, because while I can see some structural weaknesses in White's position, I don't see any that can immediately be exploited in this queenless ending. } 11... Nxe5 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Nfxd7 14. Ke2 { And now SF at depth 27 has four separate moves for Black resulting in flat equality. Each of them involves playing f5 or h5 immediately or in the next few moves to take advantage of White's kingside pawn weakness.
[SO I GUESS I'VE LEARNED A LITTLE SOMETHING ABOUT THIS OPENING DUE TO THIS GAME REVIEW.] }) 6. Nc3 { [%eval 1.02] } 6... Nbd7 { [%eval 0.36] } 7. d4 { [%eval 0.75] } 7... Nb6 { [%eval 0.52] } 8. Bb3 { [%eval 0.68] } 8... Nbxd5 { [%eval 0.67] } 9. Ne4 { [%eval 0.48] } 9... Bf5 { [%eval 0.62] } { I considered about 8 different moves here, and a few minutes before time control picked this one as giving the best chances for an active position.
Except. . . } 10. c4 { [%eval 0.48] } { I forgot to "danger check" for this move, which I would have done first in an OTB game. Now it looks like Black has to retreat or give up material. } 10... Nb6 { [%eval 0.64] } { SF says this is an inaccuracy. It suggests the sharp and dynamic } (10... Nxe4 11. fxe4 Bxe4 12. cxd5 Bxg2 13. Qc2 Bxd5 14. Qe2 e6 15. Nf3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 { Black has given up a piece for 3 pawns. SF evaluates this as +0.1. }) 11. Nxf6+ { [%eval 0.77] } 11... gxf6 { [%eval 1.09] [SF says 11...exf6 is slightly better.]
I used to play the Bronstein CaroKann in tournaments 20+ years ago. So I chose this capture to try to confuse my inexperienced opponent. } { You are much more erudite than I in such matters but, once again, this strikes me as an unpricipled move. You might say general principle holds that capturing towards the centre is best practice, but in this case it gives you three pawn islands instead of two as well as forever weakening your kingside fortress and doing nothing for Black's development. 11...exf6 would have at least had the virtue of activating Black's dsb. Where will you put it now? Logically, I would say h6 but that will cost you time you have already lost by moving around your lsb so much in the opening. For all those reasons, I think 11...exf6 was much better than 11...gxf6, not simply "slightly" better. Sure, Stockfish may rate it as slightly better but it sees far ahead into the future, deeply looking at the combinatorial possibilities which compensate for strategical or positional innacuracies. Humans don't work like that, at least not at our level. Looking at the board, White is clearly ahead with a strong centre and lots of space for his pieces against Black's oddly placed Nb6 and Bf5 which will soon enough be chased out of that square by the eventual Ng3. } 12. Ne2 { [%eval 0.97] } 12... c6 { [%eval 0.86] } 13. O-O { [%eval 1.18] } 13... Bg7 { [%eval 1.56] [At depth 25 this is tied for 2nd best move (+1.0)]
At this point I evaluated that Black is actually several tempo down from a typical Bronstein Caro and White has a more active pawn center than typical, and I became very negative about my prospects. I adopted a fatalistic attitude of just playing moves to either try to scare up counterplay or confuse you, to avoid being wiped off the board early. } { To me, this is an ineffectual move and is precisely what I was talking about when I critisized your 11...gxf6. What else is left for your dsb, unless you are prepared to waste even more time finding a better square for it? Its natural square in this situation is Bh6, but of course it would be unprotected so Black would have to prepare with h5 which was implied by your choice of 11...gxf6, it seems to me. But you didn't follow through and played the most conservative move, hoping things would eventually fall into place, it seems to me. I can understand the impulse, and even the execution, but nothing to write home about, my friend. As far as I am concerned, you were terribly off in this opening...Your responses showed that they didn't belong to an overarching strategy or even to sound opening principles. This all strikes me as rather hazardous play, to be brutally frank. After 13...Bg7, White has a significant advantage. So, I agree with you that by 13...Bg7, things were starting to look fairly grim to Black. No wonder you found this game excrutiatingly long. ;D } 14. Ng3?! { [%eval 0.6] } { Inaccuracy. Nf4 was best. } (14. Nf4) 14... Bg6 { [%eval 0.53] } 15. Be3 { [%eval 0.68] } 15... Qc7 { [%eval 1.12] } 16. Qe2?! { [%eval 0.5] } { Inaccuracy. f4 was best. } (16. f4 f5) 16... O-O-O?! { [%eval 1.1] } { Inaccuracy. f5 was best. } (16... f5 17. Qd2) 17. Rac1?? { [%eval -1.14] } { Blunder. Qd2 was best. } { I typically have trouble finding something intelligent to do with my rooks or choosing the right one to move, especially when both are on the back-rank. } (17. Qd2 f5 18. Ne2 Kb8 19. Rfd1 e5 20. d5 c5 21. a4 Nc8 22. a5 f4 23. Bf2 a6 { This line shows White going for an attack on the Q-side, which I thought would be a good plan for you. Here Black has managed to play ...c5 and ...a6 which holds back the pawn storm some. }) 17... h5?? { [%eval 1.14] } { Blunder. f5 was best. } (17... f5 18. f4 Bxd4 19. Rfd1 e5 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Qf2 c5 22. Bc2 Kb8 23. Bxf5 Bxf5 24. Nxf5) 18. Ne4?! { [%eval 0.43] } { Inaccuracy. Qd2 was best. } (18. Qd2 h4 19. Ne2 h3 20. g3 Kb8 21. d5 e5 22. a4 Nc8 23. a5 Ne7 24. Bc5 Nf5) 18... f5 { [%eval 0.31] } 19. c5?! { [%eval -0.36] } { Inaccuracy. Nc3 was best. } { [I was happy to see this. I thought it was a positional blunder, blocking off the c file as an attack lane for a long time, and allowing my worst piece either to centralize or be exchanged.] } (19. Nc3) 19... Nd5 { [%eval 0.0] } (19... fxe4 { At deeper search depths SF says this dynamic move is about 0.4 better than the move chosen if Black finds the best line after White's obvious reply moves, the position will be very close to equal.
[In my fatalistic mindset, I did not see the possibility of the g1-a7 diagonal opening up for my benefit.] } 20. cxb6 Qxb6 21. d5 Bd4 { and SF rates Black as better here. }) 20. Bxd5 { [%eval 0.0] } 20... Rxd5 { [%eval 0.48] } (20... fxe4 { shows at depth to be better. } 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. fxe4 { and now Black can exploit the weakness of White's d pawn to equalize. } 22... Bxd4 23. Bxd4 Rxd4 24. Rxf7 Qe5 25. Rf5 Qxe4 26. Re5 Qxe2 27. Rxe2 Rhd8) 21. Nc3 { [%eval 0.5] } 21... Rdd8?! { [%eval 1.42] } { Inaccuracy. Rxd4 was best. } (21... Rxd4 22. Bxd4 { SF suggests the exchange sac here, but Black has to play perfectly to stay in the game. }) (21... Rd7 { At deeper search SF considers this better than my move to d8, and better than the exchange sac, leading to equality (!?). I'd have to look at the suggested lines top see why d7 is a much better square for my R. }) 22. Qc4?! { [%eval 0.56] } { Inaccuracy. Rfd1 was best. } (22. Rfd1 { This move would solidify your center (d4 pawn) and allow you to push pawns on the Q-side, which I thought was your best plan going forward. And I thought it would be very difficult to meet, given your space advantage on the Q-side and the fact that any pawn move there by me leave a horrendous position. }) 22... f4 { [%eval 0.96] } 23. Bf2 { [%eval 0.84] } { Maybe it was obvious to you, but SF says this was the only move that allows White to keep the advantage. } 23... h4 { [%eval 1.2] } 24. h3 { [%eval 1.02] } 24... Rd7 { [%eval 1.51] } 25. d5 { [%eval 1.2] } 25... Bxc3 { [%eval 1.14] } { I thought this was the only move for me to stay in the game, but I hated to give up this B. } 26. Qxc3 { [%eval 1.28] } 26... Qd8 { [%eval 1.76] } 27. dxc6 { [%eval 1.54] } { I was very proud of myself for starting this move sequence } 27... bxc6 { [%eval 1.78] } 28. Qe5 { [%eval 1.52] } { I now felt in control of the game } { Yes. This is about the point where I adopted "the Slaughter" to name my analysis game study. The only thing I liked is that your c5 pawn is an impediment to your R attacking up the c file. } 28... Bd3?! { [%eval 2.11] } { Inaccuracy. Rd5 was best. } (28... Rd5) 29. Rfe1 { [%eval 1.65] } 29... e6?! { [%eval 2.49] } { Inaccuracy. f6 was best. } (29... f6 30. Qxf4 e5 31. Qa4 Bb5 32. Qe4 Rd5 33. Rc3 Qd7 34. Qg6 Rf8 35. Bxh4 Qf7 36. Qxf7) 30. Qxf4 { [%eval 2.09] } 30... Qe7?! { [%eval 3.13] } { Inaccuracy. Qc7 was best. } (30... Qc7) 31. Qa4?! { [%eval 2.32] } { Inaccuracy. Bd4 was best. } (31. Bd4 Rg8 32. Bf6 Qf8 33. Rc3 Rg6 34. Bxh4 Qh6 35. Bg3 Qxf4 36. Bxf4 Bb5 37. Bd6 Rh6) 31... Bb5 { [%eval 2.48] } 32. Qf4 { [%eval 2.46] } 32... Bd3 { [%eval 3.07] } 33. Bd4 { [%eval 3.22] } { Missed it the first time around } 33... Rh5 { [%eval 3.4] } 34. Bf6 { [%eval 2.82] } 34... Qf8 { [%eval 3.01] } 35. Bxh4 { [%eval 2.92] } { Things were looking pretty good to me, at this point. } 35... Rf5 { [%eval 2.61] } 36. Qh2?! { [%eval 1.75] } { Inaccuracy. Qe3 was best. } { I wanted to hang on to the diagonal but Qh2 really started my slide downwards } { Yes, I thought that h2 was a very limiting square for your Q, so it gave me a little hope. } (36. Qe3) 36... Qg7?! { [%eval 2.45] } { Inaccuracy. Qh8 was best. } (36... Qh8 37. Bg3) 37. Rc3 { [%eval 2.26] } 37... Rxf3?? { [%eval 4.73] } { Blunder. e5 was best. } { How on earth could I have missed 38.Rb3, especially since I had kept my Queen on that h2-b8 diagonal?! } { Yes, I saw 38.Rb3 before I made this move. I was almost ready to resign if you had played 38. Rb3. A few days later I went back to see if I could find a defense, and thought I found a way to stay in the game in a sharp position. But a SF evaluation after the game showed I overlooked a crushing move for you early in this "saving" line.
My move is an objective blunder, but I think it was the right choice from a practical and psychological standpoint. } (37... e5 38. Qg3 Qxg3 39. Bxg3 f6 40. Bf2 Rh5 41. h4 Bb5 42. Rc2 Rhh7 43. g4 Rd3 44. Kg2 { In this objective better line for me, you are simply up 2 pawns with a passer in an endgame. Not a position to play for. }) 38. Kh1?? { [%eval 1.13] } { Blunder. Rb3 was best. } (38. Rb3 Qd4+ 39. Kh1 Rb7 40. Rxb7 Kxb7 41. gxf3 Qxh4 42. Rd1 Qh7 43. Qd6 Qxh3+ 44. Kg1 Ba6) 38... Rf1+ { [%eval 1.27] } 39. Rxf1 { [%eval 1.08] } 39... Bxf1 { [%eval 1.08] } 40. Rc1?! { [%eval 0.47] } { Inaccuracy. Qg3 was best. } (40. Qg3 Qxg3 41. Rxg3 Bc4 42. Bf6 Rd1+ 43. Kh2 Rf1 44. Bc3 Bxa2 45. h4 Rf4 46. Kh3 Rf1) 40... Be2 { [%eval 0.92] } 41. Qf4 { [%eval 0.84] } 41... Qxb2?! { [%eval 1.57] } { Inaccuracy. Qd4 was best. } (41... Qd4 { I did look at this move some, but with a different follow up than the moves here from SF. I didn't want to just trade off queens, and leave you with a pawn edge when there were Rooks on the board with the opposite Bs. } 42. Qg5 Qxb2 43. Kh2 { (with a sharp game continuing, although Black is much better now than he has been for most of the game.) }) 42. Bg3? { [%eval 0.12] } { Mistake. Re1 was best. } (42. Re1) 42... Qxc1+ { [%eval 0.4] } { I looked for alternate moves here, but concluded that if I kept Qs on the board and tried to actively attack you, you would get an advantage on the dark squares around my K. Either by posting a Q on d6, which would be decisive if I let that happen, or by taking your Q to the back rank where you could have various mating threats. So to the endgame we go. } 43. Qxc1 { [%eval 0.32] } 43... Rd1+ { [%eval 0.44] } 44. Qxd1 { [%eval 0.25] } 44... Bxd1 { [%eval 0.43] } 45. Be5 { [%eval 0.16] } 45... Kd7 { [%eval 0.5] } 46. Bf6 { [%eval 0.5] } 46... a5 { [%eval 0.5] } 47. g4 { [%eval 0.13] } 47... a4 { [%eval 0.16] } 48. a3 { [%eval 0.35] } 48... Ke8 { [%eval 0.5] } 49. Kg2 { [%eval 0.5] } 49... Kf8 { [%eval 0.5] } 50. Kg