{ I did this analysis after you had already made the bad King move. But I was curious to see if I could find any decent response to your best reply. Since I didn't "have to" face it, I didn't try to find any holes in my initial analysis. I'm showing this because the mini-K march that is featured shows the kind of provocative maneuver that tickles my soul. }
37... Rxf3 { It was here that White should have played . . . } 38. Rb3 { was best, threatening mate on b8 and the B retreat to block the file just loses the Rf3. Black has some other tries to resist for a few moves, but none are any good.
ADDITIONAL THOUGHTS: } 38... Rb7 { is what I thought would be the best and might allow Black to survive for awhile. } 39. Rxb7 { In trying to find a defense, I was so focused on mate threats on c7 and b8, that I didn't even consider other weaknesses, like the c6 pawn. } (39. Qd6! { , which I did not consider, is crushing.
The next alt line is one that I did consider. }) (39. Rd1 { might be a better try than trading Rs on b7. I only looked at one line of play here, which turns out better for White than the variations above } 39... Rxb3 40. axb3 Qd4+ 41. Kh1 Rf1+ (41... Rf4 { looks like it could be better, since White doesn't get to activate his Q right away. } 42. Bg3 Rf1+ (42... Rf5 43. Bd6 Qe3 (43... Qxb2? 44. Qg3)) 43. Rxf1 Bxf1 { But the next B move for White is strong. } 44. Bb8! Qd7 45. Qg3 Kb7 46. Qf4 Bd3 47. Bd6 Bb5 48. Qf6 { and White has a clear advantage here. }) 42. Rxf1 Bxf1 43. Qg3 Qd7 44. Qg8+ Kb7 45. Bg3 Ka6 46. h4 Be2 { and I think that Harry is going to make the difference for White. }) 39... Kxb7 40. Bd8 { and
maybe } 40... Ka6 { Is what I focused on. This King walk invites White remove his Q from defense and perhaps allow Black to get a perpetual. (BUT again Qd6! crushes.)
Or other moves I considered briefly . . . } (40... Qg3 { or }) (40... Rg3 { or }) (40... e5 41. Qxe5 Qxe5 (41... f6 { gives White an opportunity to go wrong but ends up with a White 2 pawn advantage again } 42. Qc7+ Qxc7 43. Bxc7 Rf5) 42. Rxe5 { and White has a good advantage }) 41. Qc7 Qd4+ 42. Kh1 { (After 41. Qc7 and 42.Kh1 SF eval is 0.00) Looks like Black can bet a perpetual. } 42... Rxh3+ 43. gxh3 Be4+ 44. Rxe4 Qxe4+ 45. Kh2 Qe2+ 46. Kg3 Qd3+ 47. Kg4 Qf5+ 48. Kg3 Qd3+ 49. Kf4 Qd4+ 50. Kg5 Qg7+ *


