45. Be5 Kb7 46. g4 Ka6 47. Kg2 Ka5 48. Kg3 Kb4 49. Bd6 Ka3 50. Kf4 Kxa2? { and now SF says that White has a significant advantage. But let's follow some moves. } (50... Kb4 { is better than taking the pawn. } 51. Ke5 Be2 52. Bf8 Bf3 53. Kf4 Bd5 { and this is still practically equal. }) 51. Ke5 Bf3 52. Kf6 Bg2 53. h4 Bf3 54. g5 Bh5 55. Be5 Kb3 56. Kg7 { With Black's K far away, White is able to combine the operation of his K and h pawn to make progress. } 56... Bg6 { Best per SF. } 57. Kh6 { And now the h pawn will advance, and if not taken right away, g6 will force exchanges. Either way Black has to give up his B. } 57... Kc4 58. h5 Bxh5 59. Kxh5 Kd5 60. Bc7 e5 61. Kg4 Ke6 62. Bd8 a6 63. Ba5 e4 64. Kf4 e3 65. Kxe3 Kf5 66. Kd4 Ke6 67. Bb4 Kf5 68. Bc3 Ke6 69. Be1 Kf5 70. Kc4 { And the White K goes on a K-side tour to mop up the pawns there an pave the way for his c pawn to Q. } (70. Bd2 Ke6) 70... Ke6 71. Kb4 Kd5 72. Bf2 Ke6 73. Ka5 *


