1. Nf3 { [%eval 0.06] } 1... g6 { [%eval 0.25] } 2. e4 { [%eval 0.27] } 2... Bg7 { [%eval 0.6] } 3. d4 { [%eval 0.5] } 3... d6 { [%eval 0.64] } 4. Be2 { [%eval 0.38] } 4... Nf6 { [%eval 0.67] } 5. Nc3 { [%eval 0.35] } 5... O-O { [%eval 0.69] } 6. O-O { [%eval 0.41] } 6... c6 { [%eval 0.51] } 7. a4 { [%eval 0.53] } 7... a5 { [%eval 0.84] } 8. Be3 { [%eval 0.69] } 8... Na6 { [%eval 1.01] } 9. Nd2 { [%eval 0.65] } 9... Nb4 { [%eval 0.58] } 10. Ncb1 { [%eval 0.52] } 10... e5 { [%eval 1.03] } 11. dxe5 { [%eval 1.07] } 11... dxe5 { [%eval 0.7] } 12. Na3 { [%eval 0.79] } 12... Be6 { [%eval 0.68] } { There is as yet no question of bad Bishops or weak squares. Indeed, neither player can reasonably claim to hold the advantage,
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 123). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 13. Nac4 { [%eval 0.87] } { With threats to invade on b6 as well as the attack on the e Pawn. Black can now maintain the balance with 1…Nd7, but instead mistakenly resolves to eliminate the annoying Knight.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 123). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 13... Bxc4 { [%eval 1.3] } 14. Bxc4 { [%eval 0.96] } 14... Qd7 { [%eval 1.38] } 15. f3 { [%eval 1.49] } 15... Nh5 { [%eval 2.09] } 16. g3 { [%eval 1.7] } 16... Rad8 { [%eval 2.13] } 17. Bb3 { [%eval 2.06] } { this move marks the turning of the tide. Black has reached the top of the hill and is about to roll all the way down again. Without his White-squared Bishop he has no way of making any further impression on the White position,
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 124). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } { Reaching an active looking position with very little room to grow is a concept I call "maximized position" this happens quite a bit in practice, usually baring tactics one side can slowly push the active forces back gaining space. I'd imagine the way to avoid this is to look over so many High level games that you know where the pieces go.When Gm's beat Im's this is a very common trend. The Im at some point makes active looking moves that don't fit into an overal game plan, and the GM slowy pushes and dominates the key squares on the board. } 17... c5 { [%eval 2.25] } 18. Qe2 { [%eval 1.86] } { White can afford to take things very calmly. His domination of the White squares is probably already a winning advantage.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 125). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 18... b6 { [%eval 2.17] } 19. Rfd1 { [%eval 1.71] } 19... Qc7 { [%eval 1.83] } 20. c3 { [%eval 1.78] } 20... Nc6 { [%eval 1.72] } 21. Nc4 { [%eval 1.74] } 21... Nf6 { [%eval 1.74] } 22. Na3 { [%eval 1.71] } 22... Na7 { [%eval 1.66] } 23. Qc4 { [%eval 1.61] } 23... Rfe8 { [%eval 1.69] } 24. Kg2 { [%eval 1.57] } 24... h6 { [%eval 1.75] } 25. Rxd8 { [%eval 1.42] } { Having posted all his pieces (including his King) on good squares, White now has to tackle the problem of how to infiltrate. There is no obvious way to seize the open file, so he trades Rooks to create more free space.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 126). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 25... Rxd8 { [%eval 1.33] } 26. Rd1 { [%eval 1.26] } 26... Rxd1 { [%eval 1.08] } 27. Bxd1 { [%eval 1.04] } 27... Bf8 { [%eval 1.64] } 28. Be2 { [%eval 1.45] } 28... Kg7 { [%eval 1.52] } 29. Qb3 { [%eval 1.63] } 29... Ne8 { [%eval 1.78] } 30. Ba6 { [%eval 1.79] } { The first hint of penetration. There is an immediate threat of 19. Nc4 winning the b Pawn (Black no longer has Nc8 as a defense), together with the long-term idea Qd5, Qa8, and Bb7 winning the Knight on a7.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 126). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 30... Nd6 { [%eval 2.46] } 31. Qd5 { [%eval 2.24] } 31... Ne8?? { [%eval 4.77] } { Blunder. Best move was f6. } (31... f6 32. Nc4) 32. Nc4 { [%eval 4.2] } 32... Nf6 { [%eval 4.16] } 33. Qxe5 { [%eval 4.0] } 33... Qd8 { [%eval 4.09] } 34. Bf2? { [%eval 2.5] } { Mistake. Best move was Bf4. } (34. Bf4) 34... g5?! { [%eval 3.43] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nc6. } (34... Nc6) 35. Bb7 { [%eval 3.71] } 35... Kh8?! { [%eval 5.9] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was b5. } (35... b5 36. axb5 Nxb5 37. Bc6 Nc7 38. Nxa5 Ne6 39. Nc4 Kg8 40. Ne3 Ng7 41. Nf5 Nxf5 42. Qxf5) 36. Bd5?! { [%eval 3.81] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Qf5. } (36. Qf5 Bg7 37. e5 Qd7 38. Be4 Qxf5 39. Bxf5 Nd5 40. Be4 Ne7 41. Nxb6 Bxe5 42. Bxc5 f5) 36... Kg8 { [%eval 3.81] } 37. Qf5 { [%eval 3.42] } { 1-0 Black resigns. } { a warning to those who would willingly accept a bad Bishop and a few weak squares in return for the slightest glimpse of an attack. As stressed earlier in the book, attacks must be built on the basis of a definite superiority in your position, either in development or in structure. To try to conjure up an attack out of thin air by artificial means is simply asking for trouble.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 127). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 1-0


