Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 128). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 20... Kh8 { [%eval 0.81] } 21. Bd5 { [%eval 0.73] } 21... Bxd5 { [%eval 0.94] } 22. exd5 { [%eval 0.76] } 22... f5 { [%eval 0.82] } 23. c4 { [%eval 0.83] } 23... Rae8 { [%eval 1.0] } 24. Rd1 { [%eval 0.59] } 24... f4 { [%eval 0.96] } 25. axb6 { [%eval 0.64] } 25... axb6 { [%eval 0.94] } 26. Qe4 { [%eval 0.93] } { Compare this position with that after 18.g3. White has made all kinds of positional gains: outpost on e4, good Bishop v. bad Bishop, protected passed Pawn etc. And Black? He has been telegraphing his intention to deliver mate for some time, but has grossly underestimated his opponent’s defensive possibilities.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 129). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 26... Qd7 { [%eval 0.8] } 27. Re1 { [%eval 0.59] } 27... Qf7?! { [%eval 1.47] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was b5. } (27... b5 28. cxb5 Qxb5 29. Ra7 Qb8 30. Ra3 Qb7 31. Rc3 Rc8 32. b3 Qf7 33. Re2 Rb8 34. Ba3) 28. Re2?! { [%eval 0.69] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was g4. } (28. g4 Qf6 29. Bd2 h5 30. gxh5 Qg5+ 31. Kh1 Qxh5 32. Ra7 Rf6 33. f3 g5 34. Rg1 Rh6) 28... g5?! { [%eval 1.44] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Qd7. } (28... Qd7 29. f3 b5 30. Bd2 bxc4 31. g4 Qd6 32. Bc3 Ra8 33. Rxa8 Rxa8 34. Qxc4 Rd8 35. Qe4) 29. g4 { [%eval 1.49] } { Not only sealing up the Kingside, but also fixing yet another Pawn on a Black square.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 130). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 29... Qd7?! { [%eval 2.06] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Kg8. } (29... Kg8 30. Bd2) 30. f3 { [%eval 1.85] } { Completing his defensive program. We now see the difference between strategy and attack. Attacks can be repulsed, but positional advantages do not suddenly vanish without trace. Petrosian’s quiet but logical play has left him with a stranglehold on the White squares which he will be able to exploit now that Black’s threats have dried up.
Stean, Michael. Simple Chess: New Algebraic Edition (Dover Chess) (p. 130). Dover Publications. Kindle Edition. } 30... Ra8 { [%eval 2.01] } 31. Rxa8 { [%eval 2.01] } 31... Rxa8 { [%eval 2.09] } 32. Bd2 { [%eval 2.0] } 32... Re8 { [%eval 2.32] } 33. Bc3 { [%eval 1.85] } 33... Qd6 { [%eval 2.42] } 34. Re1 { [%eval 1.83] } 34... h6? { [%eval 3.18] } { Mistake. Best move was Kg8. } (34... Kg8) 35. Ra1 { [%eval 2.67] } 35... Rf8? { [%eval 4.54] } { Mistake. Best move was Qd7. } (35... Qd7 36. Qg6) 36. Ra7 { [%eval 4.81] } 36... Re8 { [%eval 4.18] } 37. Qf5 { [%eval 3.7] } 37... b5?? { [%eval 8.68] } { Blunder. Best move was Qf6. } (37... Qf6 38. Rb7) 38. Rd7 { [%eval 8.38] } 38... Qf8 { [%eval 8.16] } 39. Qxf8+ { [%eval 6.17] } 39... Rxf8?! { [%eval 10.76] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bxf8. } (39... Bxf8 40. cxb5) 40. cxb5 { [%eval 10.82] } 40... Rb8 { [%eval 20.55] } 41. Rxg7 { [%eval 14.04] } { 1-0 Black resigns. } { A danger of studying tactics and mates exclusively is if someone plays chess like petrosian against us, our entire skill set would be collecting dust in the attic.
The way of playing chess described in this book is one I find quite a bit when playing against 2300 + opponents.
I often wind up down a pawn after being outplayed strategically. I'm then defending a difficult ending where my opponent can only win or draw. } 1-0


