1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 { Preparing d4. } 3... g6 { Continuing the thematic pressure on the d4-square, though 3...d6 would be of great defensive value. } 4. d4 cxd4 { Now Black has an extra centre pawn but White has the more open and freer game he accepted as a trade-off for the centre-pawn imbalance. The question is: can White capitalize on the open position or will the centre-pawn imbalance eventually turn to Black's advantage? } 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 d6 7. h3 { White begins a pawn-attack on the kingside, despite the fact that the centre is not fixed and only partly closed. A premature flank attack is, however, usually immediately answered by a forceful counterattack in the centre which would require Black immediately change his game-strategy. } 7... Nf6 8. g4 O-O { Black removes his king from the centre, in preparation for the centre counterattack he intends on mounting against White whose early flank operations require a quick and vigorous response. } 1-0


