[Event "Berlin"]
[Site "Berlin GER"]
[Date "1920.12.06"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Siegbert Tarrasch"]
[Black "Savielly Tartakower"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D08"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Albin Countergambit, Tartakower Defense"]
[StudyName "Tarrasch - Tartakower (Berlin, 1920) QGD Albin Countergambit"]
[ChapterName "Siegbert Tarrasch - Savielly Tartakower"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ax73Chxi/4aT47L9j"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]

{ In this study, we see how White's attempt to open up the center is met with a countergambit in the centre superficially reminiscent of the Falkbeer Counter Gambit in the King's Gambit game. But Black is slow to develop and White quickly converts a slight advantage into a more substantial one as Black castles queenside while struggling to both maintain his central pawn and capture White's. But White's position is better and Black's only hope, a passed pawn, won't present White with enough of a problem to dampen his offensive against the beleaguered Black King's position. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 { Along with its counterpart, e4, this move is one of the two methods White has at its disposable to open up the game. The c4 is not really gambitted since } 2... e5 { Albin's Counter Gambit. } (2... dxc4 3. e3 b5 4. a4 c6 (4... Bd7 5. axb5 Bxb5 6. b3) 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Qf3 { Winning a piece and illustrating why the c4 pawn is not really gambitted. }) 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 (4. e3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 dxe3 { and Black is ahead. } 6. Bxb4 (6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. Bxb4 exf2+ 8. Kxf2 Qh4+ 9. g3 Qd4+) 6... exf2+ 7. Ke2 fxg1=N+) 4... c5 { This move contributes nothing to the development of Black's forces and White already has a not insignificant advantage. } (4... Nc6 5. Nbd2 g6 (5... Bf5 6. a3)) 5. e3 Nc6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bd3 Nge7 8. Nbd2 Bg4 9. Qb3 Qc7 10. O-O O-O-O { In an attempt to mobilize his pieces as he struggles to both maintain his d4-pawn and capture White's e5-pawn. } 11. Re1 Ng6 12. h3 Be6 13. Be4 Ngxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 { White now has a significant advantage over Black, who now has an isolated d-pawn and whose King and Queen are both vulnerable. } 15. Nf3 Qc5 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bxd6 Rxd6 19. Ne5 Rhd8 { White now has a commanding advantage and Black's only hope lies with his passed pawn. } 20. Qa4 d3 21. b4 Qd4 22. Nxc6 Rxc6 { Sacrificing the Exchange in the hopes that his passed pawn may provide compensation for the material loss. But his King is now critically exposed and White's attack against the Black regent's position can hardly fail. } 23. Qxc6+ Kb8 24. c5 d2 25. Red1 Bf5 26. Qb5+ Kc7 27. Qa5+ Kb8 28. b5 Bc2 29. b6 Rd7 30. bxa7+ Ka8 31. c6 Rd5 32. c7 Bf5 33. c8=Q+ Bxc8 34. Qc7 Rb5 35. Qxc8+ Kxa7 36. a4 Rc5 37. Qg4 Qxa1 38. Rxa1 Rc1+ 39. Qd1 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


