1. e4 e5 2. d4 { This is premature in that it hands over the initiative without proper compensation to Black who will easily enough play the freeing d5. } 2... exd4 { This opens up the long diagonal for Black's dsb which will soon enough be fianchettoed on g7. } 3. Qxd4 Nc6 4. Qe3 g6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4) 5. Bd2 Bg7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. O-O-O O-O 8. f3 { Protecting e4 but weakening e3. This chain of pawns may eventually prove problematic to White's lsb as they stand on the same coloured squares. } 8... d5 9. Qc5 dxe4 10. Bg5 Qe8 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nxe4 Bg7 13. Bb5 Qe5 { Forcing the exchange of the Queens while maintaining the advantage of the Bishop pair. } 14. Qxe5 Nxe5 15. Ne2 a6 { Starting to restrict the Bishop's range. } 16. Bd3 f5 { Both kicking the pawn away from its nice outpost and completing a light-squared pawn-chain further restricting White's lsb's range. } 17. N4c3 Be6 18. Kb1 Rad8 19. Nf4 Bf7 20. Be2 Nc6 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Rd1 Re8 { Black wants to keep his Rook which will play an active role in the coming kingside attack against the White King's defensive position. } 23. Bf1 b5 { Further restricting the range of White's lsb. } 24. Nd3 Bd4 25. Ne2 Bb6 26. b3 Kg7 { Holding the Bishop pair who have a commanding influence over both colours, Black's King feel secure enough to begin centralizing earlier than is more commonly the case. } 27. c3 Kf6 { Covering the vital e5-square which now frees Black's Nc6 as it no longer has to guard that square. } 28. Kc2 (28. Nb4 Ne7 29. Nc1 h6 30. Be2 Ba5) 28... Ne7 29. Nec1 Nd5 30. Kb2 { Black now has a significant advantage as his pieces are placed to great advantage while White's pieces are hampering each other's movement } 30... b4 31. Nxb4 Ne3 32. Re1 Nc4+ 33. Bxc4 Rxe1 34. Bxa6 Rg1 35. g3 Rg2+ 36. Ka3 Rxh2 37. Ne2 Rg2 38. Nc2 g5 39. Bd3 h5 40. Kb4 Bf2 41. a4 c5+ 42. Kb5 Bxb3 43. a5 c4 44. Bxc4 Bxc2 45. a6 Bd1 46. Nd4 Bxd4 47. cxd4 Bxf3 48. d5 Be2 49. Bxe2 Rxe2 50. a7 Ra2 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


