1. e4 { White anchors a pawn in the centre and opens lines for his pieces } 1... e5 { Fighting for the centre as whoever controls it has more mobility as hampers his opponent's efforts to get his own pieces working effectively together. } 2. Nf3 { Developing the Knight towards the centre with an attack against Black's e5 pawn } 2... Nc6 { Developing the Knight towards the centre as well as protecting his vital e5-pawn } 3. Bc4 { Develops this piece with a threat against Black's vulnerable f7 square and prepares for castling } 3... Bc5 { Same general comments and is in agreement with the general principle according to which a piece must be developed to its most effective location in the least amount of time. } 4. c3 { Preparing for d4, which will establish a superior pawn centre. This move also clears the way for Qb3, with a Q+B battery aimed at the vulnerable f7 pawn. This move, however, robs White's queenside Knight of its natural square. } 4... Qe7 { Develops a piece while parrying the threat against f7. } 5. O-O { Securing the king and mobilizing a Rook. } 5... d6 { Shoring up e5 and activating Black's lsb. } 6. d4 { Inviting the exchange which would leave White with the superior pawn centre as well as freeing up the c3 square for White's queenside Knight. } 6... Bb6 { Black is in no hurry, White centre is attacked three times and is quite shaky. } 7. a4 { Trying to set a trap for Black's dsb when he should continue with his development } 7... a6 { Preparing a retreat for Black's dsb. } 8. a5 Ba7 9. h3 { Permanently weakens the pawn structure by loosening it because of a perceived threat (pin). Black can now entertain ideas of sacking a piece in order to expose White's king. } 9... Nf6 { Developing the Knight with an attack on the e-pawn, preparing castling. } 10. dxe5 Nxe5 { Black is more than happy to comply as he is better developped and the resulting open lines will favour him over Black. } 11. Nxe5 { White removes Black's powerful Ne5 but in so doing loses the defender of his castled position. } 11... Qxe5 { The e5 square White lost his Knight for is now occupied by an even stronger piece. } 12. Nd2 { A shallow tactic hoping to win Black's Queen for the price of a measly pawn. } 12... Bxh3 (12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qxe4 14. Re1) 13. gxh3 Qg3+ { fxQb3 is impossible because the f-pawn is pinned to White's King by Black's Ba7. White's position is now utterly desparate and he soon resigns. } 14. Kh1 Qxh3+ 15. Kg1 Ng4 16. Nf3 Qg3+ 17. Kh1 Bxf2 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


