1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { White is going after a strong centre-pawn formation, putting pressure on Black's vulnerable f7-pawn at the same time } 3... Bc5 4. c3 Bb6 { Anticipating d4, yet remaining on an excellent diagonal. } 5. d4 { White now has the superior centre-pawn formation but it is attacked three times and, as such, is by no means stable. } 5... Qe7 6. O-O Nf6 { Develops with a threat against e4 } (6... exd4 7. cxd4 Qxe4 8. Re1 { winning Black's Queen }) 7. d5 { Kicking Black's queenside Knight away from its strong post but very much limiting the range and power of its lsb while increasing the range and power of Black's dsb! In the opening, pawn moves should really serve piece development. } 7... Nb8 { Moving to the side of the board would unduly expose the awkwardly placed Knight to attack } 8. Bd3 { loses time instead of developing another piece } 8... d6 { Shores up e5 as well as activating Black's lsb } 9. h3 { Purportedly to guard against ...Bg4, pinning White's Knight to its Queen, but this move weakens the White King's pawn fortress. } 9... h6 { Black has not yet castled, so this move is an attacking one, in preparation of a g5-4 advance against White's kingside. } 10. Qe2 g5 { (Stockfish does not recomment this move, prefering Nbd7)
In order to g4. } (10... Nbd7) 11. Nh2 g4 12. hxg4 Rg8 13. Bxh6 Nxg4 14. Be3 Nxh2 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qh3 17. g3 Rh8 18. f3 Bxe3+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


