1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Continuing White's attack against Black's e5-pawn by targetting its defender, hoping to induce ...d6 after which White would obtain the superior centre with d4. } 3... Nf6 { Counterattacking White's own e-pawn } 4. O-O { Eschewing the defence of his e4 pawn whose loss after ...Nxe4 will be easily enough be compensated for. If ...d6, then d4 immediately gives White the better centre anyway. } 4... Nxe4 5. d4 { White prefers to recapture the lost pawn with developing + attacking moves rather than simply via Re1 and Nxe5. } 5... Be7 6. Qe2 { Opens d1, for the Rook. } 6... Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 (7... dxc6 8. dxe5 Nf5 9. Rd1 { In this line, White stands better than in the one played. }) 8. dxe5 Nb7 9. Nc3 O-O { Black will now seek to play the liberating d5 while White's play focuses on preventing it. } 1-0


