14... g6 { White's Knight is simply too powerful on his perch and can't be allowed to stay there. But this will create "weak squares" on both f6 and h6, so-called because no longer protected by Black pawns. These squares can therefore be safely occupied by White's pieces, in theory. } 15. Nxe7+ { White further weakens f6 and h6 by depriving them of Black's dsb. These squares can therefore now be safely occupied by White's pieces, in theory. } 15... Qxe7 16. Be3 N8g7 17. O-O-O c5 { White will now seek to gain an approach to Black's weak f6 and h6 squares. } 18. d4 exd4 19. cxd4 { Black believes he is mounting an effective attack against the White King's defensive position but he is helping White obtain his approach to Black's vulnerable f6 and h6 squares. } 19... c4 *


