1. d4 { [%eval 0.25] } { A40 Queen's Pawn } 1... c6 { [%eval 0.43] } 2. Bf4 { [%eval 0.16] } 2... d5 { [%eval 0.5] } 3. Nf3 { [%eval 0.35] } 3... Bf5 { [%eval 0.2] } 4. c3 { [%eval 0.15] } 4... e6 { [%eval 0.14] } 5. Nbd2 { [%eval -0.01] } 5... Bd6 { [%eval 0.16] } 6. Bxd6 { [%eval 0.18] } { I haven't been playing the London very long but I specifically learned that the recommended move is Bg3, rather than Bxd6 as this allows Black to develop the Queen to a nice central Qd6. When White hasn't prophylactically h3, for the h2 Bishop retreat, then more typical is the Bg3 retreat which if it leads to Bxg3 is followed by hxBg3 giving White command of the half-open h-file and eyes on Black's h7, often targeted by White's lsb at d3, White martialling his forces for a kingside attack after locking up the centre. } (6. Bg3 Bxg3 7. hxg3) 6... Qxd6 { [%eval 0.15] } 7. e3 { [%eval -0.05] } 7... Nf6 { [%eval 0.25] } 8. Nh4 { [%eval 0.14] } 8... O-O { [%eval 0.21] } 9. Nxf5 { [%eval 0.15] } 9... exf5 { [%eval 0.13] } 10. Bd3 { [%eval -0.07] } 10... f4 { [%eval 0.27] } 11. O-O { [%eval 0.0] } 11... fxe3 { [%eval 0.0] } 12. fxe3 { [%eval 0.0] } 12... Re8 { [%eval 0.02] } 13. Qf3 { [%eval -0.07] } 13... Nbd7 { [%eval 0.0] } 14. e4 { [%eval 0.0] } 14... dxe4 { [%eval 0.0] } 15. Nxe4 { [%eval -0.27] } 15... Nxe4 { [%eval -0.33] } 16. Bxe4 { [%eval -0.3] } 16... Nf6 { [%eval 0.0] } 17. Rae1 { [%eval -0.11] } 17... Re7 { [%eval 0.0] } 18. Bd3 { [%eval 0.0] } 18... Rae8 { [%eval 0.0] } 19. Rxe7 { [%eval 0.0] } 19... Qxe7 { [%eval 0.0] } 20. h3 { [%eval 0.0] } 20... h5 { [%eval 0.0] } 21. Qf5 { [%eval 0.0] } 21... Qe3+ { [%eval 0.0] } 22. Kh1 { [%eval 0.0] } 22... Qe6 { [%eval -0.15] } 23. Qg5 { [%eval -0.11] } 23... Qe3 { [%eval -0.13] } 24. Qf5 { [%eval -0.02] } 24... Qe6 { [%eval 0.0] } 25. Qf2? { [%eval -1.41] } { (0.00 → -1.34) Mistake. Best move was Qg5. } (25. Qg5 b5 (25... Qxa2 26. Rxf6) (25... a6) 26. Kg1 Kf8 27. Rf3 Qd6 28. Rf1) 25... Qxa2 { [%eval -1.17] } 26. Qg3 { [%eval -1.3