1. d4 { [%clk 0:49:47] } 1... c6 { [%clk 0:50:11] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:49:27] } 2... d5 { [%clk 0:50:23] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 0:49:24] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 0:50:27] } 4. Nf3 { [%clk 0:48:39] } 4... e6 { [%clk 0:50:28] } 5. Bg5 { [%clk 0:48:33] } 5... h6 { h6 is also an option for black here, I just liked the idea behind dxc4.
EDITED: I am trying to avoid playing moves like a3/a6/h3/h6 at all costs where I have another possibility, so maybe that's why. I just like to play this line. I know that it is highly theoretical, but there are many interesting positions that might occur after dxc4. The theory is about 20+ moves there, so there is a lot of things to study, but there is a great course by Erwin L'Ami. } { And why is the idea behind ...dxc4 better or more suitable to your tastes than the one behind ...h6? Could you elaborate a bit, please? I believe I would also tend to favour 5...dxc4 - even though it trades a centre pawn for a flank pawn leaving you 1 against two - if only because ...h6 disrupts the pawn fortress and its consequences are even more disruptive of it, irrespective of what line White chooses. Having said that, ...h6 appears to be much more common, in master play. I imagine that is at least in part because White must choose between two different alternatives whereas playing ...dxc4 poses no such problem for White, e4 (with the threat of e5) appearing to be an automatic and natural response. Perhaps it is because the resulting game is more "drawish"? I don't know. In any event, for that very reason I would argue studying the 5...h6 line is worthy of some time. I imagine you would want to check the database for behaviour in your playing pool. } (5... dxc4 { [%clk 0:50:16] } 6. e4 { [%clk 0:47:56] } 6... b5 { If e5, then ...h6, I imagine. But I wonder if 7...h6 would be as propitious a time as 5...h6? Something to think about, perhaps? } { [%clk 0:50:02] } 7. a4 { here my theory ended. I knew only some ideas about development like Qb6, Be7, Bb4, Nd7, but I didn't know a proper move order. } { [%clk 0:46:40] } (7. e5 h6 8. Bxf6 (8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 (9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. exf6)) 8... gxf6) 7... Bb4 { [%clk 0:47:08] } (7... Qb6 { this move is a mainline here. Next moves could be something like } 8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Nd7 (10... a6)) 8. Be2 { [%clk 0:46:49] } (8. e5 h6 9. exf6 hxg5 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. h4 g4 12. Ne5 Rxg7) 8... Qb6 { [%clk 0:47:00] } 9. Bxf6 { My thoughts in a game were that I played Qb6 too fast here and then I realize, that Bxf6 is a threat. I was scared, but now I can see that even some grandmasters play like that.
EDIT: I was scared that I might be losing here because white could have a permanent static advantage and during a game, I didn't think about my advantages, that's why. But now I know that in this position black is perfectly fine, so avoiding to play h6 was a good decision :) } { To avoid misunderstand on my part, scared of what? Do you mean the structural damage that would follow BxNf6, ...gxBf6? It seems to me Black has sufficient compensation: a stronger pawn centre, the Bishop pair and the half-open g-file he can control at a moment's notice by Rg8. } { [%clk 0:37:00] } 9... gxf6 { [%clk 0:47:15] } 10. O-O { [%clk 0:36:10] } 10... Bb7 (10... Nd7 { This was an inaccuracy again because now white can play d5.
EDITED: I mean that Bb7 is a better option here. Because after 11.d5 cxd5 12.exd5 white is better. } { Ok, but if he does, isn't the simple and natural cxd5 better than the ...Ne5? } { [%clk 0:47:28] } 11. Qc2 { [%clk 0:35:00] } (11. d5 { Here was a game played between La Flair and Weldon which continues } 11... cxd5 (11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Ne5 (12... cxd5) 13. Nd4 exd5 14. exd5 cxd5 15. axb5 $16) 12. exd5) 11... Bb7 { [%clk 0:47:10] } 12. b3 { [%clk 0:32:59] } 12... c5 { Here is the first crucial moment in a game. I didn't want to play cxb3, because I made some calculations here and it didn't look good for me. I chose c5, because I didn't find a better move here, to be honest. I knew that simplifying a game here could only help simultanist and I wanted to keep some kind of pressure on the queenside. My idea was that after bxc4 cxd4 I still have some kind of pressure here, but after careful study, I could see that white has here good options. This is a position for further study.
EDITED: I am trying to avoid working with the engine in positions like this because it might give you bad habits. It is a practical problem what to play after cxb3 Qxb3, which will probably happen because what white could play here? And after that move, what are your options here? The engine is saying a5, because he is calculating 20 moves ahead and he knows that white has nothing here, but how do I know that during a game? In a practice, I am giving my opponent an opportunity to simplify a game and start to attack my weaknesses. Look at this 'computer' line with a5. I am not that good in calculating to find all white's moves here. Even e5 is a possibility, so I stopped my calculation process after evaluating position cxb3 Qxb3 and said to myself ok, I don't like that anyway so let's find something else, because there might be another idea. I had a lot of time here, so maybe I could calculate it all, but I don't have a skill to do so yet. I am trying to keep things simple. If something doesn't work, let's find something else. Maybe that is a mistake, but well, I am trying to learn something during analysis :) And no offense, but I know that I can check lines with an engine. } { You should reproduce your calculation because saying it didn't look good to you is no substitute for actually working it out with the engine and seeing if your conclusion was correct or not, it seems to me. } { [%clk 0:41:53] } (12... cxb3 13. Qxb3 { Exactly because of this line. What are my options here? } 13... Bxc3 (13... a5 14. Rac1 (14. Rfc1 Bxc3 15. Rxc3 b4 16. Rc4 O-O-O) 14... Rb8 15. axb5 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 cxb5 17. Bxb5) 14. Qxc3 b4 15. Qe3 a5 $14) 13. Nxb5 { [%clk 0:24:43] } (13. bxc4 cxd4 14. Nxb5 Nc5 15. Nfxd4 Bxe4 $13) (13. axb5 cxd4 14. Na4 Qxb5 15. bxc4 Qc6 $14) (13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 $14) 13... a6 { 13. Nxb5 surprised me because I didn't even consider this move as an option for white in my calculations. a6 is the only move here, I cannot allow this knight to stay here. } { [%clk 0:40:23] } 14. dxc5 { I felt like maybe he should take back his knight first anyway because now my c pawn is looking very good. I was really happy to be honest, because I maintain my goal which was to keep things complicated. } { [%clk 0:18:57] } 14... Qxc5 { Bxc5 is also a possibility, but I liked my bishop on b4 square and I wanted to maintain a dark square control on two diagonals instead of making some kind of battery. White has to make a retreat now anyway and I felt that I am for certain equal. } { [%cal Gb4e1,Gc5g1,Gc5a3] [%clk 0:40:26] } 15. Nbd4 { [%clk 0:16:52] } 15... c3 { And here is the second crucial moment in a game. Bxc4 is a real threat and black has to react. cxb3 didn't do anything and even more, it was solving all white's troubles. I spent here some time and decided to go for a c3 and I was trying to find a good way for white to counter this right away but didn't find anything. Black has a passed pawn on a dark square and here I created a basic plan which was some ideas like: Ne5, Rg8, O-O-O. } { [%clk 0:37:23] } (15... cxb3 16. Qxb3 $16) 16. Bc4 { The idea behind Bc4 is not so clear for me. In a simultaine white didn't have a lot of time to analyze my moves and possibilities and white clearly underestimate Ne5 and I was happy that I can start to make my moves with extra tempo. } { [%clk 0:11:20] } 16... Ne5 { [%clk 0:37:12] } 17. Be2 { [%clk 0:09:19] } 17... O-O-O { Now I had time to simply castle. I could go short or long, but Rg8 was looking really good and my king was safe on the queenside. Now I could more pressure on a d file, but first I wanted to make my king more safe. } { [%clk 0:37:08] } 18. Rfd1 { [%clk 0:08:40] } 18... Kb8 { [%clk 0:36:44] } 19. a5 { [%clk 0:06:52] } 19... Ka7 { [%clk 0:36:22] } 20. Ra4 { [%clk 0:06:42] } 20... Rhg8 { Here I made all the moves which I wanted. I felt that white has to react to Rg8 } { [%clk 0:35:52] } 21. g3 { [%clk 0:04:09] } 21... Nxf3+ { I considered Nxf3+ a few moves before, but I felt that my piece is better than white's piece, so I wanted to force him to solve this problem by Nxe5 and after Qxe5 I could start to put pressure on e4. But now I thought that maybe it's time to go with that. After g3 my white squared bishop is a great piece and I wanted to simplify position because actually all of my pieces are on a good squares. } { [%clk 0:35:50] } 22. Nxf3 { [%clk 0:03:59] } (22. Bxf3 { would be a mistake because of } 22... Rxd4) 22... Rxd1+ { Here I spent a lot of time just to check everything, cool down and one more time I tried to evaluate my position and chances to win. I decided to go simple way, exchange what I can and push my passed pawn. The question was how to do that, but here I was focus strictly on evaluating counterattack chances, but I didn't see anything so I was happy.
Main task for me was to activate my worst piece - Rg8 and I decided that it would be the best on open d-file, so at first I had to exchange some stuff. } { [%clk 0:26:58] } 23. Bxd1 { [%clk 0:03:59] } 23... Rd8 { [%clk 0:27:02] } 24. Be2 { [%clk 0:04:03] } 24... h5 { Another position where I wasn't sure what to play. Bxa5 is a possibility, but then Rc4 is a serious threat and this capture gives white side opportunity to start a counterattack, so I wanted to avoid that. With nothing better I decided to push harry, because why not. } { [%clk 0:23:55] } (24... f5 { I completely missed that move, and I didn't even consider it. Lines are looking good and each one is a win. } 25. exf5 (25. e5 Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Rd2) (25. Bd3 Rxd3 26. Qxd3 c2 27. Ra1 c1=Q+) (25. Rxb4 Qxb4 26. exf5 Be4 27. Qc1 c2) 25... Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Rd2 27. Qxd2 (27. Qe4 Qxf2+) 27... cxd2) 25. Ra1 { [%clk 0:03:40] } 25... Bxa5 { Now I could take, because Rc4 is not a threat. } { [%clk 0:23:55] } 26. b4 { I completely don't get the idea behind this move. I guess that maybe Bb6 is so strong that white has to sacrifice a pawn here to avoid that? I am not sure about this move. } { [%clk 0:02:16] } 26... Bxb4 { Free pawn, two passed pawns, looks like a win. } { [%clk 0:23:57] } 27. Rc1 { [%clk 0:01:50] } 27... a5 { I was talking to myself: play it slowly, play it accurately, play it patiently, slowly build advantage and try to prevent any counterplay. And of course, an inaccuracy, I should manuever my bishop to Bb6. } { [%clk 0:21:57] } 28. Rd1 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 28... Rxd1+ { [%clk 0:21:41] } 29. Bxd1 { [%clk 0:01:53] } 29... Qc6 { Pawn on e4 is dropping now } { [%clk 0:19:41] } 30. Ne1 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 30... Qxe4 { [%clk 0:19:37] } 31. Qxe4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 31... Bxe4 { Great exchange for me, two passed pawns, two bishops, safe king. } { [%clk 0:19:26] } 32. f4 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 32... Kb6 { [%clk 0:17:19] } 33. Kf2 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 33... Kc5 { [%clk 0:16:49] } 34. Ke3 { [%clk 0:00:52] } 34... Bg6 { [%clk 0:16:05] } 35. Nd3+ { [%clk 0:00:53] } 35... Kc4 { [%clk 0:15:21] } 36. Ne1 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 36... Bc5+ { [%clk 0:13:49] } 37. Ke2 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 37... Be4 { I am not good at endgames. This whole maneuver was not necessary, but I wanted to support my a pawn. I am not happy how I played endgame, but I was trying to realize my plan. } { [%clk 0:13:16] } 38. h4 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 38... Bc6 { [%clk 0:12:55] } 39. Nc2 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 39... a4 { [%clk 0:12:42] } 40. Ke1 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 40... a3 { [%clk 0:12:23] } 41. Bxh5 { [%clk 0:00:38] } 41... a2 { [%clk 0:12:23] } (41... Kb3 { Wins faster } 42. Bd1 a2 43. Na1+ Kb2 44. Nb3 c2) 42. Bxf7 { I was a little bit scared about this check with a skewer, so I tried to prevent that. But black has here better move. } { [%clk 0:00:43] } 42... Bd5 { [%clk 0:10:48] } (42... Kd3 43. Na1 c2 44. Bg6+ f5 45. Nxc2 Kxc2) 43. h5 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 43... Kb3 { [%clk 0:09:37] } 44. Na1+ { [%clk 0:00:53] } 44... Kb2 { [%clk 0:09:37] } 45. h6 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 45... c2 { [%clk 0:09:26] } 46. Nxc2 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 46... Kxc2 { [%clk 0:09:40] } 47. h7 { With a forced checkmate on Qd1# after Ke7 } { [%clk 0:00:42] } 47... a1=Q+ { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%clk 0:09:48] })) 6. Bxf6 (6. Bh4 dxc4 (6... g5 7. Bg3 dxc4 8. e4 b5) 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3 b5 9. Be2 Bb7) 6... gxf6 0-1


