[Event "Lichtenhein - Morphy (New York, 1857): The importance of quick development in open games"]
[Date "2019.12.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C56"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Scotch Gambit, Max Lange Attack"]
[StudyName "Lichtenhein - Morphy (New York, 1857)"]
[ChapterName "The importance of quick development in open games"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kOGCLNgr/rz8pogZ0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[UTCDate "2019.12.06"]
[UTCTime "03:54:40"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { Though 5.e5 is an attacking move, it is not a developing one. To justify such a loss of time in the opening phase of an open game, Black's most be forced to reply with a strictly defensive move. In the current position, however, Black now has the possibility of outpacing his opponent in development. } 5... d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black is now one move ahead in development with 5 tempi on the board as compared to White who still only has 4 tempi on the board. White's premature e5 attack is directly responsible for this unfortunate delay. } *


