[StudyName "Blackburne - Steinitz (London, 1863) Evans Gambit"]
[ChapterName "A very common centre pawn formation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/nVkpRekH/qGtSzJNZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[FEN "8/8/3p4/8/3PP3/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.12.21"]
[UTCTime "15:39:59"]

{ This White e4/d4, Black d6 pawn formation is extremely common and all serious students of the game should understand its implications:

1- White's domination of the centre allows for the possibility of quick tranfer of pieces from one side of the board to the other

2- Black's cross-board communication, however, is cut and the faulty liaison between sides proves both time-consuming and problematical. }
 *


[Event "Blackburne - Steinitz (London, 1863) Evans Gambit: The implications of the pawn formation explained"]
[Date "2019.12.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Blackburne - Steinitz (London, 1863) Evans Gambit"]
[ChapterName "The implications of the pawn formation explained"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/nVkpRekH/pOOuMbKs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[FEN "8/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/P4PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.12.21"]
[UTCTime "15:44:47"]

{ As a logical consequence of this structure, both sides have different strategic goals:

1- White will play on the flanks, preferably on the kingside.
2- Black, on the other hand, must undermine White's centre, the only area of the board where his forces can combine with greatest effect. }
 *


