[FEN "r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/1bnp4/8/2BPP3/5N2/P4PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.12.21"]
[UTCTime "15:35:31"]

9. Nc3 { Developing a piece - à la Morphy - rather than rushing into a direct attack with, say, 9.d5 which would curtail White light-squares Bishop's effectiveness as well as fixing White's centre pawns. } 9... Bg4 10. Bb5 { The intuitive response to this would be the natural 10...Bd7 which, unfortunately, would abandon Black's attack against White's centre. } 10... Kf8 { Here, Steinitz rather astonishingly and counter-intuitively unflinchingly forfeits his castling privileges, so convinced is he that the position requires he stay the course and subordinate momentary concerns to higher strategical imperatives. } 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ba3 { Black's position now looks very precarious to the untrained eye. } 12... Bxf3 { Both losing the Bishop pair and inviting White to gxBf3, opening up the g-file, seemingly favouring White's attack against the Black King's defensive position. } *


