1. e4 { [%eval 0.24] } 1... e5 { [%eval 0.37] } 2. Nf3 { [%eval 0.26] } 2... Nc6 { [%eval 0.15] } 3. Bc4 { [%eval 0.21] } 3... Nf6 { [%eval 0.28] } 4. d3 { [%eval 0.27] } { With this move, White signals he is in no hurry to create the strong pawn centre which would result from d4, after first preparing it by c3. } (4. c3 Nxe4) 4... Bc5 { [%eval 0.28] } { Carlsen, Magnus - Nakamura, Hikaru, 1-0, London Classic 3rd, 2011, https://lichess.org/gNvEgzI7 } 5. c3 { [%eval 0.26] } { C53 Italian Game: Classical Variation, Giuoco Pianissimo } { Move order is important, for it changes the very nature of the game } 5... O-O { [%eval 0.24] } 6. O-O { [%eval 0.32] } 6... a6 { [%eval 0.64] } { The players are now out of book, d6 shoring up Black's centre e5 pawn and activating his lsb was best. } 7. b4?! { [%eval 0.0] } { Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son - Karthikeyan, P2., 1-0, Asian Rapid 2015, https://lichess.org/Y7mI6183 } { (0.64 → 0.00) Inaccuracy. Best move was d4. } { d4, attacking Black's dsb with tempo and stacking a strong claim on the centre was best as well as being thematic to this opening } (7. d4 Be7 8. d5 Nb8 9. Bd3 d6 10. c4 c6 11. Be3 Bg4) 7... Ba7 { [%eval 0.33] } { Although retreating to the sanctuary of a7 while staying on a powerful diagonal, this gives White options of Bg5, pinning Black's Nf6 to his Queen. Better was e7. } 8. Ba3?! { [%eval -0.59] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bg5. } { (0.33 → -0.35) Inaccuracy. Best move was Bg5. } { Though placed on a strong diagonal, Bg5 was much stronger for reasons given above. This is compounded by the fact that Ba3 prevents the space gaining a4. Also, though ...b5 will activate White's dsb, it is precariously placed on on file that could easily be opened and become prey to Black's Ra8 should that happen and the Knight protecting it having been developed. At the moment, the Bishop is simply an oversized pawn. It is rarely a good idea to dedicate a piece to the protection of a pawn. Pawns should generally protect pawns. That is the reason why an isolated pawn is so vulnerable to an opponent, apart from the fact that the square directly in front of the isolated pawn becomes a wonderful outpost. } (8. Bg5 h6 (8... d6 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. Kh1 Nd8 11. Nh4 Ne6 12. Nf5 Qd8 13. Bh4 Nf4 14. Ne3 c6 15. Nf3 Ng6 16. Bg3 d5 17. exd5 cxd5 18. Bb3 d4 19. cxd4 exd4 20. Nc4 Nd5 21. Nd6 Be6 22. Nxb7 Qe7 23. Na5 Nxb4 24. Re1 Qd7 25. Bxe6 fxe6 26. Nc4 Bc5 27. Ng5 Rfe8 28. a3 Nd5 29. Nxh7 Kxh7 30. Qh5+ Kg8 31. Qxg6 Qf7 32. Qxf7+ Kxf7 33. Bd6 Rec8 34. g3 Kf6 35. Bxc5 Rxc5 36. Re4 Rb8 37. Rae1 Rc6 38. Rxd4 g5 39. Kg2 Rb5 40. h4 gxh4 41. Rxh4 Ne7 42. Rh6+ { Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son - Karthikeyan, P2., 1-0, Asian Rapid 2015, https://lichess.org/Y7mI6183 }) 9. Bh4 d6 10. a4 g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7) 8... b5 { [%eval -0.51] } 9. Bb3 { [%eval -0.57] } 9... d6 { [%eval -0.46] } 10. Bb2 { [%eval -0.45] } { Trying to rectify my mistake, wrestling with the delay in development, or rather, allowing my opponent to get positionally better } 10... a5? { [%eval 0.75] } { Mistake. Best move was Ne7. } { (-0.12 → 0.78) Inaccuracy. Best move was Ne7. } (10... Ne7 11. a4) 11. a4 { [%eval 0.74] } { a4! I chose this yod pawn structure knowing opponent probably take b pawn making my bishop doubly stupid for moving again } 11... bxa4 { [%eval 0.79] } { This suprised me... } 12. Bxa4 { [%eval 0.63] } 12... Bd7 { [%eval 0.83] } 13. b5?! { [%eval -0.01] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bxc6. } { (0.80 → -0.11) Inaccuracy. Best move was Bxc6. } (13. Bxc6) 13... Ne7 { [%eval -0.02] } { Here’s some hope chess rules... one must have an idea, and then one hopes it’s the right one...
The idea was to push the pawn another time to blind the bishop For as long as it takes... } 14. Nbd2 { [%eval -0.09] } 14... Ng6 { [%eval -0.16] } 15. d4 { [%eval 0.07] } { I saw an earlier chance to blind the bishop... } 15... Nf4 { [%eval 0.02] } { I always dislike my opponents knight placement here, ughhhh!! I always just want to take it !!! } 16. dxe5? { [%eval -0.13] } { (-0.13 → -1.19) Mistake. Best move was Qc2. } { This is emotional chess, I took because I disliked the knight there, also, fathers my plan to open d file...
Of course my idea to blind the bishop just one move ago had been derailed by the “how dare you” rule of chess... } (16. Qc2 { Stockfish points out that my protection of d3 strategy was wasteful, and a clean qc2 more appropriate. } 16... Rb8 17. Kh1 exd4 18. cxd4 Bxb5 19. Bxb5 Rxb5 20. Nc4 Re8 21. Rxa5 Rxa5 22. Nxa5 Qd7 { Uhmmm... don’t you love stockfish fantasy’s heh heh heh,
Oh yeah my first thought is to move my king to h1... }) 16... dxe5? { [%eval 1.13] } { Mistake. Best move was Ng4. } { (-1.19 → 0.99) Blunder. Best move was Ng4. } (16... Ng4 17. Nb3 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Bc1 Be6 20. Bxf4 { Seems that my instincts are right, knight there is undesirable } 20... exf4 21. Nd4 Bc4 22. Re1 Qh4 23. Qf3 { Ohhh, that was not really that much fun...
But at least I could manage to equalize this way, ... right like I’d remember this otb... }) 17. Nxe5 { [%eval 1.05] } 17... Re8?! { [%eval 1.81] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Be6. } { Now, my center dissolution was to continue with taking bishop on d7, but I wanted knight on e5 for one more move, not wanting to block my bishop, I weighed heavily blocking my bishop or moving my knight... then I saw, my pawn at risk and f2 falling soon after... } (17... Be6 18. c4) 18. c4 { [%eval 1.76] } 18... N6h5?? { [%eval 5.21] } { Blunder. Best move was Qe7. } { (1.51 → 5.23) Blunder. Best move was Qe7. } { Okay, I agree this plan was simple and not really playing chess at all, I figured my opponents knights would look good in such position, then when I show this game the spectacle of it all could be impressive.. } (18... Qe7 19. Qf3 (19. Nxd7) 19... Ng6 20. Nxg6 fxg6 21. Bc2 Ng4 22. Qc3 Bc5 23. Nf3 Be6 24. Bd3 Rf8 25. Be2) 19. Nxd7 { [%eval 5.1] } 19... Qg5 { [%eval 5.01] } { I was hoping for b6 with tempo... egad! Wasn’t ready for queen actually going there instead of taking...but in line with my earlier assessment, scary... really scary... } 20. Qf3 { [%eval 5.02] } { My only move as you see opponents m8 knights attacking I was like... omg what if he brings his rook in...
Then the thought struck me Qf3 has a discovery on rook, so, opponent doesn’t really have the time to overpower me... } 20... Re6?! { [%eval 8.86] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Ng6. } { (5.04 → 8.87) Inaccuracy. Best move was Ng6. } { Omg!! he did it, now I thought, opponent will merely move rook, but if he don’t, I got back rank... } (20... Ng6 21. e5 (21. g3)) 21. e5 { [%eval 8.45] } 21... Rg6? { [%eval #3] } { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Best move was Qxg2+. } { (8.69 → Mate in 3) Checkmate is now unavoidable. Best move was Qxg2+. } (21... Qxg2+ 22. Qxg2) 22. Qxa8+ { [%eval #2] } { Black resigns. } 1-0


