1. d4 { [%eval 0.25] } 1... d5 { [%eval 0.25] } 2. Bf4 { [%eval 0.0] } 2... Nf6 { [%eval 0.0] } 3. e3 { [%eval 0.0] } 3... g6 { [%eval 0.37] } { Here or within the next few moves I would recommend playing actively against the London and applying pressure on the d4 pawn via c5 instead of playing the solid but passive c6. Also I would recommend a Kings Indian type of setup against White's London Setups instead of a Grünfeld setup because with a pawn on d6 you get the additional idea of playing the e5 break. } { I think I understand what you are saying but, not to make any excuses, I am still "feeling my way around the opening" and rather insecure about my play, which explains the passive c6... } (3... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4] }) 4. c4 { [%eval -0.05] } { Now we have a Grünfeld on the board. Still that doesn't change much about the fact that I prefer c5 here or Bg7 first instead of c6. } 4... c6?! { [%eval 0.49] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bg7. } (4... Bg7 5. Nc3 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. Rc1 dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. Nf3) (4... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4] }) 5. Nf3 { [%eval 0.16] } 5... Bg7 { [%eval 0.39] } 6. c5?! { [%eval -0.13] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nc3. } (6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nbd7 9. h3 b5 10. Be2 Bb7) 6... O-O { [%eval -0.33] } { Of course castling kingside is a normal looking move but you should start thinking here if White plays a move like c5, releasing central pressure. The standard move to attack the tip of the pawn chain here is b6 which is incredibly effective here because White can't hold his pawn structure with b4 a5 a3 due to his unprotected rook on a1. } (6... b6! { [%cal Gb6c5] } 7. b4 a5 8. a3? axb4 9. axb4?? Rxa1 $19) 7. Be2 { [%eval -0.07] } 7... Bg4 { [%eval -0.01] } { I don't like this move that much. Sure, you develop a piece but White wants to play h3 anyways to get a retreat square for his bishop and you don't really want to trade on f3 giving up your bishop pair. } { You are right, of course. I'm just speculating but I believe I wanted to develop my remaining Knight but wasn't comfortable with Bf4 because of the possible ...Nh4, if that makes any sense to you, considering the fact I am a weak to intermediate or intermediate level player at best. } 8. Nbd2 { [%eval 0.0] } 8... Nh5 { [%eval 0.04] } { Yeah, thats a common theme here, if White hasn't played h3 yet. } 9. O-O { [%eval 0.0] } 9... Nxf4 { [%eval 0.0] } 10. exf4 { [%eval -0.21] } 10... Qc7 { [%eval 0.0] } 11. h3?? { [%eval -1.75] } { Blunder. Best move was Ne5. } (11. Ne5 Bf5 12. Bg4 e6 13. Bxf5 exf5 14. Re1 Re8 15. Ndf3 Nd7 16. g3 Nf6 17. Kg2 Re6) 11... Bxf3 { [%eval -1.64] } 12. Nxf3 { [%eval -1.74] } 12... Nd7? { [%eval -0.45] } { Mistake. Best move was Qxf4. } { Here and in the next move you could just have taken on f4. } { Yes, of course. I am still horribly blunder-prone, I'm ashamed to admit. I believe I was so concerned about developing that Knight that I wasn't paying proper attention to the board. } (12... Qxf4 13. Rb1 Nd7 14. b4 Rfe8 15. b5 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. g3 Qf6 19. Qc2) 13. b4? { [%eval -1.7] } { Mistake. Best move was Qd2. } (13. Qd2 b6) 13... Nf6 { [%eval 0.31] } 14. g3 { [%eval 0.43] } 14... Nh5 { [%eval 0.8] } { This is a mysterius move for me. I understand that you wanted to move your knight to a better square and you probably already had that Nh5-g7-e6 maneuvre in mind when you played this move. Still I think the central e4 is a better square for this piece and you only need one move instead of four! } { I have absolutely no idea what this whole sortie is about. lol } (14... Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c3,Ge4f2,Ge4g3] }) 15. Qd2 { [%eval 0.63] } 15... Qd7 { [%eval 1.04] } 16. Kg2 { [%eval 0.91] } 16... Bh8 { [%eval 1.42] } 17. Ng1 { [%eval 0.94] } 17... Ng7 { [%eval 1.09] } 18. Bg4 { [%eval 0.53] } 18... f5?! { [%eval 1.35] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was e6. } { Weakening the e5 square without need and giving White's knight a potential outpost. Instead Ne6 was the better choice threatening f5 and thus forcing Bxe6 or Ne2 if White doesn't want to lose his d4 pawn. If you really want to play f5 you can maybe do it if White plays Ne2 because then he can't go to e2 with his bishop after f5! } { Yes, this game is quite horrible, isn't it? So haphazard and misguided, through and through, in hindsight. } 19. Bf3?! { [%eval 0.61] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Be2. } (19. Be2 Ne8 20. a4 Nf6 21. Nf3 e6 22. Qc2 Ne4 23. h4 Qe7 24. Rh1 Nf6 25. Ne5 Ne4) 19... Ne6 { [%eval 0.79] } 20. h4 { [%eval -1.45] } { Oh, ok, I remember now! A laughable tactic, really. } 20... Nxd4 { [%eval -1.48] } 21. Rfe1?! { [%eval -2.21] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rae1. } (21. Rae1 a5) 21... Nxf3 { [%eval -1.97] } 22. Nxf3 { [%eval -2.49] } 22... Bxa1 { [%eval -2.37] } 23. Rxa1 { [%eval -2.22] } 23... e6?! { [%eval -1.5] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was d4. } (23... d4 24. h5) 24. Ne5 { [%eval -1.36] } 24... Qe7 { [%eval -1.18] } 25. Qd4?! { [%eval -1.78] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rh1. } (25. Rh1 Qg7) 25... Rfc8 { [%eval -1.25] } 26. Rh1 { [%eval -1.5] } 26... b6? { [%eval 0.0] } { Mistake. Best move was Qe8. } { Here this move doesn't work in your favour. In fact it's bad here because it weakens c6 and binds one of your pieces to the defence of that pawn. With his last move Rh1 White intended to play h5 opening the h-file for his rook. It was necessary to be ready for that here and play a move like Rc7 and moving the queen out of the way to defend your king. } { Yes, you are correct on all counts. I believe I felt I could turn his c5 pawn into a weakness...I must admit I had the devil of a time figuring out how not to get mated afterwards because his Ke5 exerted such an influence and limited the scope of movement of more than one of my pieces in the small space I had to move around. } 27. h5 { [%eval 0.0] } 27... bxc5 { [%eval 0.0] } (27... gxh5) 28. bxc5 { [%eval 0.0] } 28... Qg7 { [%eval 0.0] } 29. hxg6 { [%eval 0.0] } 29... hxg6 { [%eval 0.0] } 30. Qd1 { [%eval 0.0] } 30... Rc7 { [%eval 0.0] } 31. Rh4? { [%eval -1.17] } { Mistake. Best move was Rh2. } (31. Rh2 Rb8 32. Qh1 Rf8 33. a4 Rb7 34. Rh6 Rf6 35. Rh4 d4 36. Kh3 Rc7 37. Kg2 Rf8) 31... g5 { [%eval -1.15] } { good moment to punish Rh4 here! } { Yes, I believe I let out a sigh of relief when I saw my opponent had moved Rh4. } 32. fxg5 { [%eval -7.52] } 32... Qxe5 { [%eval -7.46] } 33. Qh5 { [%eval -7.05] } 33... Qg7 { [%eval -7.35] } 34. g6 { [%eval -8.01] } 34... Rd7 { [%eval -7.87] } 35. Qg5 { [%eval -8.0] } 35... Rad8?? { [%eval -1.84] } { Blunder. Best move was Qe5. } { Here I succumbed to irrational fear, I guess. I imagine you are rolling your eyes to high-heaven. lol } (35... Qe5 36. Qe3 Qxe3 37. fxe3 Rb8 38. Kf3 Rg7 39. Ra4 Rb5 40. g4 fxg4+ 41. Kxg4 Rxg6+ 42. Kf4) 36. Rh7 { [%eval -2.16] } 36... Qe5 { [%eval -1.8] } 37. Qh4?? { [%eval -9.68] } { Blunder. Best move was Qh5. } { In lower-level play, you can generally count on the ubiquitous egregious mistakes and blunders and wild fluctuations in the advantage that are so characteristic at that stage of development. I often ask myself: is this move my opponent's blunder? Obviously, in this case he just handed me the game on a silver platter, to my relief. } (37. Qh5 d4) 37... Qe4+ { [%eval -9.54] } 38. Qxe4 { [%eval -9.76] } 38... dxe4 { [%eval -9.33] } { White resigned } 0-1


