1. e4 e5 2. f4 { With this move, White gambit's his pawn in exchange for a quick development. } 2... exf4 3. Bc4 { This bold Bishop sortie squarely and resolutely sets its sights on Black's vulnerable underbelly, the f7 pawn, at the cost of the castling priviledge which will be lost as a consequence of the coming ...Qh4+ } 3... Qh4+ 4. Kf1 b5 { Black, in turn, counter gambit's a pawn of his own } 5. Bxb5 { White obliges, pinning Black's Queen's pawn in the doing! } 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 { Developing with tempo against Black's Queen which must move or be captured, delaying Black's development } 6... Qh6 7. d3 { White's centre is now rock-solid } 7... Nh5 { The Black King's natural defender leaves his post, presumably to defend the f5 pawn, further delaying Black's development (Nh5 is not a developing move) as well as curtailing that Knight's mobility and influence over the centre. } 8. Nh4 Qg5 { Black's Queen comes out of hiding with a double-attack against Nh4 and Bb5 but this threat is easily parried with Nf5 which was the Knight's intented square anyway! } 9. Nf5 c6 { Unpinning the d7-pawn. } 10. g4 { White keeps its eye on the prize, unconcerned by the potential cxBb5 } 10... Nf6 11. Rg1 { White has written-off his Bb5 and trains his guns on Black's Queen and beyond on the g-file } 11... cxb5 { Black greedily gobbles un White's useless Bb5, further delaying development in the face of a coming kingside onslaught! } 12. h4 { Steamrolling towards Black's kingside, closing the net around his forlorn Queen. } 12... Qg6 13. h5 Qg5 14. Qf3 { Black's position is now terribly precarious as Bxf4 wins Black's Queen and it's alternative, e5, attack's Nf6 and Ra8 simultaneously. } 14... Ng8 { With this ignominious retreat, White's lead in development is now crushing. This is compounded by the fact that his forces are martialled against Black's kingside whose only active piece - the Queen - will also retreat after Bxf4. } 15. Bxf4 Qf6 16. Nc3 Bc5 { Black's misguided attempt at catching up some of his lost time by this developing move with apparent tempo which unfortunately for Black makes White's progress towards the promised land even easier with the simple d4 advance. } 17. Nd5 { Tactically threatening Black's Queen as well as Nc7+ with a double-attack on Ke8 and Ra8 } 17... Qxb2 { Black continues running after material, grabbing a useless pawn and threatening to take White's inactive Ra1 } 18. Bd6 { White offers up both his rooks on a platter!! } 18... Bxg1 { It is from this move that Black's defeat stems. Wilhelm Steinitz suggested in 1879 that a better move would be 18... Qxa1+; likely moves to follow are 19. Ke2 Qb2 20. Kd2 Bxg1. } { Black can't believe his good fortune and jumps at the chance of having such an unsuspected and seemingly devastating material advantage } 19. e5 { White closes the critical a1-h8 diagonal, effectively shutting the Black Queen out of the action that is about to unfold on the really critical field of battle - Black's kingside - rather than bother himself with the trivial skirmish going on in his own backyard. } 19... Qxa1+ 20. Ke2 { A little "pas-de-deux" leaves Black to contend with the fact that he has no attack at all, despite having a Queen and Bishop on White's backrank, both of which are now rendered completely useless in the defense of their beleaguered regent. } 20... Na6 { Black belatedly develops his Queenside Knight to its only safe square, on the edge of the board. But the die is cast and mate is now unavoidable! } 21. Nxg7+ Kd8 22. Qf6+ Nxf6 23. Be7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } 1-0


