1. d4 { This study is a mean to analyse some of my games I find instructive. First I do analysis without the engine, then I turn it on to see if I missed something important. I also note my thinking process in some moves. } { [%clk 0:30:00] } 1... Nf6 { Move involving least commitment, I will do it anyway so why not play it as a first move. } { [%clk 0:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:30:20] } 2... d5 { Natural continuation } { [%clk 0:30:05] } 3. c4 { [%clk 0:30:30] } 3... e6 { I go with QGD. My opening theory is still very poor, in most cases up to 5-6 moves. } { I'm useless at theory too but always feel a bit as if I'm shooting myself in the foot with 3...e6, because it blocks Black's lsb. I don't know how recommended it is or not but I have pretty much made my bed with ...Bf5/Bg4, depending on the circumstances and only then ...e6. Do you guys have any thoughts about the relative merits of these different approaches? } { e6 is a fully playable system against the catalan and is the most popular move at the highest levels, but the gm's know exactly what to do. If instead you're running on instincts getting your LSB out of your pawn chain leads to a simpler position. I don't think you played poorly in the opening and as you can see from all my inaccuracies, I didn't fully understand the position either. } { [%clk 0:30:13] } 4. g3 { I've been fooling around with the catalan with mixed results, I'm not booked up but enjoy the challenge learning of this complex opening. } { [%clk 0:30:45] } 4... c6 { Sure but 1- it's not a developing move and 2- doesn't this make developing Queenside Bishop + Night even more problematical? Not judging here, just thinking out loud. } { On general grounds C6 is not a move you want to make here, in this exact position it's fine though. Black will play b6, Bb7 or a6 and eventually get in c5, when white has the sunny side of equality or nagging pressure. Without c6 blacks set up can get into concrete difficulties when he plays b6, white starts hopping toward the c6 square. It would take variations to show why c6 is played. But if you are playing on general principals then c6 should be delayed untill it is absolutely nessessary. For one reason if white doesn't know what he is doing , black might get c5 in one go. } { [%clk 0:29:11] } 5. Qc2 { Once again, I am no chess erudite but I was expecting 5.Bg2 so 5.Qc2 really gets me thinking in that it strikes me as more aggressive than 5.Bg2. It has its eyes on h7 and Ng5 is only one move away, for White. It also protects the c4 pawn(square) as well as keeping options open on b3/a4 squares, should circumstances allow. What really concerns me with Black's setup is that if Black castles kingside, White may lock up the centre and proceed with a kingside attack because not only will black lose time developing his queenside knight and bishop but lines of communication between both sides of the board will be blocked for him. } { There are some aggressive set ups where white sacrifices his c pawn but I wasn't confident in a hyper sharp position yet. so I decided on this move over Bg2. } { [%clk 0:29:54] } 5... Be7 { I was thinking long after 5.Qc2 , it looked very uncomfortable since three of White's pieces are now directed towards my kingside. After castling, Ng5 could be tricky, there is also a tematic sacrifice Bxh6 in case I play h6, etc. I have considered all this, and decided that I can safely chase away the knight from g5 and that there is really nothing to worry about there. So I played a normal developing move, preparing to castle. } { [%clk 0:26:39] } (5... dxc4 6. Qxc4) 6. Bg2 { [%clk 0:29:55] } 6... O-O { Just as I feared. Black now exposes himself to immediate c5. } { [%clk 0:26:12] } 7. O-O { [%clk 0:29:05] } 7... b5?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was b6. } { I had several candidate moves here, like Nd7, c5, Re8 (to make room for a king or a defensive piece in case of early attack on a kingside). In the end I chose b5 in order to deveolop my LSB. Downside of this move is the permament weakness on c6, which will hunt me to the end of the game. } { Challenging White's c4 pawn but this can't be good because it plays into White's hand who can simply push the pawn to c5, locking up the centre in preparation for a kingside attack and also created a vulnerable backward c6 pawn, unsupported by flanking pawns as well as a beautiful outpost c5-square for White, should he choose not to push his c4 pawn up to c5. } { [%clk 0:24:58] } (7... b6 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2 Ba6 10. Nbd2 c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Rad1) 8. b3?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was c5. } { I looked at c5 with an idea of an eventual e4 and if dxe4 I get access to an outpost on d6 in exchage for black getting one on d5. I decided to maintain pawn tension, but It seems this was an inaccurate idea. } { [%clk 0:27:39] } (8. c5 a5 9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 h6 11. a3 Ba6 12. h3 b4) 8... bxc4 { [%clk 0:23:59] } 9. bxc4 { [%clk 0:27:44] } 9... Ba6 { Developing a bishop and making pressure on both c4, e2 and X-ray attacking Rf1. Also stopping c4-c5. } { I can't say that I like this move either because, though it does develop the lsb, I prefer to do this after a5 so it is supported by the queenside Rook. I mean, isn't Black's queenside Knight now tied to the defence of Ba6? And doesn't this prevent Black from activating Ra8? Surely White can see now both Black' queenside Night and Rook development are hampered by Ba6 and will try to capitalize on the fact, no? } { I don't understand why the bishop on a6 would tie black down to it's defense, it looks like a good move to me. I also don't understand the statement that Ba6 prevents c4-c5 } { [%clk 0:23:40] } (9... Nbd7 10. c5) 10. Nbd2?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was c5. } { White prefers this developing move, rather than locking up the centre with c5. Perhaps Justin could let us in on what he was thinking, at the time? } { Stockfish finds my conception of maintaining pawn tension just wrong. I could only guess as to why. I'm trying to prepare e2-e4 while maintaining control over the d5 square. I want to gain squares for my pieces while disallowing black to do the same. Maybe this is over ambitious, maybe the pawn tension on c4 favors black, I just don't know. } { [%clk 0:26:00] } (10. c5 Ne4) 10... Nbd7 { I was considering other moves here, especially c5, but in the end I've decided to develop my least active piece. } { [%clk 0:20:21] } 11. Rd1?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bb2. } { Tricky move, escaping X-ray attack on f1-a6 diagonal, supporting d4-pawn in case Nd2 has to be moved away, allowing e-pawn breakthrough. } { This move seemed natural to me, preparing e2-e4 getting out of an x ray strengthening my position against c5 which should be coming anytime now. } { [%clk 0:23:55] } (11. Bb2 Rb8 12. Rab1 Qa5 13. Rfc1 Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qxb2 15. Rxa6 c5 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Rxa7 c4) 11... Bb4? { Mistake. Best move was c5. } { This move is a consequence of mis-calculation. I was thinking that if I take the knight with Bb4xNd4 that c4-pawn will be left undefended. I didn't see that White could just recapture with Nf3xd2 and c4-pawn is again well-protected. If I've seen this, I would probably play something else, like c5. } { Luka is fighting for the c4 square with all his might, but preparing c6-c5 seems like the natural way to play for equality to me. } { [%clk 0:17:43] } (11... c5 12. Ne5) 12. e4 { This move is what I have been preparing so after a two minute think to calculate a bit and make sure I'm not losing material, I played it. } { [%clk 0:21:37] } (12. Qa4 Qa5 13. Qxa5 Bxa5 14. Ba3 Rfc8 15. e3 Bxc4) 12... dxe4 { This can't be good because not only is Black's e4-pawn White's for the taking and Black's Qd8 one less degree of separation from White's Rd1, White still has his strong - now uncontested - pawn centre and is almost naturally impelled towards Ne5 which Black could hardly do anything about in the immediate because of ...NxNe5, dxNe5 forcing the castled king's main defender away. Am I wrong here? Your thought on the situation, please. } { [%clk 0:15:31] } 13. Ng5?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Ne5. } { A fancy way of taking back the pawn? I don't see why White would prefer having a Knight on e4 rather than on e5, at the moment. } { Completely missed Ne5, This position took up much of the two minutes, I had spent on e2-e4, I felt that black had one free move while I recaptured on e4, so I looked at 13... c5,e5, and e3. Immediately after the game I mentioned e3 to Luka as well as a few other improvements. SO I guess I drove straight to this position and missed my exit . } { [%clk 0:19:36] } (13. Ne5) 13... Qc7?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was e3. } { This probably wasn't the best move. The intention was to protect c6 weakness and to move the queen away from X-ray attack from Rd1. Maybe e3 would be better here. } { Now, both Black's Qc7 and Ba6 are hanging. Besides that, what is accomplished by this move, even though c7 is often a natural developing square for Black's Queen? } { [%clk 0:12:00] } (13... e3 14. fxe3 h6 15. Ngf3 Qc7 16. e4 e5 17. Nb3 Be7 18. Bh3 Rab8 19. Bd2 Bb4 20. Be3) 14. Ngxe4 { I've achieved what I wanted, a square on e4 while denying a square on d5, notice how the bishop on g2 is now doing something whereas a minute ago it was just staring at a solid pawn on d5. It's pretty common that if you're playing towards a certain strategic goal even if stockfish dislikes your individual moves you can still get a decent position. One of the reason's is that we're not playing against stockfish. } { [%clk 0:18:02] } 14... Rad8 { A mistake. I should have noticed that I am putting my rook and queen on a same diagonal on a dark squares, and White still has DSB. } { I don't think having your Rook and Queen on the same dark diagonal is at all the reason why your move is a mistake. There is absolutely no threat from White's dsb in the sense that you are talking about. Now, if NxNf6, ...NxNf6, White could eventually Bg5 pinning Nf6 to Rd8. That threat seems much more immediate and viable than anything having to do with R + Q on same dark-square diagonal. } { This game has a theme going of"get off of the diagonal" first Rd1, now Rd8 and in a minute Ba5 where the bishop manages to pin and skewer at the same time } { [%clk 0:10:59] } (14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Be7 16. Bf4 Qa5) 15. Rb1?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nxf6+. } { I saw this move too while it was White's turn to think. Too bad I didn't see it a move before. } { I calculated for three or four minutes before playing Rb1, I had a lot of options, If he takes on d2 My little bishop on d2 becomes beastly, he can't play c5 since it loses an exchange for a pawn, he can't gang up on the c4 square with Nb6 as the game continuation showed. That little guy on d2 is just incredibly annoying for black to deal with in this position , he has potential squares on b4 a5 f4 and g5 to start with . out of nowhere White is going to dominate the dark squares. Even if stockfish evaluated it as 0.00 It wouldn't matter that much the position is easier to play for white than black. } { [%clk 0:14:24] } (15. Nxf6+) 15... Bxd2 { I am not sure about this move, it looked to me that Nf2 has an important role to support the center, and that by DSB doesn't have a bright future. Also it became too complicated to me, so I chose simplification instead. } { Only making things even simpler for White! (see previous comment concerning NxNf6) } { [%clk 0:08:54] } 16. Bxd2 { [%clk 0:13:49] } 16... Nxe4 { Same logic, simplification and removing pieces supporting the activity in the center. } { [%clk 0:08:02] } 17. Bxe4 { Now what does the board look like, objectively? White has a strong pawn centre. Both his rooks are more active than Black's. Both Black's Qc7 and Ba6 are unsupported. White lsb and Queen form a powerful battery on the b1-h7 diagonal, directly aiming at Black's vulnerable h7 square. If Black is not feeling very bad, he should be. } { When you prepare a break in the center like e2-e4 in this game, you often get a little flurry of activity, Black tried to trade out because things were getting a bit complex, but the resulting position is just no fun for black. I have a space advantage two bishop and chances to create little problems for a long time to come. Anyway I think after my Rb1 you should have admitted a mistake and retreated your bishop,to e7 or something. I know it's a bit general but he could cover some of the holes in your pawn structure. } { [%clk 0:13:40] } 17... f5 { I think this was the only logical defense. g6 would've been terrible, and Nd7-f6 was dangerous in light of Bd2-g5. } { Almost forced but this unfortunately created another backward, unsupported, e6 pawn as well as opening up the a2-g8 diagonal Black's Kg8 sits on. Black is now in positionally very dire straits. } { [%clk 0:07:11] } 18. Bg2 { for some reason I considered Bd3 and Bf3 for a bit here before playing Bg2, I felt that the position was good so if I could get away with Bd3, I would, since it frees my queen from the defense of c4. I can't remember exactly but I think I calculated that Bd3 get's into some trouble after c6-c5 } { [%clk 0:11:59] } 18... Nb6 { Huge blunder. I never noticed that by queen and rook are on the same diagonal, and now I pay the price.
ENGINE: It looks like things could be partially saved by c6-c5 thus preventing c4-c5. } { Ouch! Black now sends an open invitation to White for Ba5 pinning Nb6 to his Qc7/Rd8, which could be compounded by White c5 if Black isn't very careful. } { [%clk 0:05:54] } 19. Ba5 { [%clk 0:11:03] } 19... Qe7? { Mistake. Best move was c5. } { The game is essentially over, now. } { I win the exchange by force but 19...c5 instead of 19...Qe7 would have netted you a pawn for the exchange I think. } { [%clk 0:04:41] } (19... c5 20. dxc5 Qxc5 21. Bb4 Qxc4 22. Qxc4 Rxd1+ (22... Bxc4 23. Bxf8 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Kxf8) 23. Rxd1 Bxc4 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Bf1 Bxa2 26. Ra1) 20. c5 { [%clk 0:09:55] } 20... Nd5 { [%clk 0:04:45] } 21. Bxd8 { [%clk 0:09:53] } 21... Qxd8 { [%clk 0:04:24] } 22. Re1 { [%clk 0:09:08] } 22... Qd7 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 23. Re5 { I thought forever over this move, I I was trying to calculate a forced win while preventing all counterplay instead of just playing chess up an exchange. I don't know how to justify this time sink. } { [%clk 0:05:31] } 23... Bb5 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 24. Qd2?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rxb5. } { SF suggests 24. Rxb5 which I wouldn't find in game since I don't understand it even after I'm told it's best.
I wanted to play 24. Rb-e1 but that move loses an exchange to 24...Nb4, a drawback of Qd2 is I no longer eye the c4 square, so black can try to sneak a bishop into d5 from c4 } { [%clk 0:04:58] } (24. Rxb5) 24... Nf6 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 25. Qb4 { A nothing move, I cover c4 and disallow the continuation 25...Ng4 26. Re-e1 e5, but don't further my agenda. } { [%clk 0:03:47] } 25... Ng4 { I could comment on all the random stuff I calculated but I don't know what good it would do, Im mostly eating my own clock for no good reason. } { [%clk 0:01:27] } 26. Ree1 { [%clk 0:03:54] } 26... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 27. a4 { [%clk 0:03:31] } 27... Ba6 { [%clk 0:01:13] } 28. h3 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 28... Nf6 { I start speeding up now since I actually don't have much time left. } { [%clk 0:01:32] } 29. Re5 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 29... Nd5 { [%clk 0:01:39] } 30. Qd2 { [%clk 0:01:38] } 30... Bb7?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nc7. } { Last big mistake, deactivating my good bishop. I was down an exchange, in time trouble and generally out of ideas for any meaningful counter-play. After the game, my opponent gave me a very valuable advice: the ideal place for my LSB was d5 square. It never occured to me during the game, although it makes perfect sense.
The rest of the game was an easy win for White. } { [%clk 0:01:10] } (30... Nc7) 31. Rbe1 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 31... Re8 { [%clk 0:01:21] } 32. Bxd5 { Now that I'm all set up I trade off his knight and break things. } { [%clk 0:01:37] } 32... cxd5 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 33. g4 { [%clk 0:01:50] } 33... g6? { Mistake. Best move was fxg4. } { [%clk 0:01:38] } (33... fxg4 34. hxg4) 34. Qh6 { [%clk 0:02:06] } 34... Kg8 { [%clk 0:01:26] } 35. gxf5 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 35... gxf5 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 36. Rxe6 { [%clk 0:02:10] } 36... Rxe6 { [%clk 0:01:30] } 37. Rxe6 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 37... Bc8 { [%clk 0:01:48] } 38. Qg5+ { [%clk 0:02:02] } 38... Qg7?! { Checkmate is now unavoidable. Best move was Kf8. } { [%clk 0:01:50] } (38... Kf8 39. Rf6+) 39. Re8+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:02:26] } *


