1. d4 { [%eval 0.25] } 1... Nf6 { [%eval 0.22] } 2. Bf4 { [%eval 0.0] } 2... d5 { [%eval 0.0] } 3. Nf3 { [%eval 0.0] } { D02 Queen's Pawn Game: London System } 3... c5 { [%eval 0.0] } { Black immediately challenges White's d4 pawn for the centre and prepares Qb6, with an eye towards its vulnerable b2 pawn, as well as Nc6 putting additional pressure on the d4 pawn. } 4. e3 { [%eval 0.0] } 4... Nc6 { [%eval -0.08] } 5. c3 { [%eval -0.17] } 5... Qb6 { [%eval 0.0] } { Black seizes the initiative and a mexican stand-off is in the cards } 6. Qb3 { [%eval -0.35] } 6... c4 { [%eval -0.34] } { Encroaching on White's Queenside and forcing the White Queen's retreat because the exchange would leave Black with the half-open a-file and an immediate b7-b5. } 7. Qc2 { [%eval -0.42] } 7... Bf5 { [%eval -0.25] } { With tempo, as capturing the Bishop would lose the rook after Qxb2 } 8. Qc1 { [%eval -0.51] } 8... Nh5 { [%eval -0.48] } 9. Bg3 { [%eval -0.4] } { White can't retreat it lsb to h2, so prepares to open the h-file in exchange for the loss of the Bishop pair. } 9... h6 { [%eval -0.45] } { A prophylactic move against Black's Nh4 which would rob Black of the Bishop pair. Black appears slightly better with a space advantage on the Queenside, White having nothing to show for the loss of territory. } 10. Nbd2 { [%eval -0.35] } 10... e6 { [%eval -0.31] } { Black's continues his development, before proceeding with a queenside attack. } 11. Be2 { [%eval -0.46] } { White is feeling the pinch now and develops his lsb to the lone available square in preparation of 0-0. } 11... Nxg3 { [%eval -0.09] } { Black wins the Bishop pair, confident that his Queenside activities will force White to 0-0, effectively preventing it from mustering his forces sufficiently quickly for martial intentions against Black's kingside using the half-open h-file it will control after hxg3. } 12. hxg3 { [%eval -0.38] } 12... Be7 { [%eval -0.41] } 13. b3 { [%eval -0.35] } 13... cxb3 { [%eval -0.44] } 14. axb3 { [%eval -0.56] } { White has regained lost ground as well as controlling the half-open a-file and providing its lsb with greater range of motion. This is still a very close game. } 14... O-O { [%eval -0.5] } 15. O-O { [%eval -0.75] } 15... Rac8 { [%eval -0.4] } { Taking control of the half-open c-file and putting pressure on White's backward c3-pawn. } 16. c4 { [%eval -0.61] } { White moves quickly to rid itself of its liability. } 16... Qc7 { [%eval -0.41] } { Black somewhat compromises his a7-pawn's safety in exchange for the battering ram on the c-file and greater Queen mobility with options on the kingside. } 17. Qb2 { [%eval -0.5] } 17... Bb4 { [%eval -0.01] } 18. Rfc1 { [%eval 0.03] } 18... Qe7 { [%eval 0.0] } 19. Ne1 { [%eval 0.0] } { The point of this escapes me. Why not Nh4 instead? } 19... Rfd8 { [%eval 0.16] } 20. Bd3 { [%eval 0.21] } 20... Qf6 { [%eval 0.08] } 21. cxd5 { [%eval 0.0] } 21... exd5 { [%eval -0.01] } 22. Ra4 { [%eval -0.34] } { This seems like a lost tempo because it must surely retreat after the inevitable a5, securing Black's hold on b4 till the end of time. } 22... a5 { [%eval -0.31] } 23. Raa1 { [%eval -0.43] } 23... Ne7 { [%eval -0.31] } 24. Ndf3 { [%eval -0.43] } 24... Qd6?! { [%eval 0.39] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Be4. } (24... Be4 25. Be2) 25. Bxf5 { [%eval 0.39] } 25... Nxf5 { [%eval 0.27] } 26. Nd3 { [%eval 0.38] } 26... Rxc1+ { [%eval 0.8] } 27. Rxc1?? { [%eval -3.09] } { Blunder. Best move was Qxc1. } { Blundering away his remaining Rook to Ba3 rather than gaining a lasting advantage by Qxc1 } (27. Qxc1 Ra8 (27... b6 28. Ra4 b5 29. Ra1 Ne7 30. Nxb4 Qxb4)) 27... Ba3 { [%eval -3.07] } { White resigns. } 0-1


