[Event "PixelatedParcel's Lichess studies: my first attempts at systematic analysis: NN (2198) vs Pix"]
[Date "2019.09.13"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A20"]
[Opening "English Opening: King's English Variation"]
[StudyName "PixelatedParcel's Lichess studies: my first attempts at systematic analysis"]
[ChapterName "NN (2198) vs Pix"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Hgl735Zr/1fRrf9eF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[UTCDate "2019.09.13"]
[UTCTime "00:04:27"]

1. c4 e5 { I am really not familiar with this type of opening. What immediately springs to mind is that it is "a reverse sicilian", White having the advantage of a tempo on Black for the same asymmetrical structure. This strikes me as a fundamentally sound idea if one proceeds from the basic premise that victory in chess is closely correlated with the creation and maintaining of some form of advantageous imbalance. Contrary to more classical openings, the imbalance is created right from the start, at least with Black's response in the centre. So, as in the Sicilian, there is a battle for the centre but moving first mitigate's the fact that developing the pieces is less straightforward then with the classical 1.e4 or 1.d4 approaches. } 2. g3 { A second pawn move, preparing the lsb fianchetto on the long diagonal. Nc3, developing a minor piece and fighting for control of the centre would have been a much more classical approach to the opening but White is not in a hurry and is almost inviting Black to occupy the centre with d5. The major problem with this, as I see it, is that after cxd5 followed by Qxd5 then Nc3 with tempo on the Black queen which most find another suitable post or retreat to its initial position. This is added to the fact that developing the queen early is against general opening principles. } 2... Nc6 { Developing the knight to its natural square, supporting the central e5 pawn and contributing to the control of the d4 square. An excellent move, it seems to me. } (2... d5 3. cxd5 Qxd5?! { [%csl Rh1][%cal Rd5h1] } (3... Nf6 4. Nc3 Nxd5 { should be playable though, and transpose back into regular main lines }) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 $32 { as you correctly noted }) 3. Bg2 { White's lsb is powerfully posted on the long diagonal and stakes a claim to the light-coloured central squares, supporting the c4 pawns effort along those lines. This bishop will also be key to White's defence should he castle kingside as without it, the White king's pawn fortress will be seriously compromised on the light-squared h3, g2 and f3, especially if Black retains his lsb or queen. } 3... Bc5 { Developing Black's dsb very actively, contributing to control of the dark-squared central d4 and putting pressure on Black's weakest pawn, f2. So far, Black's opening has been both quick and harmonious. } 4. Nc3 { Develops a minor piece and fights for control of the central light-squares. So, Black is staking a claim to the central dark squares and White is staking a claim to the central light squares. } 4... a6 { At first glance, this move strikes me as contrary to principle. Did I think of this on my own or did I find it when researching the position? I do not remember. Unlike the previous moves, it does not directly contribute to Black's claim on the central dark squares. Nor does it develop a piece or contribute to Black's castling the king to safety which is generally of paramount importance in opening theory. So, what is the point of this move? Is it simply prophylactic, to guard against a possible Nb5? If so, couldn't Nb5 be kicked away afterwards? Perhaps it can...and perhaps that would be the point...to move to a different post from the original one at c3? Where could that be, should that be the case? No, that doesn't seem to make much sense for White so a6 must be in preparation of b5, to attack White's pawn at c4 and contribute to undermining his control of the central white squares. } (4... Nf6 5. Nb5 (5. e3 d5 6. cxd5 Nb4 7. d4 exd4 8. exd4 Be7 9. Nge2 Nbxd5 10. Nf4 Nxf4) 5... a6 6. Nc3) 5. e3 { This move fights for control of the central d4 square, prepares for an eventual d2-d4 push and keeps the long diagonal open for White's lsb as well as further activating White's queen. It does however impede Black's dsb's movement along the c1-h6 diagonal. So, one can safely assume said bishop's post will not be along that diagonal...So, its next posting necessarily seems to be either at the rather passive d2 or the potentially more active b2 or a3. } 5... d6 { Activates Black's lsb and supports both the central pawn at e5 as well as the dsb at c5 but does nothing about the outpost d5 square White's knight may eventually come to occupy... } 6. Nge2 { Develops a minor piece, contributes to the fight for control of the central dark-squared d4, protects the other knight at c3 and keeps the long diagonal clear for White's lsb to exert its full and immediate influence on the central light squares and beyond. So far, White's opening is excellent. I am certain he has retained his initial advantage and probably even built upon it though not +1. } 6... f5?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Ba7. } { A fourth pawn move, of only 6 moves so far for Black in the opening. This is definitely contrary to classic opening principles. This move gives Black space on the kingside, fights for control of the central light-squared e4 and prepares a possible e5, locking up the center and drastically reducing White's lsb activity for the immediate future. If e3-e4 then either fxe4 or not seem like valid choices because in the former, Black will be exchanging a flank pawn for a central pawn and in the latter Black will simply develop his lsb with Bxf4 should White break the tension with exf4. } (6... Ba7 7. d4 Nf6 8. b3 Rb8 9. O-O O-O 10. Bb2 exd4 11. exd4) 7. d4 { White has had enough and puts the question to Black who must either take with exd4, thus exposing his king while still on a central file, or posting his bishop to a new home as it is attacked with tempo by the pawn at d4. } 7... Bb4 { Black chooses b4 for his dark-squared bishop, threatening BxNc3. But is this a real threat? Surely Black would only consider losing the bishop pair in a closed game or against some form of compensation such as a weakened pawn structure which is unlikely here as BxNc3 can simply be followed by NxBc3...Now it a3, Black will either be forced to capture or move to a5 which would lead to b4 forcing the bishop back to b3...A patently absurd sequence of events, it seems to me. } (7... Ba7) 8. O-O { White is totally unconcerned by the empty threat and continues his development, castling the king to safety and centralizing his kingside rook. } 8... Bxc3 { Black executes his threat and this seems like a mistake to me as after the exchange, not only has he lost the bishop pair but White now has a serious development advantage. I am certain White now has a significant advantage over Black. Certainly more than +1. So, things are going well for White and rather poorly for Black and the opening is not even over yet. } { but why take ? } (8... Nf6 9. Nd5 Ba5 { admittedly, the bishop isn't a fantastic piece here, but it's still worth comparing both options }) 9. Nxc3 { As expected. } 9... Nf6 { Develops the knight to its natural square, contributes to the fight for the light-coloured central e4 square, prepares for castling. } 10. dxe5 { Black's king is still in the centre and White opens up the game. } 10... Nxe5 { Nxe5 with a threat of Nxc4 but now White's lsb has an unimpeded line of sight on b7 and Ra8 behind it... But dxe5 appears impossible because even though it would have avoided this situation and provided cover for Black's king, it would have left Black's queen open to QxQd8+ which would have forced KxQd8, losing castling privileges. Then, almost certainly Rd1+... } (10... dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Nxd8 { is possible, and it's not that bad : } { Yes, of course: if I missed that in my analysis I may very well have missed it during the game. Perhaps "board blindness"? In any case, a clear indication that I am not methodical enough when considering moves. } { [%csl Gf5,Ge5] } (11... Kxd8 12. Rd1+ Ke7 13. Nd5+ Nxd5 14. Rxd5 Be6 { even this isn't that bad - in both cases, your central pawns help } { [%csl Gf5,Ge5] }) 12. e4!?) 11. c5 { Gaining space on the queenside and seeking to further open lines while Black's king sits vulnerable on e8. } (11. b3) 11... O-O?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was dxc5. } { The king seeks safe harbour before the sea starts to rage. } (11... dxc5 { this is a pawn : you should at least explain why you don't take it :-) } { You are quite right, I also missed that the second time around! } 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Ke7 14. Nd5+ Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Ke6 16. Rxc5 c6 $16) 12. cxd6 { exchanging a flank pawn for Black's central pawn. Now, if cxd6, Black will be saddled with a isolated queen pawn, weakening his pawn structure. } 12... Nf7?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was cxd6. } { This move is a bit incomprehensible to me at the moment...Perhaps Black thinks White will let him take with Nxd6? I don't know... } (12... cxd6 13. b3) (12... Qxd6 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. b3 Bd7) 13. dxc7 Qxc7 { Forced. Now White has the bishop pair in an open game, a central pawn vs none for Black and is up one pawn in material. Furthermore, Black's Knight at f7 is badly posted whereas White's on c3 exerts a powerful influence on the central light squares, in harmony with White's lsb sitting at g2. Contrast this with Black's passive lsb and the whole picture makes it obvious that White now has a very solid advantage over Black. I wouldn't be surprised if it was +- 3, perhaps more. } { As they say, white has both the material and the compensation :-) } 14. e4 { White is intent upon opening lines and Black really can't do much about it... } 14... Be6 { This seems a wasted tempo as surely this is only a further incentive for White to take with exf5, forcing Bxf5 which could have been done in only one move had Black found something more constructive to do... } { still, what's the alternative for black ? } (14... fxe4) 15. exf5 { As expected. } 15... Bxf5 { As expected. Notice how Black's Rf8, Kf7 are hopelessly passive and none of the pieces strangely posted on the f-file are working in harmony towards a common goal. } (15... Bc4 16. Bf4 Qb6 17. Re1 Qxb2 18. Qd4 Rac8) 16. Bf4 { Attacks Black's queen with tempo and lands White's dsb on an even more active post. } 16... Qc8 { Black's rooks are no longer communicating and their movement is hampered by their Queen wich probably would have been better off at c6. } (16... Qc6?? { not really better ;-) } 17. Bxc6) (16... Qc5 17. Bxb7 Rab8?? 18. Bxb8) (16... Qb6 { maybe } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Rb6b2] }) 17. Re1 { Activates the kingside rook and takes control of the open central e-file. } 17... Bh3 { Proposes to exchange bishops as White wants to activate his queenside rook but can't because of the weak b7 pawn which is the only thing standing between it and White's lsb. } 18. Nd5 { White wants to pick away at Black's defences. } 18... Kh8?! { Inaccuracy. Best move was Nxd5. } { Perhaps I am too tired and missing something I saw during the game but Black doesn't seem to see the coming Nb6 forking his Qc8 and Ra8... The game is quite lost as after the exchanges Black will be at a severe material and positional disadvantage without any form of counterplay mitigating it. } (18... Nxd5 19. Rc1 Qf5 20. Be4 Qd7 21. Qxd5 Rad8 22. Qxb7 Qxb7 23. Bxb7 h6 24. Bxa6 Ng5 25. Re7) 19. Nb6 Qf5 20. Nxa8 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxa8 22. Qb3 Nd5 23. Be5! { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


