1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. d5 c6 5. c4 cxd5 6. cxd5 Be7 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O { This study is from one of the first correspondence games I played, a few months ago, in the spring of 2019. White (Pix) has just castled and Stockfish (depth20) gives it +0.78. A few inaccuracies will follow, but nothing major until White's 21.Nb5 which Stockfish considers a mistake, evaluating play as having gone from +0.73 to -0.90. (P.S.: White went on to win this contest, Black resigning after his 32nd move) } 8... a5 9. Nbc3 Na6 10. f3 Nc5 11. Bb1 Bd7 12. a4 Qb6 13. Be3 Qxb2 14. Bd3 Qb3 15. Qxb3 Nxb3 16. Rab1 Nc5 17. Bxc5 dxc5 18. Rxb7 Rfb8 19. Rfb1 Rxb7 20. Rxb7 Kf8 21. Nb5 { Stockfish (depth 20) considers this a mistake. Can you figure out why without using the engine? More generally, at what level of play do you feel this type of "mistake" can usually be capitalized on by a player of that strength? } *


