[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation, Lipnitsky Attack"]
[StudyName "PixelatedParcel's Study #4: opening knowledge without accurate play in the middlegame"]
[ChapterName "Innacurate play leads to serious trouble"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/nxiNNLM5/qZ4zUlKc"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/PixelatedParcel"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:19:35"]

1. e4 { This study is from a recent correspondence game I played as White against a similarly rated opponent. It illustrates the importance of accurate play between players of equal strength when no obvious tactical opportunity can change the course of the game to the innacurate player's benefit. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. Bg5 O-O 9. a4 h6 10. Bh4 Qc7 11. Qe2 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bg3 e5 14. b3 Bb7 15. Qf3 Qd7 16. Rad1 Qg4 { After 16...Qg4, White has a slight advantage but nothing to write home about. However, Black's situation quickly goes downhill when he plays 3 consecutive inaccuracies (one being a mistake) against White's more accurate play. } 17. Qe3 c5 18. h3 Qd7 19. Bxe5 Ne8 { After 19...Ne8, Stockfish 10 at a depth of 20 gives White +3.8.
Though between intermediate players, this game nevertheless illustrates why play between experts, masters and grandmasters hinges on accuracy, all other things being equal. Below these levels, where the advantage fluctuates more often and in greater amplitude, the search for the "best" move is less relevant. What is required, however, is consistently "good" play. One might say "better" play rather than the systematically sought after "best" play of stronger levels. White went on to win this contest, his 96.2% accuracy far outclassing his opponent's 40.3% accuracy. } *


